{"title_page": "Timeline of LGBT history, 21st century", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{very long|date=August 2015}}\n{{Globalize |date=September 2016 |discuss=Talk:Timeline of LGBT history#Globalize }}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n\nThe following is a '''timeline of lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender''' ('''[[LGBT]]''') history in the 21st century.\n\n==2000s==\n{{World homosexuality laws map|align=right|size=350px}}'''2001'''\n* '''Same-sex marriages laws''':\n** '''Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in the Netherlands|The Netherlands]] (with joint adoption)\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Germany|Germany]] (without adoption until Oct 2004, then with step-adoption only)\n** '''Passed''': [[Registered partnership in Finland|Finland]] (without joint adoption until May 2009, then with step-adoption)\n* '''Limited Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[De facto union in Portugal|Portugal]] (without joint adoption) (replaced with marriage in 2010)\n** '''Came into effect''': Swiss canton of [[Geneva]] (without joint adoption)\n* '''Anti-discrimination legislation''': US states of [[Rhode Island]] (private sector, gender identity) and [[Maryland]] (private sector, sexual orientation)\n* '''Equalization of age of consent''': [[LGBT rights in Albania|Albania]], [[LGBT rights in Estonia|Estonia]], [[LGBT rights in Liechtenstein|Liechtenstein]] and [[LGBT rights in the United Kingdom|United Kingdom]].\n* '''Repeal of Sodomy laws''': US state of [[Arizona]]\n* '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': the rest of the United Kingdom's territories{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}\n* '''Homosexuality no longer an illness''': [[Homosexuality in China|China]]\n* '''Marches and Prides''': Protesters disrupt the first Pride march in the [[LGBT rights in Serbia|Serbian]] capital city of [[Belgrade]]\n* The '''first memorial in the United States honoring LGBT veterans''' was dedicated in [[Desert Memorial Park]], Cathedral City, California.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nlgbtvm.org/Home_Page.html|title=National LGBT Veterans Memorial|work=nlgbtvm|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n* '''Helene Faasen and Anne-Marie Thus''', from the Netherlands, became the first two women to legally marry.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/world/worlds-first-legally-wed-lesbian-couple-celebrates-their-10th-wedding-anniversary/story-e6frfkyi-1226030866529|title=World's first legally wed lesbian couple celebrates their 10th wedding anniversary|work=NewsComAu|accessdate=6 October 2014|date=30 March 2011}}</ref>\n* '''[[Pink Triangle Park]]''' was dedicated; it is the first permanent, free-standing memorial in America dedicated to the thousands of [[Persecution of homosexuals in Nazi Germany and the Holocaust|persecuted homosexuals in Nazi Germany during the Holocaust]] of World War II.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ebar.com/news/article.php|title=Bay Area Reporter :: Article.php|website=The Bay Area Reporter / B.A.R. Inc.}}</ref><ref>Plaque which is part of the monument.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2003/06/27/EB291143.DTL |title=Park honors gay, lesbian Holocaust victims, '&#39;San Francisco Chronicle'&#39; June 27, 2003 |publisher=Sfgate.com |date=2003-06-27 |accessdate=2013-02-12}}</ref>\n\n'''2002'''\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': Canadian province of [[Civil unions in Quebec|Quebec]] (with joint adoption)\n** '''Came into effect''': [[Registered partnership in Finland|Finland]] (without joint adoption until May 2009, then with step-adoption)\n** '''Passed''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Argentina|Argentinian]] city of [[Buenos Aires]] (without joint adoption)\n* '''Limited Partnerships laws''':\n** '''Passed''': Swiss canton of [[Zurich]] (without joint adoption)\n* '''Same-sex couple adoption legalisation''': [[South Africa]] (joint and step adoption) and [[Sweden]] (joint and step adoption)\n* '''Anti-discrimination legislation''': US states of [[Alaska]] (public sector, sexual orientation) and [[New York (state)|New York]] (private sector, sexual orientation)\n** Canada's [[Northwest Territories]] updates human rights legislation to formally include sexual orientation, and is the first jurisdiction in Canada to ban discrimination based on [[Transgender rights in Canada|gender identity]]; they all would by 2017.\n* '''Equalization of age of consent''': [[LGBT rights in Austria|Austria]], [[LGBT rights in Bulgaria|Bulgaria]], [[LGBT rights in Cyprus|Cyprus]], [[LGBT rights in Hungary|Hungary]], [[LGBT rights in Moldova|Moldova]], [[LGBT rights in Romania|Romania]] and the Australian state of [[Western Australia]]\n* '''Repeal of Sodomy laws''': [[Romania]], [[Costa Rica]] and the US States of [[Arkansas]] and [[Massachusetts]]\n* '''Other''': openly gay Dutch politician [[Pim Fortuyn]] is assassinated by [[Volkert van der Graaf]]\n* '''[[Parents and Friends of Lesbians and Gays]]''' established its Transgender Network, also known as TNET, as its first official \"Special Affiliate,\" recognized with the same privileges and responsibilities as its regular chapters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.pflag.org/Page.aspx?pid=398 |title=PFLAG: Parents, Families, & Friends of Lesbians and Gays |publisher=community.pflag.org |date=9 April 2013 |accessdate=19 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120620050818/http://community.pflag.org/Page.aspx?pid=398 |archivedate=20 June 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* At the Reform seminary [[Hebrew Union College-Jewish Institute of Religion]] in New York, the Reform rabbi [[Margaret Wenig]] organized the '''first school-wide seminar at any rabbinical school which addressed the psychological, legal, and religious issues affecting people who are intersex or [[transsexual]].'''<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web|url=http://huc.edu/faculty/faculty/MargaretWenig.shtml |title=Rabbi Margaret Moers Wenig, D.D. |publisher=Hebrew Union College |accessdate=2013-07-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130623080230/http://huc.edu/faculty/faculty/MargaretWenig.shtml |archivedate=23 June 2013 }}</ref>\n'''2003'''\n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Belgium|Belgium]] (without joint adoption until Apr 2006) and the Canadian provinces of [[Same-sex marriage in Ontario|Ontario]] and [[Same-sex marriage in British Columbia|British Columbia]]\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Came into effect''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Argentina|Argentinian]] city of [[Buenos Aires]] (without joint adoption)\n** '''Passed:''': Australian state of [[Domestic partnership in Tasmania|Tasmania]] (step adoption only)\n* '''Limited Partnerships laws''':\n** '''Came into effect''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Austria|Austria]] (without joint adoption)(replaced with registered partnerships 2010) and [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Croatia|Croatia]] (without registration or adoption)\n* '''Anti-discrimination legislation''':[[Bulgaria]] ( all sectors, sexual orientation), [[United Kingdom]] (excluding religious organisations, sexual orientation), US states of [[Arizona]] (public sector, sexual orientation), [[Kentucky]] (public sector, sexual orientation and gender identity), [[Michigan]] (executive branch of the state government, sexual orientation), [[New Mexico]] (private sector, sexual orientation and gender identity) and [[Pennsylvania]] (public sector, gender identity)\n* '''End to ban on gay people in the military''': [[LGBT rights in Russia|Russia]]\n* '''Equalization of age of consent''': Australian state and territory (resp.) of [[LGBT rights in New South Wales|New South Wales]] and [[Northern Territory]]\n* '''Repeal of Sodomy laws''': [[Armenia]]\n* '''Repeal of the concept of [[Buggery]] in law''': [[United Kingdom]]\n* '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Iraq|Iraq]], [[LGBT rights in Armenia|Armenia]] and [[LGBT rights in the United States|United States]] [nationwide]\n* '''Recriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Belize|Belize]]\n* [[Section 28]] was repealed in [[England and Wales]] and [[Northern Ireland]]. \n* [[Gene Robinson]] became the first openly gay Bishop in the Episcopal church in the USA.\n*  '''[[Reuben Zellman]]''' became the first openly transgender person accepted to the [[Hebrew Union College-Jewish Institute of Religion]], where he was ordained in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forward.com/articles/14854/transgender-jews-now-out-of-closet-seeking-commun-/#ixzz25FOl5U4v |title=Transgender Jews Now Out of Closet, Seeking Communal Recognition \u2013 |publisher=Forward.com |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref><ref>[http://www.jewishmosaic.org/page/load_page/50] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070506220137/http://www.jewishmosaic.org/page/load_page/50|date=6 May 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bethelberkeley.org/aboutus/rabbi-zellman |title=Rabbi Zellman |publisher=bethelberkeley.org |accessdate=2013-10-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007023144/http://www.bethelberkeley.org/aboutus/rabbi-zellman |archive-date=7 October 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* In 2003, the '''[[Committee on Jewish Law and Standards]]''' approved a rabbinic ruling that concluded that [[sex reassignment surgery]] (SRS) is permissible as a treatment of [[gender dysphoria]], and that a transgender person's sex status under Jewish law is changed by SRS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishmosaic.org/page/file/17 |title=Status of Transsexuals |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721041507/http://www.jewishmosaic.org/page/file/17 |archivedate=21 July 2011 }}</ref>\n* '''Legal recognition of indeterminate gender''': [[Alex MacFarlane]] became the first person reported to obtain a birth certificate and passport, in [[Australia]], showing indeterminate gender.\n* In 2003 the Reform rabbi [[Margaret Wenig]] organized the '''first school-wide seminar at the [[Reconstructionist Rabbinical College]] which addressed the psychological, legal, and religious issues affecting people who are intersex or [[transsexual]].'''<ref name=\"autogenerated2\" />\n* [[Jennifer Finney Boylan]]'s autobiography, ''She's Not There: A Life in Two Genders'', was '''the first book by an openly [[transgender]] American to become a bestseller.'''<ref name=\"GLAAD bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.glaad.org/about/board/jenniferboylan |title=Professor Jennifer Finney Boylan (Maine) (May 2011 \u2013 Present) |publisher=GLAAD |accessdate=2012-12-26}}</ref>\n* '''''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]''''' showed girlfriends Willow Rosenberg and Tara Maclay in bed together, which though not a sex scene was considered the first scene of its kind for a broadcast network series.<ref name=\"nytimes1\">{{cite news|first=Maya |last=Salam |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/29/arts/television/lesbian-tv-shows.html |title=The Very (Very) Slow Rise of Lesbianism on TV - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date= |accessdate=2019-12-09}}</ref> \n* '''The first lesbian sex scene in broadcast TV history''' occurred, on ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Frost |first=Karen |url=https://www.afterellen.com/tv/474467-long-road-lesbian-sex-sensuality-network-tv#UjXTCyxhuYzGUkMG.99 |title=The Long Road to Lesbian Sex & Sensuality on Network TV |publisher=AfterEllen |date=2017-08-19 |accessdate=2019-06-03}}</ref>\n* '''[[Patrick Harvie]]''' became the first openly bisexual [[Member of the Scottish Parliament]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/17665293.30-years-of-stonewall-the-fight-for-lgbt-rights/ |title=30 years of Stonewall: The fight for LGBT rights |publisher=HeraldScotland |date= |accessdate=2019-06-04}}</ref>\n'''2004'''\n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': Canadian provinces of [[Same-sex marriage in Manitoba|Manitoba]] (with adoption), [[Same-sex marriage in Newfoundland and Labrador|Newfoundland and Labrador]], [[Same-sex marriage in Nova Scotia|Nova Scotia]], [[Same-sex marriage in Quebec|Quebec]] (with adoption), and [[Same-sex marriage in Saskatchewan|Saskatchewan]], and the Canadian territory of [[Same-sex marriage in Yukon|Yukon]], US State of [[Same-sex marriage in Massachusetts|Massachusetts]]\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': Brazilian State of [[Rio Grande do Sul]], [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Luxembourg|Luxembourg]] (without joint adoption) and US state of [[Domestic partnership in Maine|Maine]]\n** '''Came into effect:''': Australian state of [[Tasmania]] (step adoption only)\n** '''Passed''': [[civil unions in New Zealand|New Zealand]] (without joint adoption)\n* '''Limited Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in New Jersey|New Jersey]]\n* '''Same-sex couple adoption legalisation''': [[Germany]] (Step Adoption)\n* '''Banning of Same-sex marriage''': [[Australia]], US states of [[Mississippi]], [[Missouri]], [[Montana]], [[Oregon]] and [[Utah]]\n* '''Banning of Same-sex marriage and civil unions''': US states of [[Arkansas]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[Kentucky]], [[Louisiana]], [[Michigan]], [[North Dakota]], [[Ohio]], [[Oklahoma]], [[Virginia]] and [[Wisconsin]]\n* '''Anti-discrimination legislation''': [[Portugal]], US States of [[Indiana]] (public sector, gender identity), [[Louisiana]] (public sector, sexual orientation) and [[Maine]]\n* '''Equalization of age of consent''': [[Lithuania]]\n* '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Cape Verde|Cape Verde]], [[LGBT rights in the Marshall Islands|Marshall Islands]] and [[LGBT rights in San Marino|San Marino]]\n* ''[[The L Word]]'' featured '''television\u2019s first ensemble cast of lesbian characters.'''<ref name=\"nytimes1\"/>\n* The first all-transgender performance of the '''[[Vagina Monologues]]''' was held. The monologues were read by eighteen notable transgender women, and a new monologue revolving around the experiences and struggles of transgender women was included.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baltimoregaylife.com/item/451-vagina-monologues |title=\u2018V\u2019 is for Victory, Valentine and Vagina |publisher=Baltimore Gay Life |date=2 February 2012 |accessdate=15 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120806183929/http://www.baltimoregaylife.com/item/451-vagina-monologues |archivedate=6 August 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* '''[[Del Martin and Phyllis Lyon]]''' became the first same-sex couple to be legally married in the United States,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2004/02/12/GAYMARRIAGE.TMP |work=The San Francisco Chronicle |title=Lesbian couple wedded at SF City Hall Women had been together for five decades |date=13 February 2004 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080521071039/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=%2Fc%2Fa%2F2004%2F02%2F12%2FGAYMARRIAGE.TMP |archivedate=21 May 2008 |df=dmy }}</ref> when San Francisco mayor Gavin Newsom allowed city hall to grant marriage licenses to same-sex couples.<ref>[http://www.newsweek.com/2009/01/16/hoping-that-left-is-right.html SF Mayor Gavin Newsom Risks Career on Gay Marriage]. Newsweek (17 January 2009). Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> However, all same-sex marriages done in 2004 in California were annulled.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/US/12/19/california.proposition/index.html|work=CNN|title=Prop 8 proponents seek to nullify same-sex marriages|date=19 December 2008}}</ref> After the California Supreme Court decision in 2008 that granted same-sex couples in California the right to marry, Del Martin and Phyllis Lyon remarried, and were again the first same-sex couple in the state to marry.<ref>{{cite web |title=First couple in California's 2004 marriages will say vows again on Monday |url=http://www.gaypeopleschronicle.com/stories08/june/0613082.htm |accessdate=2 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/16/us/16cnd-weddings.html?hp|title=Gay Marriages Begin in California|first=Jesse|last=McKinley|date=16 June 2008|work=The New York Times}}</ref> Later in 2008 Prop 8 banned same-sex marriage in California,<ref>[http://www.tuftsdaily.com/editorial-maine-was-asking-the-wrong-people-1.2058087#3 Editorial | Maine was asking the wrong people] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609211433/http://www.tuftsdaily.com/editorial-maine-was-asking-the-wrong-people-1.2058087 |date= 9 June 2011 }}. Tuftsdaily.com (9 November 2009). Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> but the marriages that occurred between the California Supreme Court decision legalizing same-sex marriage and the approval of Prop 8 are still considered valid, including the marriage of Del Martin and Phyllis Lyon.<ref>[http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Justice/2009/0527/p02s01-usju.html California's top court upholds Prop. 8 ban on same-sex marriage]. CSMonitor.com (27 May 2009). Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> However, Del Martin died in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2008-08-28/news/17122864_1_same-sex-marriage-marriage-licenses-phyllis-lyon |work=The San Francisco Chronicle |first=Rachel |last=Gordon |title=Same-sex Marriage Timeline |date=28 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111054704/http://articles.sfgate.com/2008-08-28/news/17122864_1_same-sex-marriage-marriage-licenses-phyllis-lyon |archivedate=11 January 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* '''[[James McGreevey]]''', then governor of New Jersey, came out as gay, thus becoming the first openly gay state governor in United States history.<ref name=\"aeispeakers.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aeispeakers.com/print.php?SpeakerID=1249 |title=James McGreevey - AEI Speakers Bureau |publisher=Aeispeakers.com |accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref> He resigned soon after.<ref name=\"aeispeakers.com\" />\n* '''Bisi Alimi''' became the first Nigerian to declare his homosexuality on television.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://amanpour.blogs.cnn.com/2014/01/16/meet-the-first-gay-nigerian-to-come-out-on-tv/ | work=CNN | title=Meet the first gay Nigerian to come out on TV | date=16 January 2014}}</ref>\n* '''Luna''', by [[Julie Anne Peters]], was published, and was the first young-adult novel with a transgender character to be released by a mainstream publisher.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://mobile.nytimes.com/2015/06/07/business/media/transgender-childrens-books-fill-a-void-and-break-a-taboo.html?referrer=&_r=0 | work=The New York Times | first=Alexandra | last=Alter | date=7 June 2015 | title=Transgender Children's Books Fill a Void and Break a Taboo}}</ref>\n* The first Trans pride march was held in San Francisco in 2004.<ref name=\"transmarch-2012\">{{cite web|url=http://www.transmarch.org/about |title=About the San Francisco Trans March &#124; San Francisco Trans March |publisher=Transmarch.org |date=2004-06-25 |accessdate=2012-11-06}}</ref>\n* '''[[Karamo Brown]]''' started his career in television on the [[MTV]] reality series ''[[The Real World: Philadelphia]]'' in 2004, becoming the first out gay black man on reality TV.<ref name=Plus>{{Cite news|author=Anderson-Minshall, Jacob|url=https://www.hivplusmag.com/entertainment/2017/7/24/futures-so-bright-hes-got-unshade|title=How Did Karamo Brown find his way back to Hollywood?|date=July 24, 2017|access-date=September 4, 2018|language=en|publisher=Plus}}</ref>\n'''2005'''\n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Canada|Canada]] [nationwide], [[Same-sex marriage in Spain|Spain]] (with joint adoption)\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passes and Came into effect''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Andorra|Andorra]], [[United Kingdom]] (without joint adoption (England and Wales) until December 2005,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ukgaynews.org.uk/Archive/2005dec/3001.html |title=New Adoption Law Gives Gay Couples Joint Rights |work=UK Gay News |date=30 December 2005 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120919092646/http://www.ukgaynews.org.uk/Archive/2005dec/3001.htm |archivedate=19 September 2012 |url-status=dead |accessdate=4 September 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> without joint adoption (Scotland) until Sep 2009, without joint adoption (Northern Ireland)) and US state of [[Same-sex marriage in Connecticut|Connecticut]]\n** '''Came into effect''': [[civil unions in New Zealand|New Zealand]] (without joint adoption) and US state of [[Domestic partnership in California|California]]\n** '''Passed''': [[Registered partnership in Switzerland|Switzerland]] (without adoption) and [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Slovenia|Slovenia]]\n* '''Same-sex couple adoption legalisation''': UK Subdivisions of [[England]] and [[Wales]]\n* '''Banning of Same-sex marriage''': [[Same-sex marriage in Latvia|Latvia]], [[Uganda]] and [[Honduras]]\n* '''Banning of Same-sex marriage and civil unions''': US states of [[Kansas]] and [[Texas]]\n* '''Anti-discrimination legislation''': US States of [[Illinois]] (private sector, sexual orientation and gender identity) and [[Maine]] (private sector, sexual orientation and gender identity){{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}\n* '''Repeal of Sodomy laws''': [[LGBT rights in Puerto Rico|Puerto Rico]]\n* Two gay male teenagers, [[Mahmoud Asgari and Ayaz Marhoni]], are executed in [[Iran]], \n* [[Andr\u00e9 Boisclair]] is chosen leader of the [[Parti Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois]], becoming the first openly gay man elected as the leader of a major political party in North America. \n* [[Pine City, Minnesota]] holds [[East-Central Minnesota Pride]], the first rural LGBT pride in North America.\n* The [[Roman Catholic Church]] issues an instruction prohibiting any individuals who \"present deep-seated homosexual tendencies or support the so-called 'gay culture'\" from joining the priesthood.<ref name=\"seminarydoc\">''[https://www.vatican.va/roman_curia/congregations/ccatheduc/documents/rc_con_ccatheduc_doc_20051104_istruzione_en.html Instruction Concerning the Criteria for the Discernment of Vocations with regard to Persons with Homosexual Tendencies in view of their Admission to the Seminary and to Holy Orders] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080225072042/https://www.vatican.va/roman_curia/congregations/ccatheduc/documents/rc_con_ccatheduc_doc_20051104_istruzione_en.html |date=25 February 2008 }}'', (Vatican Website, 4 November 2005)</ref>\n* '''The Simpsons''' became the first cartoon series to dedicate an entire episode to the topic of same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://news.avclub.com/new-study-suggests-the-simpsons-likes-its-homosexuals-f-1798239020  | work=The AV Club | first=Sean | last=O'Neal | title=New study suggests The Simpsons likes its homosexuals flaming, effecting social change| date=2 July 2013}}</ref>\n* The '''first European Transgender Council Meeting''' was held in Vienna.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tgeu.net/|title=TransGender Europe - TGEU.net|publisher=|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n* '''Publication of the [[Intersex#San Francisco Human Rights Investigation|first human rights report on the situation]] of intersex people,''' by the Human Rights Commission of the City and County of San Francisco.\n* Eli Cohen became '''the first openly gay man to be ordained a rabbi by the Jewish Renewal Movement.'''<ref>{{cite web|last=Scupham |first=Tony |url=http://queerstoryfiles.blogspot.com/2016/04/a-feast-of-firsts-for-passover.html |title=The Queerstory Files: A Feast of Firsts for Passover |publisher=Queerstoryfiles.blogspot.com |date=2016-04-26 |accessdate=2017-06-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://alephstudents.homestead.com/elicohen.html |title=ALEPH Rabbinic Program SENIORS |publisher=Alephstudents.homestead.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-29}}</ref>\n* [[Andrew Goldstein]] was '''the first American male team-sport professional athlete to be openly gay during his playing career.'''<ref name=mll>{{cite news|last1=Zeigler|first1=Cyd|title=Andrew Goldstein Openly Tending Goal For Major League Lacrosse|url=https://www.outsports.com/2013/2/21/4015350/andrew-goldstein-openly-tending-goal-for-major-league-lacrosse|accessdate=2 December 2017|work=Outsports|date=18 June 2006}}</ref> He came out publicly in 2003 and was drafted by his hometown team, the [[Boston Cannons]] of [[Major League Lacrosse]], in 2005. Goldstein played [[goaltender (lacrosse)|goaltender]] for the [[Long Island Lizards]] from 2005 to 2007, appearing in two games in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|title=Andrew Goldstein - MLL|url=http://pointstreak.com/prostats/playerpage.html?playerid=797170&seasonid=1617|website=Pointstreak.com|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref>\n'''2006'''\n[[File:Kim Coco Iwamoto.jpg|upright|thumb|In 2006 [[Kim Coco Iwamoto]] became the first transgender official to win statewide office in Hawaii.]] \n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in South Africa|South Africa]] (with joint adoption)\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Registered partnership in the Czech Republic|Czech Republic]] (without joint adoption)\n** '''Came into effect''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Slovenia|Slovenia]]\n** '''Passed''': Mexican City of [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Mexico|Mexico City]] and US state of [[Recognition of same-sex unions in New Jersey|New Jersey]]\n* '''Limited Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed''': Australian State of [[LGBT rights in South Australia|South Australia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-3200.html|title=South Australia gays get new rights|work=PinkNews.co.uk|accessdate=6 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mCZgviO5?url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-3200.html|archivedate=22 December 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* '''Abroad Union recognition''': [[Same-sex marriage in Israel|Israel]]\n* '''Banning of Same-sex marriage''': US State of [[Tennessee]]\n* '''Banning of Same-sex marriage and civil unions''': US States of [[Alabama]], [[Colorado]], [[Idaho]], [[South Carolina]], [[South Dakota]] and [[Virginia]], [[Wisconsin]]\n* '''Same-sex couple adoption legalisation''': [[Same-sex marriage in Belgium|Belgium]]\n* '''Anti-discrimination legislation''': [[LGBT rights in the Faroe Islands|Faroe Islands]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://365gay.com/Newscon06/12/121506islands.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071015122058/http://365gay.com/Newscon06/12/121506islands.htm|archivedate=2007-10-15|title=Island Chain Votes To Ban Discrimination Against Gays|publisher=|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref> [[LGBT rights in Germany|Germany]] (sexual orientation and gender identity), [[LGBT rights in New Zealand|New Zealand]] (gender identity){{Citation needed|date=May 2010}} and US States and Districts of [[Illinois]] (sexual orientation), [[New Jersey]] (private sector, gender identity), [[Washington (state)|Washington]] (sexual orientation and gender identity) and [[Washington, D.C.]] (private sector, gender identity)\n* '''Voiding of Anti-discrimination legislation''': [[Kentucky]]\n* '''Equalization of age of consent''': [[LGBT rights in Hong Kong|Hong Kong]], [[LGBT rights in the Isle of Man|Isle of Man]],<ref>[http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-2222.html Gay sex at 16 legal, Man] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100328114423/http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-2222.html |date=28 March 2010 }} Pink News, 14 August 2006</ref> [[LGBT rights in Serbia|Serbia]]\n* '''Marches and Prides''': the first homosexual pride march in [[Moscow]] ends with violence, the first regional [[Zagreb Pride#First Eastern European Pride|Eastern European Pride]] is held in [[Zagreb]], Croatia\n* Springfield, [[Missouri]] repeals gay soliciting laws.<ref>[http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-13978.html/ Missouri city set to remove anti-gay law] Pink News, 8 September 2009</ref> \n* [[United States Senate]] fails to pass the [[Federal Marriage Amendment]]. \n* The [[2006 World Outgames#International Conference on LGBT Human Rights|International Conference on LGBT Human Rights]] is held in [[Montreal]].\n* The original [[Yogyakarta Principles]] is adopted in [[Yogyakarta]] of Indonesia.\n* Section 28 \"successfully repealed\" in Isle of Man<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stonewall.org.uk/help-advice/whats-my-area|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061105163534/http://www.stonewall.org.uk/information_bank/history__lesbian__gay/89.asp|url-status=dead|title=What's In My Area?|date=6 May 2015|archivedate=5 November 2006|website=Stonewall}}</ref> \n* '''[[Chaya Gusfield]]''' and '''[[Rabbi Lori Klein]]''', both ordained in America, became the first openly lesbian rabbis ordained by the Jewish Renewal movement. Conservative Judaism decided to allow openly lesbian rabbis and cantors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewcy.com/religion-and-beliefs/conservative_judaism_puts_its_money_where_its_mouth_is |title=Conservative Judaism Walks the Walk |publisher=Jewcy.com |accessdate=2014-05-18}}</ref> '''[[Elliot Kukla]]''', who came out as transgender six months before his ordination in 2006, was the first openly transgender person to be ordained by the Hebrew Union College-Jewish Institute of Religion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forward.com/articles/14854/transgender-jews-now-out-of-closet-seeking-commun-/ |title=Transgender Jews Now Out of Closet, Seeking Communal Recognition \u2013 |publisher=Forward.com |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n* '''State Rep. Patricia Todd''', D-Birmingham, became Alabama's first openly gay public official when she was elected in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.al.com/breaking/2013/06/patricia_todd_alabamas_first_o.html |title=Patricia Todd, Alabama's first openly gay state legislator, coming to Huntsville to talk Supreme Court gay marriage rulings &#124; al.com |publisher=Blog.al.com |date=2013-06-28 |accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref>\n* '''[[Kim Coco Iwamoto]]''' became the first transgender official to win statewide office in Hawaii.\n* '''[[Bern\u00e1rd J. Lynch|Bernard Lynch]]''' became the first Catholic priest in the world to undertake a civil partnership in 2006 in the Republic of Ireland (he had previously had his relationship blessed in a ceremony in 1998 by an American Cistercian monk<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/father-bernard-lynch-the-vatican-has-told-them-to-get-rid-of-me-7619004.html|title=Father Bernard Lynch: 'The Vatican has told them to get rid of me'|date=8 April 2012|publisher=|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>). He was subsequently expelled from his religious order in 2011, and went on to legally wed his husband in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/social-affairs/religion-and-beliefs/married-gay-priest-says-catholic-church-has-got-god-s-message-very-wrong-1.2958118|title=Married gay priest says Catholic Church has got God's message 'very wrong'|publisher=|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n'''2007'''\n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Recognition''': [[Same-sex marriage in Aruba, Cura\u00e7ao and Sint Maarten|Aruba, Cura\u00e7ao and Sint Maarten]] (Recognition of Dutch same-sex marriages only)\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': Mexican state of [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Mexico|Coahuila]]\n** '''Came into effect''': Mexican City of [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Mexico|Mexico City]], [[Registered partnership in Switzerland|Switzerland]] (without adoption) and US state of [[Recognition of same-sex unions in New Jersey|New Jersey]]\n** '''Passed''': [[Hungary]] (with adoption), US state of [[Same-sex marriage in New Hampshire|New Hampshire]] and [[Same-sex marriage in Uruguay|Uruguay]] (without adoption until Sep 2008)\n* '''Limited Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': US state of [[Domestic partnership in Washington|Washington]] and [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Colombia|Colombia]]\n** '''Came into effect''': Australian state of [[LGBT rights in South Australia|South Australia]] and US state of [[Domestic partnership in Oregon|Oregon]]\n* '''Anti-discrimination legislation''': [[Equality Act (Sexual Orientation) Regulations|United Kingdom]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts2006/20060003.htm |title=Equality Act 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071119183746/http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts2006/20060003.htm |archivedate=19 November 2007 }}</ref> (sexual orientation) and US states of [[LGBT rights in the United States|Colorado]] (private sector, sexual orientation and gender identity), [[LGBT rights in the United States|Iowa]] (private sector, sexual orientation and gender identity), [[LGBT rights in the United States|Kansas]] (public sector, sexual orientation and gender identity), [[LGBT rights in the United States|Michigan]] (public sector, gender identity), [[LGBT rights in Ohio|Ohio]] (public sector, sexual orientation and gender identity), [[LGBT rights in the United States|Oregon]] (private sector, sexual orientation and gender identity) and [[LGBT rights in the United States|Vermont]] (private sector, gender identity)\n* '''Equalization of age of consent''': [[LGBT rights in Portugal|Portugal]], [[LGBT rights in South Africa|South Africa]], UK territory of [[Jersey]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/jersey/5151592.stm|title=BBC: State votes for consent age drop|publisher=|accessdate=6 October 2014|work=BBC News|date=5 July 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jerseylaw.je/Law/Display.aspx?url=LawsInForce/htm/lawfiles/2007/L-02-2007.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722071226/http://www.jerseylaw.je/Law/Display.aspx?url=LawsInForce%2Fhtm%2Flawfiles%2F2007%2FL-02-2007.htm|url-status=dead|title=Sexual Offences (Jersey) Law 2007|archivedate=22 July 2011}}</ref> [[LGBT rights in Vanuatu|Vanuatu]]\n* '''Decriminalization of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Nepal|Nepal]] and New Zealand territories of [[LGBT rights in Niue|Niue]] and [[LGBT rights in Tokelau|Tokelau]]\n* '''Marches and Prides''': the first ever gay pride parade in a [[Muslim]] country is held in [[Istanbul]], Turkey;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IGUC0zEMEcU|title=''See video''|work=YouTube|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Logo (TV channel)|Logo cable channel]] hosts the first presidential forum in the United States focusing specifically on LGBT issues. Six [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] candidates participate in the event. GOP candidates were asked to attend but turned it down.\n* '''[[Candis Cayne]]''' played Carmelita Rainer, a transgender woman having an affair with married New York Attorney General Patrick Darling (played by [[William Baldwin]]), on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] prime time drama ''[[Dirty Sexy Money]]''.<ref name=\"October Surprises\">{{cite web |last=Brownworth | first=Victoria A. | title=October Surprises | work=[[Bay Area Reporter]]| date=18 October 2007 | url =http://ebar.com/arts/art_article.php?sec=lavendertube&article=49 | accessdate=20 October 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Advocate 2009-03\">{{cite news|title=I Advocate ...|date=March 2009|work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|issue=1024|page=8}}</ref><ref name=\"Metro UK 2008-03-13\">{{cite web|publisher=Metro.co.uk|date=13 March 2008|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/fame/article.html?in_article_id=117834&in_page_id=7&expand=true |title=Transsexual beauty makes TV history|accessdate=20 February 2009}}</ref> The role made Cayne the first openly transgender actress to play a recurring transgender character in prime time.<ref name=\"October Surprises\" /><ref name=\"Advocate 2009-03\" /><ref name=\"Metro UK 2008-03-13\" />\n* On 29 November, the first foreign gay wedding was held in [[Hanoi]], '''[[Vietnam]]''' between a Japanese and an Irish national. The wedding raised much attention in the gay and lesbian community in Vietnam.<ref name=\"vietbao.vn\">{{cite web |url=http://vietbao.vn/The-gioi-giai-tri/Le-ket-hon-dong-gioi-tai-Ha-Noi/50795684/407/ |title=L\u1ec5 k\u1ebft h\u00f4n \u0111\u1ed3ng gi\u1edbi t\u1ea1i H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i |publisher=Vietbao.vn |accessdate=4 August 2009 |language=vi |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080219070103/http://vietbao.vn/The-gioi-giai-tri/Le-ket-hon-dong-gioi-tai-Ha-Noi/50795684/407/ |archive-date=19 February 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* '''[[Jalda Rebling]]''', a German woman born in the Netherlands, became the first openly lesbian cantor ordained by the Jewish Renewal movement.<ref name=\"jta\">{{cite news |last=Axelrod |first=Toby |url=http://www.jta.org/news/article/1999/11/30/14879/Newfemalecantorin |title=New Renewal cantor looks ahead |publisher=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]] |date=1999-11-30 |accessdate=2012-04-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130415065937/http://www.jta.org/news/article/1999/11/30/14879/Newfemalecantorin |archivedate=15 April 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* Rabbi '''[[Toba Spitzer]]''' became the first openly lesbian or gay person to head a [[rabbi|rabbinical assembly]] when she was elected president of the Reconstructionist Rabbinical Assembly at the group's annual convention, held in [[Scottsdale, Arizona]].<ref name=\"radin\">{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/news/globe/city_region/breaking_news/2007/03/first_openly_ga.html |title=First openly gay rabbi elected leader |first=Charles A. |last=Radin |newspaper=The Boston Globe\n|date=13 March 2007}}</ref>\n* '''[[Joy Ladin]]''' became the first openly transgender professor at an Orthodox institution (Stern College for Women of [[Yeshiva University]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Through-Door-Life-Journey-Autobiog/dp/0299287300/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1346529351&sr=1-1&keywords=through+the+door+of+life+a+jewish+journey+between+genders |title=Through the Door of Life: A Jewish Journey between Genders (Living Out: Gay and Lesbian Autobiog): Joy Ladin: 9780299287306: Amazon.com: Books |publisher=Amazon.com |date=2012-03-15 |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sjjcc.org/arts/performance-guest-speakers/ |title=Performance & Guest Speakers |publisher=Sjjcc.org |accessdate=2013-10-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314060544/http://www.sjjcc.org/arts/performance-guest-speakers/ |archivedate=14 March 2013 }}</ref>\n* '''Amaranta G\u00f3mez Regalado''' (for [[M\u00e9xico Posible]]) became the first transsexual person to appear in the Mexican Congress.\n* '''[[Ellen DeGeneres]]''' became the first open lesbian to host the Academy Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://famousdaily.com/history/ellen-degeneres-hosts-academy-awards.html |title=Ellen DeGeneres hosts the 79th Academy Awards as the first openly gay woman |publisher=Famousdaily.com |date=2012-02-25 |accessdate=2012-11-06}}</ref> \n* Ventura Place in [[Studio City]] was renamed Dr. '''[[Betty Berzon]]''' Place in her honor, making it the first street ever officially dedicated to a known lesbian in California.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wehonews.com/z/wehonews/betty-berzon-place-unveiled/ |title=WeHo News - News |accessdate=14 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141222040635/http://www.wehonews.com/z/wehonews/betty-berzon-place-unveiled/ |archivedate=22 December 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Theresa Sparks]] was elected president of the [[San Francisco Police Commission]] by a single vote, making her the first openly transgender person ever to be elected president of any San Francisco commission, as well as San Francisco's highest ranking openly transgender official.<ref name=\"Renne quits\">Selna, Robert; Sward, Susan; Vega, Cecilia M. [http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2007/05/11/BAG3TPP7881.DTL Renne Quits Police Commission], San Francisco Chronicle (11 May 2007), pp. B-9. Retrieved on 13 May 2007.</ref><ref>[http://www.kcbs.com/pages/440257.php?contentType=4&contentId=486609 SF Police Commission Makes History], [[KCBS (AM)|KCBS]] (10 May 2007). Retrieved on 13 May 2007.  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070529044945/http://www.kcbs.com/pages/440257.php?contentType=4&contentId=486609 |date=29 May 2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"Sparks Is First Trans\">McMillan, Dennis. [http://www.sfbaytimes.com/index.php?sec=article&article_id=6411 Sparks Is First Trans Person to Lead Major Commission] [[San Francisco Bay Times]] (17 May 2007). Retrieved on 15 October 2007.</ref>\n'''2008'''\n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': US states of [[Same-sex marriage in California|California]] (May\u2013Nov 2008), [[Same-sex marriage in Connecticut|Connecticut]] and [[Same-sex marriage under United States tribal jurisdictions#Mashantucket Pequot|Mashantucket Pequot]]\n** '''Passed''': [[Same-sex marriage in Norway|Norway]] (with joint adoption)\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': The Australian [[Recognition of same-sex unions in the Australian Capital Territory|Capital Territory]], [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Ecuador|Ecuador]] (without joint adoption), US state of [[Domestic partnership in Washington|Washington]] (expansion of previous legislation)\n** '''Came into effect''': US state of [[Same-sex marriage in New Hampshire|New Hampshire]] and [[Same-sex marriage in Uruguay|Uruguay]] (without joint adoption until Sep 2008)\n* '''Limited Partnership laws''':\n** '''Came into effect''': Australian state of [[LGBT rights in Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] and US state of [[Domestic partnership in Oregon|Oregon]]\n* '''Banning of Same-sex marriage''': US states of [[Same-sex marriage legislation in the United States|Arizona]] and [[Same-sex marriage in California|California]]\n* '''Banning of Same-sex marriage and civil unions''': US state of [[Same-sex marriage legislation in the United States|Florida]]\n* '''Same-sex couple adoption legalisation''': [[Same-sex marriage in Uruguay|Uruguay]]\n* '''Banning of Same-sex adoption''': [[Arkansas Proposed Initiative Act No. 1|Arkansas]] (struck down by the Arkansas Supreme Court in 2011)\n* '''Anti-discrimination legislation''': California{{Citation needed|date=May 2010}}\n* '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Nicaragua|Nicaragua]] and [[LGBT rights in Panama|Panama]]\n* '''Marches and Prides''': the first ever gay pride parade in [[Bulgaria]]\n* '''[[Matthew Mitcham]]''' became the first openly gay athlete to win an Olympic gold medal.<ref name=\"masi\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-09-28/macklemore-singing-at-gf-like-seeping-sewage-into-debutante-ball/8998442 |title=Macklemore singing at NRL grand final like 'seeping sewage into debutante ball', says Bob Katter |author=Julia Holman |accessdate=28 September 2017 |date=28 September 2017 |work=ABC News |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=3 min read |url=https://gaynation.co/retired-australian-gold-medal-diver-matthew-mitcham-is-engaged/ |title=Retired Australian Gold Medal Diver Matthew Mitcham Is Engaged &#124; Gay Nation |publisher=Gaynation.co |date= |accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref> \n* Kosovo declares itself to be an independent country with a new constitution that includes mention of \"sexual orientation\", the first of its kind in Eastern Europe{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}} \n* The first two same-sex civil marriages (two men and two women) take place in Greece on the island of [[Tilos]]; the supreme court prosecutor and the minister of Justice claim the marriages are null and void.\n* Portland voters elect openly gay [[Sam Adams (Oregon politician)]] mayor\n* '''[[Annise Parker]]''' was elected as the first openly gay or lesbian mayor of Houston, Texas.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2009-12-14/news/17942843_1_openly-gay-mayor-gay-rights-activists-annise-parker|title=Texas-sized first: Newly-elected Annise Parker hailed for being first openly gay mayor of Houston|date=14 December 2009|work=Daily News|location=New York}}</ref>\n* '''[[Kate Brown]]''' was elected as the [[Oregon Secretary of State]] in the [[2008 Oregon state elections|2008 elections]], becoming America's first openly bisexual statewide officeholder.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.portlandmercury.com/portland/walking-bi/Content?oid=2610445|title=Walking Bi &#124; Queer|last=Ferguson|first=Courtney|newspaper=Portland Mercury|accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n* Silverton, Oregon elected '''[[Stu Rasmussen]]''' as the first openly transgender mayor in America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sturasmussen.com/realityCheck.htm |title=Stu Rasmussen for Mayor - Reality Check |publisher=Sturasmussen.com |accessdate=15 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120420133725/http://www.sturasmussen.com/realityCheck.htm |archivedate=20 April 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-election-diary-the-sex-change-we-can-all-believe-in-1003960.html |title=US election diary: The sex change we can all believe in - Americas - World |newspaper=The Independent |date=9 November 2008 |accessdate=15 May 2012 |location=London}}</ref>\n* '''[[Angie Zapata]]''', a transgender woman, was murdered in [[Greeley, Colorado]]. Allen Andrade was convicted of [[first-degree murder]] and committing a [[bias-motivated crime]], because he killed her after he learned that she was [[transgender]]. This case was the first in the nation to get a conviction for a [[hate crime]] involving a transgender victim.<ref name=\"spellman2009\">{{cite news |first=Jim |last=Spellman |title=Transgender murder, hate crime conviction a first |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2009/CRIME/04/22/transgender.slaying.trial/ |publisher=CNN |date=22 April 2009 |accessdate=}}</ref> Angie Zapata's story and murder were featured on [[Univision]]'s \"[[Aqu\u00ed y Ahora (TV series)|Aqui y Ahora]]\" television show on 1 November 2009.\n* The first ever U.S. Congressional hearing on discrimination against transgender people in the workplace was held, by the House Subcommittee on Health, Employment, Labor, and Pensions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.civilrights.org/lgbt/resources/transgender-hearing.html |title=House Subcommittee Holds First Hearing on Transgender Discrimination - The Leadership Conference on Civil and Human Rights |publisher=Civilrights.org |date=7 February 2008 |accessdate=15 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120720225646/http://www.civilrights.org/lgbt/resources/transgender-hearing.html |archivedate=20 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''[[Rachel Maddow]]''' became the first openly gay or lesbian anchor of a major prime-time news program in the United States when she began hosting ''[[The Rachel Maddow Show (TV series)|The Rachel Maddow Show]]'' on U.S. cable network [[MSNBC]].<ref>[http://www.lesbiatopia.com/2008/09/congrats-to-rachel-maddow-knock-em-dead.html Congrats to Rachel Maddow; Knock 'em Dead Tonight!] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091107213523/http://www.lesbiatopia.com/2008/09/congrats-to-rachel-maddow-knock-em-dead.html |date=7 November 2009 }} Lesbiatopia, 8 September 2008</ref>\n'''2009'''\n[[File:Johanna sigurdardottir official portrait.jpg|upright|thumb|[[J\u00f3hanna Sigur\u00f0ard\u00f3ttir]] became the [[Prime Minister]] of [[Iceland]] in 2009, and thus became the first openly gay [[head of government]] in modern times.]] \n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Sweden|Sweden]]<ref>[http://www.365gay.com/news/sweden-oks-gay-marriage Sweden oks gay marriage] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090403065011/http://www.365gay.com/news/sweden-oks-gay-marriage/ |date=3 April 2009 }} 365GAY, 1 April 2009</ref> (with joint adoption), US states of [[Same-sex marriage in Iowa|Iowa]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.desmoinesregister.com/article/20090403/NEWS/90403010 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120629165642/http://www.desmoinesregister.com/article/20090403/NEWS/90403010 |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 June 2012 |title=Unanimous ruling: Iowa marriage no longer limited to one man, one woman |newspaper=Des Moines Register |accessdate=7 May 2009 |first1=Jeff |last1=Eckhoff |first2=Grant |last2=Schulte |lastauthoramp=yes |date=3 April 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and [[Same-sex marriage in Vermont|Vermont]]<ref>[https://archive.is/20120728180414/http://www.burlingtonfreepress.com/article/20090407/NEWS03/100120038/Vermont-legalizes-gay-marriage Vermont legalizes gay marriage] The Burlington Free Press, 7 April 2009</ref>\n** '''Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Norway|Norway]] (with joint adoption) and the [[Same-sex marriage in the Coquille Indian Tribe|Coquille Indian Tribe]]<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2008-08-23/news/17125334_1_same-sex-marriage-gay-marriage-tribal | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | title=Same-sex marriage opponents' ranks dwindle | date=2008-08-23}}</ref>  In 2009 Kitzen and Jeni Branting married in the Coquille Indian tribe's Coos Bay plankhouse, a 3-year-old meeting hall built in traditional Coquille style with cedar plank walls. They were the first same-sex couple to have their marriage recognized by the tribe, of which Kitzen was a member.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oregonfaithreport.com/2009/05/indian-gay-marriage-law-takes-effect-in-oregon/ |title=Indian gay marriage law takes effect in Oregon |publisher=Oregon Faith Report |date=2009-05-27 |accessdate=2012-11-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pewforum.org/Religion-News/Indian-gay-marriage-law-takes-effect-in-Oregon.aspx |title=Indian gay marriage law takes effect in Oregon |publisher=Pew Forum |date=2009-05-26 |accessdate=2012-11-06}}</ref>\n** '''Passed''':  Mexican City of [[Same-sex marriage in Mexico City|Mexico City]] (with joint adoption), US states and districts of [[Same-sex marriage in New Hampshire|New Hampshire]] (step adoption only), [[Same-sex marriage in Maine|Maine]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.boston.com/news/local/breaking_news/2009/05/gay_marriage_la.html |work=The Boston Globe |title=Gay marriage law signed in Maine, advances in N.H |date=6 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090510085213/http://www.boston.com/news/local/breaking_news/2009/05/gay_marriage_la.html |archivedate=10 May 2009 }}</ref> (never came into effect), [[Same-sex marriage in the District of Columbia|Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=\"Hopkins2009\">{{cite news |title=Catania: Gay Marriage Bill Will Debut Tuesday |last=Hopkins |first=Christopher Dean |date=4 October 2009 |newspaper=The Washington Post |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/dc/2009/10/catania_gay_marriage_bill_will.html}}</ref>\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Hungary|Hungary]] (without joint adoption), [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Colombia|Colombia]]  (expansion of previous rights without joint adoption), US states of [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Nevada|Nevada]] and [[Domestic partnership in Washington|Washington]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apps.leg.wa.gov/billinfo/summary.aspx?bill=5688&year=2009 |title=SB 5688&nbsp;\u2013 2009\u201310&nbsp;\u2013 Expanding the rights and responsibilities of state registered domestic partners. |publisher=Washington State Legislature |accessdate=4 August 2009}}</ref> (expansion of previous rights)\n** '''Passed''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Austria|Austria]] (without joint adoption)\n* '''Limited Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': US states of [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Colorado|Colorado]] and [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Wisconsin|Wisconsin]]\n* '''Same-sex couple adoption legalisation''': [[LGBT rights in Finland|Finland]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-12468.html |title=Finland allows gay couples to adopt partner's children |newspaper=Pink News |date=24 February 2008 |accessdate=18 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5jitOngc7?url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-12468.html |archivedate=12 September 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> (step adoption), UK Subdivision of [[Scotland]]\n* '''Banning of Same-sex marriage''': [[Same-sex marriage in Maine|Maine]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Mainers vote down gay marriage law |first=Susan M. |last=Cover |newspaper=[[Portland Press Herald]] |date=4 November 2009 |url=http://pressherald.mainetoday.com/story.php?id=293976&ac=PHnws |accessdate=4 November 2009 |quote=The measure is repealed in a close vote, 53\u201347 percent |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100206142719/http://pressherald.mainetoday.com/story.php?id=293976&ac=PHnws |archivedate=6 February 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* '''Anti-discrimination legislation''': [[LGBT rights in Serbia|Serbia]] and US state of [[LGBT rights in Delaware|Delaware]] (private sector, sexual orientation), USA [[Matthew Shepard Act]] (hate crimes). Canadian province [[Alberta]] adds \"sexual orientation\" to human rights legislation\u2014the last jurisdiction in Canada to do so''.''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.assembly.ab.ca/net/index.aspx?p=bills_status&selectbill=044|title=Bill 44: Human Rights, Citizenship and Multiculturalism Amendment Act, 2009 (Blackett)|date=26 May 2009|publisher=Legislative Assembly of Alberta|accessdate=4 August 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090508044617/http://www.assembly.ab.ca/net/index.aspx?p=bills_status&selectbill=044|archivedate=8 May 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* '''End to ban on gay people in the military''': [[LGBT rights in Argentina|Argentina]], [[LGBT rights in the Philippines|Philippines]] and [[LGBT rights in Uruguay|Uruguay]]\n* The '''[[International Transgender Day of Visibility]]''' was founded by Michigan-based transgender activist<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thespec.com/opinion-story/4432181-a-time-to-celebrate/|title=A time to celebrate|date=27 March 2014|newspaper=The Hamilton Spectator|accessdate=31 March 2014}}</ref> Rachel Crandall in 2009<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pridesource.com/article.html?article=34351|title=Transgender Day of Visibility plans erupt locally, nationwide|last=Carreras|first=Jessica|publisher=PrideSource|accessdate=3 April 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130327152446/http://www.pridesource.com/article.html?article=34351|archivedate=27 March 2013|df=dmy}}</ref> as a reaction to the lack of [[LGBT]] holidays celebrating transgender people, citing the frustration that the only well-known transgender-centered holiday was the [[Transgender Day of Remembrance]] which mourned the loss of transgender people to hate crimes, but did not acknowledge and celebrate living members of the transgender community.\n* '''Politics:''' \n** Iceland elects the first openly gay [[head of government]] in the world, [[J\u00f3hanna Sigur\u00f0ard\u00f3ttir]]<ref name=\"time\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1875032,00.html|title=Iceland Picks the World's First Openly Gay PM|first=Jonas|last=Moody|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=30 January 2009|accessdate=31 January 2009}}</ref>\n** [[Annise Parker]] is elected mayor of [[Houston]], [[Texas]], which becomes the largest city in the United States with an openly gay mayor.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/chronicle/6767658.html|title=Houston makes its choice; Parker makes history|date=15 December 2009|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|accessdate=18 January 2010}}</ref>\n** '''Diego Sanchez''' became the first openly transgender person to work on [[Capitol Hill]]; he was hired as a legislative assistant for [[Barney Frank]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edgeboston.com/index.php?ch=news&sc=&sc3=&id=84890|title=HRC Applauds Naming of Diego Sanchez to Key Legislative Staff Position for Chairman Barney Frank|last=Lavers|first=Michael K.|date=18 December 2008|publisher=EDGE Boston|accessdate=15 May 2012}}</ref> Sanchez was also the first transgender person on the Democratic National Committee's (DNC) Platform Committee in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/capital-living/24154-i-was-not-a-pretty-girl-and-i-felt-like-i-was-a-man|title='I was not a pretty girl, and I felt like I was a man'|last=Yager|first=Jordy|date=10 March 2009|publisher=TheHill.com|accessdate=15 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edgeboston.com/index.php?ch=news&sc=glbt&sc3=&id=72406|title=First Black Transsexual Delegate Headed to Dems\u2019 Convention|last=Lavers|first=Michael K.|date=31 March 2008|publisher=EDGE Boston|accessdate=15 May 2012}}</ref>\n** '''Barbra \"Babs\" Siperstein''' was nominated and confirmed as an at-large member of the [[Democratic National Committee]], becoming its first openly transgender member.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jerseycityindependent.com/2011/08/17/trailblazing-transgender-rights-advocate-babs-siperstein-tapped-as-hudson-pride-parade-grand-marshal/|title=Trailblazing Transgender Rights Advocate Babs Siperstein Tapped as Hudson Pride Parade Grand Marshal|date=17 August 2011|publisher=The Jersey City Independent|accessdate=15 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110820212146/http://www.jerseycityindependent.com/2011/08/17/trailblazing-transgender-rights-advocate-babs-siperstein-tapped-as-hudson-pride-parade-grand-marshal/|archive-date=20 August 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Uzi Even and his life partner was the first same-sex male couple in Israel whose right of adoption has been legally acknowledged.<ref name=\"edelman\">{{Cite news|last=Edelman|first=Ofra|title=Gay couple wins right to adopt foster son|work=Haaretz|accessdate=11 March 2009|date=11 March 2009|url=http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/1070060.html}}</ref> \n* Welsh rugby star [[Gareth Thomas (rugby)|Gareth Thomas]] becomes the first known top-level professional male athlete in a team sport to come out while still active.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1168953/index.htm |title=Gareth Thomas... The Only Openly Gay Male Athlete |first=Gary |last=Smith |authorlink=Gary Smith (sportswriter) |magazine=Sports Illustrated |date=3 May 2010 |accessdate=17 February 2011}}</ref> \n* '''[[Carol Ann Duffy]]''' was chosen as the first openly lesbian or gay [[Poet Laureate]] of the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Janet |last=Stobart |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2009/may/02/world/fg-britain-poet2 |title=Britain names first woman as poet laureate - Los Angeles Times |publisher=Articles.latimes.com |date=2007-08-03 |accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref>\n* In October 2009, LGBT activist '''Amy Andre'''<ref name=\"Amy Andre Binet\">{{cite web|url=http://binetusa.blogspot.com/2009/10/out-bisexual-amy-andre-to-head-san.html|title=BiNet USA's Blog: Out Bisexual Amy Andre to Head San Francisco Pride|first=Binet|last=Usa|date=6 October 2009}}</ref> was appointed as executive director of the San Francisco Pride Celebration Committee, making her San Francisco Pride's first openly bisexual woman of color executive director.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.oaklandlocal.com/article/sf-pride-40|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130706205444/http://archive.oaklandlocal.com/article/sf-pride-40|url-status=dead|title=SF Pride at 40 - Oakland Local|date=6 July 2013|archivedate=6 July 2013}}</ref><ref>Adrienne Williams, 19 October 2009. [https://archive.is/20120711215215/http://bisocialnetwork.com/amy-andre-sf-pride/ Interview with Amy Andre: New Bisexual Executive Director of SF Pride], ''BiSocial Network''.</ref>\n* Orthodox Israeli rabbi '''[[Ron Yosef]]''' became in 2009 the first Israeli orthodox [[Rabbi]] to come out, which he did when appearing in Uvda (\"Fact\"), [[Israel]]'s leading investigative television program, in an episode regarding [[conversion therapies]] in Israel.<ref>{{cite video|first=Yermi |last=Brenner |date=2009 |title=Gay Rabbi Comes Out of His Orthodox Closet |publisher=VJ Movement |url=http://www.vjmovement.com/truth/537 |accessdate=26 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112130252/http://www.vjmovement.com/truth/537 |archivedate=12 November 2013 }}</ref> Yosef remains in his position as a pulpit Rabbi.<ref name=\"yn\">{{cite news |first=Nissan |last=Strauchler |date=16 February 2010 |url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3849500,00.html |title=Gay with perfect faith |work=[[Ynetnews]] |accessdate=26 November 2014}}</ref>\n* '''Siddur Sha'ar Zahav''', the first complete prayer book to address the lives and needs of LGBTQ as well as straight Jews, was published.\n\n==2010==\n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Passed and came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Portugal|Portugal]] (without joint adoption), [[Same-sex marriage in Iceland|Iceland]] (with joint adoption) and [[Same-sex marriage in Argentina|Argentina]] (with adoption)<ref>{{cite news|title=Argentina legalizes same-sex marriage|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/americas/07/15/argentina.gay.marriage/index.html?eref=edition&fbid=0D-fErZV88m|publisher=CNN | date=16 July 2010}}</ref>\n** '''Came into effect''': Mexican City of [[Same-sex marriage in Mexico City|Mexico City]] (with joint adoption), US state of [[Same-sex marriage in New Hampshire|New Hampshire]] (step adoption only) and [[Same-sex marriage in the District of Columbia|Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=\"Hopkins2009\"/>\n** '''Recognition''': The Mexican Supreme Court rules that marriages contracted in Mexico City are valid throughout the country, although no other jurisdiction is required to perform them. Australian State of [[Tasmania]] recognises same-marriages performed in other jurisdictions.\n** '''Other''': U.S. state of [[California]], United States District Judge [[Vaughn Walker]] strikes down California's [[Proposition 8]] as violative of the United States Constitution's Fourteenth Amendment's Equal Protection and Due Process Clauses.<ref>{{cite news|title=Prop 8 Ruling: Read the Full Text|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/08/04/prop-8-ruling-read-the-fu_n_671050.html | work=Huffington Post | first=Nick|last=Graham|date=4 August 2010}}</ref>\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Came into effect''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Austria|Austria]] (without adoption and IVF access rights)\n** '''Passed''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Ireland|Ireland]] (without adoption rights)\n* '''Limited Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and came into effect''': Australian state of [[LGBT rights in New South Wales|New South Wales]] (without joint adoption until Sep 2010)\n* '''Same-sex couple adoption legislation''': Australian state of [[LGBT rights in New South Wales|New South Wales]] and [[LGBT rights in Denmark|Denmark]]\n* '''End to ban of same-sex couple adoption''': US states of [[Arkansas]] and [[Florida]]\n* '''End to ban of gay people in the military''': [[LGBT rights in Serbia|Serbia]]\n* '''End to ban of trans people in the military''': [[Australia]]\n* '''Decriminalization of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Fiji|Fiji]]<ref>[http://ilga.org/ilga/en/article/mjLN9SM1Oz Great news from Fiji. Homosexuality is finally legal!] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101101130910/http://ilga.org/ilga/en/article/mjLN9SM1Oz |date=1 November 2010 }} ILGA.org, 26 February 2010</ref>\n* '''Marches and Prides''': the first ever legal gay pride parade in [[Russia]], held in [[St. Petersburg]]\n* Guinness World Records recognized transgender man '''[[Thomas Beatie]]''' as the world's \"First Married Man to Give Birth.\"<ref>\"First Married Man to Give Birth\", Guinness World Records 2010 edition, page 110\"</ref>\n* '''[[Amanda Simpson]]''' became the first openly transgender presidential appointee in America when she was appointed as senior technical adviser in the Commerce Department's Bureau of Industry and Security.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/amanda-simpson-transgender-presidential-appointee-begins-work-commerce/story?id=9477161 |title=Amanda Simpson, First Transgender Presidential Appointee, Begins Work at Commerce Department - ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=5 January 2010 |accessdate=15 May 2012}}</ref>\n* '''[[Kye Allums]]''' became the first openly transgender athlete to play in NCAA basketball.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.cnn.com/2010-11-03/us/transgender.basketball.player_1_transgender-athletics-staff-basketball-team?_s=PM:US |title=First transgender athlete to play in NCAA basketball - CNN |publisher=Articles.cnn.com |date=3 November 2010 |accessdate=15 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111013085241/http://articles.cnn.com/2010-11-03/us/transgender.basketball.player_1_transgender-athletics-staff-basketball-team?_s=PM%3AUS |archivedate=13 October 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lgbtqnation.com/2011/10/lgbt-history-month-kye-allums-first-openly-transgender-athlete/ |title=LGBT History Month: Kye Allums, first openly transgender NCAA athlete \u2013 LGBTQ Nation |publisher=Lgbtqnation.com |date=2013-09-22 |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref> He was a transgender man who played on [[George Washington University]]'s women's team.<ref name=\"kaykay\">{{cite news|url=http://www.startribune.com/sports/gophers/106641518.html?elr=KArksLckD8EQDUoaEyqyP4O:DW3ckUiD3aPc:_Yyc:aUvDEhiaE3miUsZ |title=Ex-Centennial star deals with transgender publicity |newspaper=Star Tribune |first=Joseph |last=White |accessdate=5 November 2010 |date=4 November 2010 }}{{dead link|date=March 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/11/02/at-george-washington-univ_n_777637.html |title=Kye Allums, Transgender George Washington University Basketball Player, Takes The Court |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date= 2 November 2010|accessdate=15 May 2012 |first=Danielle |last=Wienerbronner}}</ref>\n* '''[[Phyllis Frye]]''' became the first openly transgender judge appointed in the United States.<ref name=dallas-voice_20101117>{{cite news | first=John | last=Wright | url=http://www.dallasvoice.com/phyllis-frye-texas-1st-transgender-judge-1052664.html | title=Phyllis Frye becomes Texas\u2019 1st trans judge | work=[[Dallas Voice]] | date=17 November 2010 | accessdate=8 July 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Houston Press\" /><ref name=\"Fox 26\">{{cite web|url=http://www.myfoxhouston.com/dpp/news/local/101117-judge-appointment-angers-pastors|title=Judge Appointment Angers Pastors: First transgender judge in Texas|publisher=FOX 26 TV News|last=McDonald|first=Sally|date=17 November 2010|accessdate=8 July 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Houston Press\">{{cite news|url=http://blogs.houstonpress.com/hairballs/2010/11/phyllis_fryejudge_transgender.php|newspaper=Houston Press|title=Phyllis Frye: Annise Parker Appoints Houston's First Transgender Judge (That We Know Of)|last=Connelly|first=Richard|date=18 November 2011|accessdate=8 July 2011}}</ref>\n* '''Mary Albing''' became the first openly lesbian minister ordained by the [[Evangelical Lutheran Church in America]], serving the Lutheran Church of Christ the Redeemer on the south side of Minneapolis.<ref>[http://www.sdgln.com/news/2010/05/24/video-minneapolis-luthern-church-welcomes-denominations-first-lesbian-pastor VIDEO: Minneapolis Lutheran church welcomes denomination's first lesbian pastor | San Diego Gay and Lesbian News]. Sdgln.com. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref>\n* '''[[Chai Feldblum]]''', who was openly lesbian, became the first openly LGBT person to serve on the [[EEOC]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Ring |first=Trudy |url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/2013/05/24/obama-nominates-lesbian-attorney-second-eeoc-term |title=Obama Nominates Lesbian Attorney for Second EEOC Term |publisher=Advocate.com |date=2013-05-24 |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n* '''Donna Ryu''' became the first Asian-American woman, first Korean-American, and first lesbian to be appointed as a judge of the United States District Court, Northern District of California.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apawla.org/donnaryu |title=Honorable Donna Ryu |publisher=APAWLA |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n\n==2011==\n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Passed and came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in New York|New York]] and the [[Same-sex marriage in the Suquamish Tribe|Suquamish Tribe]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Gardner |first=Steven |title=Suquamish Tribe approves same-sex marriage |newspaper=[[Kitsap Sun]] |date=1 August 2011 |url=http://www.kitsapsun.com/news/2011/aug/01/suquamish-tribe-approves-same-sex-marriage/ |accessdate=2 August 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/60dKJvJfP?url=http://www.kitsapsun.com/news/2011/aug/01/suquamish-tribe-approves-same-sex-marriage/ |archivedate=2 August 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Came into effect''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Ireland|Ireland]] (without adoption rights)<ref>{{cite news|title=Civil Partnership Bill signed into law|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2010/0719/breaking29.html|newspaper=The Irish Times | date=7 July 2010}}</ref>\n** '''Passed and came into effect''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in the Isle of Man|Isle of Man]] (with joint adoption), US State of [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Illinois|Illinois]] (with joint adoption rights), [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Rhode Island|Rhode Island]] and [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Liechtenstein|Liechtenstein]]\n** '''Passed''': US State of [[LGBT rights in Delaware|Delaware]] (came into effect 2013) and [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Hawaii|Hawaii]] (came into effect Jan 2012)\n* '''End to ban on openly gay, lesbian, and bisexual people in the military''': [[LGBT rights in the United States|USA]] (see [[Don't Ask, don't tell]])\n* [[Tony Briffa (politician)|Tony Briffa]], believed to be the '''world's first intersex mayor''', elected in the City of Hobsons Bay in the suburbs of Melbourne, Australia, at the end of November.<ref>{{Citation\n| last = Canning\n| first = Paul\n| title = Australia town believed to have elected world's first intersex mayor\n| journal = World News Australia\n| date = 10 December 2011\n| url = http://www.lgbtqnation.com/2011/12/australia-town-believed-to-have-elected-worlds-first-intersex-mayor/}}</ref>\n* '''[[Elio Di Rupo]]''', '''first openly gay male head of government''', becomes Prime Minister of Belgium, 6 December.\n* '''[[Chaz Bono]]''' appeared on the 13th season of the US version of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]'' in 2011. This was the first time an openly transgender man starred on a major network television show for something unrelated to being transgender.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/society/transgendered/2011/12/28/14-reasons-made-2011-great-trans-people?page=0,11 |title=14 Reasons That Made 2011 Great for Trans People |publisher=Advocate.com |date=2011-12-28 |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n* '''[[Harmony Santana]]''' became the first openly transgender actress to receive a major acting award nomination; she was nominated by the [[Independent Spirit Awards]] as Best Supporting Actress for the movie ''[[Gun Hill Road (film)|Gun Hill Road]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/society/transgendered/2011/12/28/14-reasons-made-2011-great-trans-people?page=0,2 |title=14 Reasons That Made 2011 Great for Trans People |publisher=Advocate.com |date=2011-12-28 |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n* The '''[[Presbyterian Church]] (U.S.A.)''' voted to allow the ordination of openly gay and lesbian ministers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.cnn.com/2011-05-10/us/presbyterian.gay.lesbian.ordination_1_glasspool-lesbian-bishop-lesbian-ministers?_s=PM:US |work=CNN |title=Los Angeles Episcopalians elect lesbian bishop |date=6 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120618200956/http://articles.cnn.com/2011-05-10/us/presbyterian.gay.lesbian.ordination_1_glasspool-lesbian-bishop-lesbian-ministers?_s=PM%3AUS |archivedate=18 June 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''[[Rachel Isaacs]]''' became the first openly lesbian rabbi ordained by the Conservative movement's [[Jewish Theological Seminary of America|Jewish Theological Seminary]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.forward.com/sisterhood-blog/138141/ |title=JTS Ordains Its First Openly Gay Rabbi \u2013 The Sisterhood \u2013 Forward.com |publisher=Blogs.forward.com |date=2011-05-25 |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n* Petty Officer 2nd Class '''Marissa Gaeta''' of California and Petty Officer 3rd Class '''Citlalic Snell''' of Los Angeles became the first same-sex couple chosen to share the first kiss upon a U.S. Navy ship's return.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/nationnow/2011/12/a-public-embrace-between-two-female-sailors-from-california-is-being-hailed-as-the-kiss-heard-round-the-world-by-activists-wh.html|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|title=A public embrace between two female sailors from California is being hailed as the kiss heard around the world by activists | date=22 December 2011}}</ref>\n* '''Brenda Sue Fulton''' was named to the West Point Board of Visitors, making her the first openly gay member of the board that advises the Academy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freep.com/usatoday/article/1738665?odyssey=mod%7Cnewswell%7Ctext%7CFRONTPAGE%7Cp |title=West Point chapel hosts first same-sex marriage &#124; Detroit Free Press |publisher=freep.com |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n* Miss New York, [[Claire Buffie]], became the '''first [[Miss America]] contestant to campaign for the Miss America title on a gay rights platform'''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsfeed.time.com/2013/09/14/miss-kansas-bares-tattoos-and-6-other-memorable-miss-america-moments/|title=Miss Kansas Bares Tattoos and 6 Other Memorable Miss America Moments|work=TIME.com|accessdate=14 March 2015|date=14 September 2013}}</ref>\n* '''Jaiyah \"Johnny\" Saelua''' became the first openly transgender international footballer to play in the World Cup when she took the field for American Samoa in Oceania's first round of World Cup qualifiers for Brazil 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/aug/29/jaiyah-saelua-transgender-footballer-interview|title=Jaiyah Saelua: interview with the world's first transgender football international - Football - theguardian.com|first=Pete|last=Smith|work=the Guardian|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n* A resolution submitted by [[South Africa]] requesting a study on discrimination and sexual orientation (A/HRC/17/L.9/Rev.1) passed, 23 to 19 with 3 abstentions, in the '''UN [[Human Rights Council]]''' on 17 June 2011.<ref name=\"UN Human Rights Council\">{{cite news |url=http://www.ohchr.org/EN/NewsEvents/Pages/DisplayNews.aspx?NewsID=11167&LangID=E |title=UN Human Rights Council |date=17 June 2011 |accessdate=17 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110624081557/http://www.ohchr.org/EN/NewsEvents/Pages/DisplayNews.aspx?NewsID=11167&LangID=E |archivedate=24 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> This is the first time that any United Nations body approved a resolution affirming the rights of LGBT people.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5gpjOuYqR_9HwpkxaT7bS6f0x_glA?docId=3e1fdafae97c40f393a3d245c0df9fe4|title=UN group backs gay rights for the 1st time ever|author=Jordans, Frank|date=2011-05-17|accessdate=2011-05-17|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> \n* '''[[Fred Karger]]''' began his unsuccessful run for the 2012 Republican nomination for President, which made him America's first openly gay Republican presidential candidate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.salon.com/2011/03/23/gay_republican_president|title=Fred Karger, gay Republican, for president|publisher=|accessdate=30 October 2014}}</ref>\n* '''San Francisco\u2019s Human Rights Commission released a report on bisexual visibility''', titled \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20141010222618/http://sf-hrc.org/sites/sf-hrc.org/files/migrated/FileCenter/Documents/HRC_Publications/Articles/Bisexual_Invisiblity_Impacts_and_Recommendations_March_2011.pdf Bisexual Invisibility: Impacts and Regulations]\"; this was the first time any governmental body released such a report.<ref name=\"advocate 2011\">{{cite news|title= The Biggest Bisexual News Stories of 2011|url=http://www.advocate.com/news/daily-news/2011/09/23/biggest-bisexual-news-stories-2011|date=23 September 2011 |first=Diane|last=Anderson-Minshall}}</ref>\n* '''[[Sandra Lawson]]''' became the first openly gay African-American and the first African-American admitted to the [[Reconstructionist Rabbinical College]].<ref name=\"lawson\">{{cite web|url=https://whyy.org/articles/rabbi-is-latest-of-many-titles-for-philly-woman/|title=Rabbi is latest of many titles for Philly woman|website=WHYY|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref><ref name=\"apbspeakers1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.apbspeakers.com/speaker/sandra-lawson/ |title=Book Sandra Lawson for Speaking, Events and Appearances |publisher=APB Speakers |date= |accessdate=2019-06-03}}</ref>\n\n==2012==\n[[File:Rep Kyrsten Sinema, Official Portrait.jpg|upright|thumb|[[Kyrsten Sinema]] became the first openly bisexual person elected to the U.S. Congress in 2012.]] \n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Passed and came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Denmark|Denmark]], Mexican state of [[Same-sex marriage in Quintana Roo|Quintana Roo]], U.S. states of [[Same-sex marriage in Maine|Maine]] and [[Same-sex marriage in Washington State|Washington]], the [[Same-sex marriage under United States tribal jurisdictions#Port Gamble S'Klallam Tribe|Port Gamble S'Klallam Tribe]], \n** '''Passed''': U.S. state of [[Same-sex marriage in Maryland|Maryland]]\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Came into effect''': U.S. State of [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Hawaii|Hawaii]]\n* '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Lesotho|Lesotho]] and [[LGBT rights in S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe|S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe]]\n* '''Anti-discrimination legislation''':\n** '''For sexual orientation and gender identity''': [[LGBT rights in Chile|Chile]]\n** The [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development|U.S. Dept. of Housing and Urban Development]]'s [[Office of Fair Housing and Equal Opportunity]] issued a regulation to prohibit LGBT discrimination in federally assisted housing programs. The new regulations ensure that the Department's core housing programs are open to all eligible persons, regardless of sexual orientation or gender identity.\n** For '''gender identity:''' Canadian provinces of [[Manitoba]]; and '''gender expression:''' [[Ontario]]\n* '''Family and Relationships:'''\n** The first gay Israeli couple was granted a divorce by an Israeli family court. The divorce of Tel Aviv University Professor [[Avi Even]], the first openly gay Knesset member, and Dr. Amit Kama was granted on Sunday by the Ramat Gan Family Court, according to [[Haaretz]], which ordered the Interior Minister to register their status as divorced.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thejewishweek.com/news/breaking-news/israel-grants-first-gay-divorce |title=Israel Grants First Gay Divorce |newspaper=The Jewish Week |accessdate=2013-10-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007071208/http://www.thejewishweek.com/news/breaking-news/israel-grants-first-gay-divorce |archivedate=7 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n** Taiwan's first same-sex Buddhist wedding was held for '''Fish Huang''' and her partner '''You Ya-ting''', with Buddhist master Shih Chao-hui presiding over the ritual.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/China/Taiwan-gets-its-first-same-sex-Buddhist-wedding/Article1-911937.aspx|title=Taiwan gets its first same-sex Buddhist wedding|date=2012-08-11|newspaper=Hindustan Times|accessdate=2013-10-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131010225722/http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/China/Taiwan-gets-its-first-same-sex-Buddhist-wedding/Article1-911937.aspx|archivedate=10 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** The '''first same-sex marriage at the U.S. Military Academy''' was held for a young lieutenant and her partner (Ellen Schick and Shannon Simpson) at the Old Cadet Chapel in West Point's cemetery.<ref name=\"boston.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.boston.com/news/nation/2012/12/02/west-point-chapel-hosts-its-first-same-sex-wedding/sHjOTBBa2hweA3KxjU3m9O/story.html|title=West Point Chapel hosts its first same sex wedding|accessdate=2013-10-05|newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130823023451/http://www.boston.com/news/nation/2012/12/02/west-point-chapel-hosts-its-first-same-sex-wedding/sHjOTBBa2hweA3KxjU3m9O/story.html|archivedate=23 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://outservemag.com/2012/12/first-gay-weddings-held-at-west-point/|title=First Gay Weddings Held at West Point &#124; OutServe Magazine|date=2012-12-01|publisher=Outservemag.com|first=David|last=Small|accessdate=2013-10-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131006165540/http://outservemag.com/2012/12/first-gay-weddings-held-at-west-point/|archivedate=6 October 2013|df=dmy}}</ref> Navy Chief '''Elny McKinney''' and '''Anacelly McKinney''' became the first known same-sex couple to marry on a U.S. military base. They were wed at Naval Base Point Loma in San Diego.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/military/2012/09/18/11-firsts-after-repeal-dadt?page=0,5|title=11 Firsts After The Repeal of DADT|last=Garcia|first=Michelle|date=2012-09-18|publisher=Advocate.com|accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n** The '''first same-sex couple became engaged in the White House''' (Ben Schock and Matthew Phelps).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rt.com/usa/news/gay-white-house-couple-321/|title=Gay Marine proposes in the White House \u2014 RT USA|date=2012-12-18|publisher=Rt.com|accessdate=2013-10-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117073054/http://rt.com/usa/news/gay-white-house-couple-321/|archivedate=17 January 2013|df=dmy}}</ref>\n** Air Force Col. '''Ginger Wallace''' became the first known out member of the U.S. military to have their same-sex partner participate in the pinning ceremony tradition that had been reserved for spouses and family members. Her partner of 10 years, Kathy Knopf, pinned colonel wings on Wallace days after the two attended President Obama's State of The Union address as a guest of the First Lady.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/military/2012/09/18/11-firsts-after-repeal-dadt?page=0,4|title=11 Firsts After The Repeal of DADT|last=Garcia|first=Michelle|date=2012-09-18|publisher=Advocate.com|accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n* '''Arts and Culture:'''\n** '''Kate McKinnon''' became [[Saturday Night Live]]'s first openly [[lesbian]] cast member; [[Danitra Vance]] never disclosed her sexual orientation publicly, but was revealed to be a lesbian when she died.<ref name=\"shewired\">{{cite news|url=http://www.shewired.com/box-office/2012/04/08/snls-first-out-lesbian-featured-player-kate-mckinnon-makes-splash-penelope|title=SNL's First Out Lesbian Featured Player Kate McKinnon Makes Splash with Penelope Cruz Pantene Sketch|last=Gilchrist|first=Tracy E.|date=8 April 2012|accessdate=10 April 2012|newspaper=SheWired}}</ref><ref>Danitra Vance's sexual orientation was not revealed until [https://www.nytimes.com/1994/08/23/obituaries/danitra-vance-35-an-actress-worked-at-shakespeare-festival.html her death in 1994].</ref>\n** On 28 June 2012 '''[[Diana King]]''' declared \"Yes I am a Lesbian\" to her fans from her official Facebook page, thus becoming the first Jamaican artist to ever publicly come out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.outmusicawards.com/pages/honorees.html|title=OUTmusic Awards The Biggest Night of the LGBT Music Industry|publisher=Outmusicawards.com|accessdate=2013-10-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007002002/http://www.outmusicawards.com/pages/honorees.html|archivedate=7 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/notes/dianaking/yes-i-am-a-lesbian/10151076275753885|title=Yes!! I Am A Lesbian|publisher=Facebook.com|accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n** '''Katie Ricks''' became the first open lesbian ordained by the [[Presbyterian Church]] (U.S.A.)<ref>[http://www.advocate.com/news/2012/04/16/katie-ricks-presbyterians-ordain-their-first-out-lesbian Katie Ricks: Presbyterians Ordain Their First Out Lesbian]. ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]].'' retrieved 6 June 2012.</ref>\n** '''Emily Aviva Kapor''', an American rabbi who had been ordained privately by a \"[[Conservadox]]\" rabbi in 2005, began living as a woman in 2012, thus becoming the first openly transgender female rabbi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forward.com/articles/180230/emily-aviva-kapor-creating-a-jewish-community-for/|title=Emily Aviva Kapor: Creating a Jewish Community for Trans Women|date=15 July 2013|publisher=The Forward|accessdate=25 October 2013}}</ref>\n**  '''Rainbow Jews''', an oral history project showcasing the lives of Jewish bisexual, lesbian, gay, and transgender people in the [[United Kingdom]] from the 1950s until the present, was launched.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rainbowjews.com/about-us/|title=About us|publisher=Rainbow Jews|accessdate=2014-04-05}}</ref> It is the United Kingdom's first archive of Jewish bisexual, lesbian, gay, and transgender history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haaretz.com/jewish-world/jewish-world-features/.premium-1.573723|title=Trove of Jewish LGBT history goes on display in U.K.|date=2014-12-02|publisher=Haaretz.com|accessdate=2014-04-05}}</ref>\n** ''[[ParaNorman]]'', released in 2012, had the '''first openly gay character in a mainstream animated film.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://diversity.nbcuni.com/in_the_news/paranorman-screenwriterco-director-chris-butler-on-writing-the-first-gay-character-in-a-mainstream-animated-film|title=\"ParaNorman\" Screenwriter/Co-Director Chris Butler on Writing the First Gay Character in a Mainstream Animated Film - diversity.nbcuni.com|work=diversity.nbcuni.com|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://parentpreviews.com/movie-reviews/paranorman|title=Parent Guide for \"ParaNorman\" On Home Video|publisher=|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref>\n* '''Politics:'''\n** '''US Politics:'''\n*** '''[[Barack Obama]]''' became the first [[President of the United States|U.S. president]] to publicly announce support for same-sex marriage on 9 May.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://firstread.msnbc.msn.com/_news/2012/05/09/11621156-obama-i-think-same-sex-couples-should-be-able-to-get-married?lite |agency=MSNBC |title=Obama: 'I think same sex couples should be able to get married' |first=Michael |last=O'Brien |date=9 May 2012 |accessdate=9 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120510060229/http://firstread.msnbc.msn.com/_news/2012/05/09/11621156-obama-i-think-same-sex-couples-should-be-able-to-get-married?lite |archivedate=10 May 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>Jackie Calmes and Peter Baker (9 May 2012). [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/10/us/politics/obama-says-same-sex-marriage-should-be-legal.html?hp Obama Says Same-Sex Marriage Should Be Legal] ''nytimes.com'' Retrieved 9 May 2012.</ref>\n*** '''Marlene Pray''' joined the Doylestown, Pennsylvania City Council in 2012, though she resigned in 2013; she was the first openly bisexual office holder in Pennsylvania.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://amplifyyourvoice.org/u/jordan/2012/01/04/marlene-pray-becomes-first-openly-bisexual-office-holder-in-pa |title=Marlene Pray Becomes First Openly Bisexual Office Holder In PA - Amplify |publisher=Amplifyyourvoice.org |date=2012-01-04 |accessdate=2013-10-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007063401/http://amplifyyourvoice.org/u/jordan/2012/01/04/marlene-pray-becomes-first-openly-bisexual-office-holder-in-pa |archivedate=7 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.phillyburbs.com/my_town/doylestown/marlene-pray-resigns-from-doylestown-council/article_f6cb9457-ac07-5300-910e-162ddd29419b.html |title=Marlene Pray resigns from Doylestown Council - phillyburbs.com: Doylestown |publisher=phillyburbs.com |date=2013-03-19 |accessdate=2013-10-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130615223150/http://www.phillyburbs.com/my_town/doylestown/marlene-pray-resigns-from-doylestown-council/article_f6cb9457-ac07-5300-910e-162ddd29419b.html |archivedate=15 June 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*** '''[[Tammy Baldwin]]''' was elected as the first openly lesbian or gay U.S. Senator.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/blogs/ticket/tammy-baldwin-elected-first-openly-gay-senator-043558173--election.html |title=Tammy Baldwin is elected the first openly gay senator - Yahoo! News |publisher=News.yahoo.com |date=2012-11-06 |accessdate=2013-09-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029195528/http://news.yahoo.com/blogs/ticket/tammy-baldwin-elected-first-openly-gay-senator-043558173--election.html |archivedate=29 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*** '''[[Kyrsten Sinema]]''' (D-AZ) became the first openly bisexual person elected to the US Congress.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2012/11/kyrsten-sinema-becomes-first-openly-bisexual-member-of-congress | work=ABC News | title=Kyrsten Sinema Becomes First Openly Bisexual Member of Congress | date=12 November 2012}}</ref>\n*** '''[[Stacie Laughton]]''' became the first openly transgender person elected to any American state legislature when she won a seat in the New Hampshire House of Representatives.<ref>{{cite web|first=Chris |last=Geidner |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/new-hampshire-elects-nations-first-trans-lawmaker |title=New Hampshire Elects Nation's First Out Trans Lawmaker |publisher=Buzzfeed.com |date=2013-09-19 |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref> However, she resigned from the New Hampshire state legislature before she took office, after it was revealed that she had served four months in Belknap County House of Corrections following a 2008 credit card fraud conviction.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/11/27/stacie-laughton-resigns-transgender-new-hampshire-state-rep_n_2200297.html?ir=Gay+Voices | work=Huffington Post | first=Curtis | last=Wong | title=Transgender New Hampshire Rep Steps Down Amid Shocking Revelations | date=27 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/new-hampshire-elects-nations-first-trans-lawmaker |title=New Hampshire Elects Nation's First Out Trans Lawmaker|publisher=buzzfeed.com |date=8 November 2012 |accessdate=8 November 2012}}</ref>\n*** '''[[Mark Pocan]]''' was elected in Wisconsin's 2nd Congressional District, becoming the first openly gay candidate who will follow an openly gay member of the U.S. Congress (in this case [[Tammy Baldwin]]).<ref name=\"gaypolitics.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gaypolitics.com/2012/11/07/victory-fund-celebrates-huge-night-for-gay-candidates/|title=Gay Politics \u2014 Victory Fund celebrates huge night for gay candidates|date=2012-11-07|publisher=Gaypolitics.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108175351/http://www.gaypolitics.com/2012/11/07/victory-fund-celebrates-huge-night-for-gay-candidates/|archive-date=2012-11-08|url-status=dead|accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n*** '''[[Sean Patrick Maloney]]''' became the first openly gay candidate elected to represent New York in Congress.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/election/2012/11/07/openly-gay-congressional-winner-makes-history-new-york|title=Openly Gay Congressional Winner Makes History in New York|last=Bolcer|first=Julie|date=2012-11-07|publisher=Advocate.com|accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n*** '''[[Mark Takano]]''' became the first openly gay person of color to win election to the U.S. House. He was elected to represent California's 41st Congressional District.<ref name=\"gaypolitics.com\" />\n*** '''[[Josh Boschee]]''' was elected as North Dakota's first openly gay legislator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wday.com/event/article/id/71107/group/homepage/|title=Josh Boschee North Dakota's first gay legislator &#124; WDAY &#124; Fargo, ND|date=2012-11-07|publisher=WDAY|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130217004318/http://www.wday.com/event/article/id/71107/group/homepage/|archive-date=17 February 2013|url-status=dead|accessdate=2013-10-05|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*** '''[[Stephen Skinner (American politician)|Stephen Skinner]]''' was elected as West Virginia's first openly gay state legislator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lgbtqnation.com/2012/11/west-virginia-elects-first-openly-gay-state-legislator/|title=West Virginia elects first openly gay state legislator \u2013 LGBTQ Nation|date=2013-09-22|publisher=Lgbtqnation.com|accessdate=2013-10-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921104440/http://www.lgbtqnation.com/2012/11/west-virginia-elects-first-openly-gay-state-legislator/|archive-date=21 September 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*** '''[[Jacob Candelaria]]''' was elected as New Mexico's first openly gay male state legislator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitolreportnewmexico.com/?tag=jacob-candelaria|title=Capitol Report &#124; New Mexico \" Jacob Candelaria Jacob Candelaria \" Capitol Report &#124; New Mexico|publisher=Capitolreportnewmexico.com|accessdate=2013-10-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160209085635/http://www.capitolreportnewmexico.com/?tag=jacob-candelaria|archivedate=9 February 2016|df=dmy}}</ref>\n*** '''[[Brian Sims]]''' became Pennsylvania's first openly gay state legislator who was out when he was elected.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lgbtqnation.com/2012/04/pennsylvania-to-get-first-openly-gay-lawmaker/|title=Pennsylvania to get first openly gay lawmaker \u2013 LGBTQ Nation|date=2013-09-22|publisher=Lgbtqnation.com|accessdate=2013-10-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131006235307/http://lgbtqnation.com/2012/04/pennsylvania-to-get-first-openly-gay-lawmaker/|archive-date=6 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> After [[Brian Sims]] was elected but before he took office, Rep. '''[[Mike Fleck]]''' came out as gay, making him Pennsylvania's first openly gay state legislator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/20121201_Republican_Pa__lawmaker_announces_hes_gay.html|title=Republican Pa. lawmaker announces he's gay|date=2012-12-02|publisher=Philly.com|accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n*** '''[[David Richardson (Florida politician)|David Richardson]]''' was elected as Florida's first openly gay state legislator.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/08/15/david-richardson-florida-first-out-state-legislator-elected_n_1778616.html|title=Florida's 1st Gay Legislator: 'Not One Person Closed Their Doors On Me'|last=Campbell|first=Janie|date=15 August 2012|work=Huffington Post}}</ref>\n*** Colorado Democrats elected '''[[Mark Ferrandino]]''' as the first openly gay House speaker in state history.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/2012/11/09/colo_democrats_pick_states_1st_gay_house_speaker/|title=Colo. Democrats pick state's 1st gay House speaker|last=Moreno|first=Ivan|date=2012-11-09|work=Salon.com|accessdate=2013-10-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131115025708/http://www.salon.com/2012/11/09/colo_democrats_pick_states_1st_gay_house_speaker/|archivedate=15 November 2013|df=dmy}}</ref>\n*** '''[[Tina Kotek|Tina Kotek was elected the first openly gay House speaker in the State of]] [[Oregon]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/today/index.ssf/2012/11/tina_kotek_selected_oregon_hou.html|title=Tina Kotek selected Oregon House speaker|date=15 November 2012|work=The Oregonian}}</ref>'''\n*** '''[[Richard Grenell]]''' was a foreign policy spokesperson for Republican Mitt Romney during Romney's 2012 campaign for president of the United States; this made him the first openly gay individual to work as a spokesperson for a Republican presidential candidate.\n* '''Other'''\n* '''[[San Francisco]]''' voted to become the first U.S. city to provide and cover the cost of sex reassignment surgeries for uninsured transgender residents.<ref>{{cite web |title=S.F. health care to cover sex reassignment surgery |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/sf-health-care-to-cover-sex-reassignment-surgery/ |date=9 November 2012 |accessdate=13 February 2017}}</ref> \n* '''[[Berkeley, California]]''' became the first city in the U.S. to officially proclaim a day recognizing bisexuals\u201423 September as '''[[Celebrate Bisexuality Day|Bisexual Pride and Bi Visibility Day]]'''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/berkeley-becomes-first-us-city-to-declare-bisexual-pride-day-support-marginalized-group/2012/09/18/8556fd92-0208-11e2-bbf0-e33b4ee2f0e8_story.html|title=Berkeley becomes first US city to declare Bisexual Pride Day, support \u2018marginalized\u2019 group|newspaper=The Washington Post|accessdate=19 September 2012}} {{Dead link|date=April 2014|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref>\n* '''California''' became the first U.S. state to sign a ban on therapy that claims to convert gay people into heterosexual.<ref name=\"washingtonblade.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2013/08/19/christie-to-sign-law-barring-ex-gay-conversion-therapy/|title=Christie signs law barring 'ex-gay' conversion therapy - Washington Blade - America's Leading Gay News Source : Washington Blade \u2013 America's Leading Gay News Source|last=Johnson|first=Chris|date=2013-08-19|newspaper=Washington Blade|accessdate=2013-10-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130823235731/http://www.washingtonblade.com/2013/08/19/christie-to-sign-law-barring-ex-gay-conversion-therapy/|archivedate=23 August 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"news.yahoo.com\">{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/gay-conversion-therapy-know-201649505.html|title=Gay Conversion Therapy: What You Should Know - Yahoo News|last=Pappas|first=Stephanie|date=2013-08-19|publisher=News.yahoo.com|accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n* At a ceremony in Arlington, Army Reserve officer '''Tammy Smith''' became the first openly gay, active duty general in American history. Smith was promoted to brigadier general at a private ceremony at the Women's Memorial at Arlington National Cemetery.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metroweekly.com/poliglot/2012/08/lesbian-becomes-highest-ranking-out-military-offic.html |title=Lesbian Becomes Highest Ranking Out Military Officer - Poliglot |publisher=Metroweekly.com |date=2012-08-10 |accessdate=2013-10-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131006221021/http://www.metroweekly.com/poliglot/2012/08/lesbian-becomes-highest-ranking-out-military-offic.html |archivedate=6 October 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* '''[[Orlando Cruz]]''' became the world's first professional boxer to come out as gay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/world/interview-with-first-openly-gay-boxer-orlando-cruz-a-866052.html |title=Interview with First Openly Gay Boxer Orlando Cruz - SPIEGEL ONLINE |publisher=Spiegel.de |date=2012-11-09 |accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref>\n* The '''Bisexuality Report''', the first report of its kind in the United Kingdom, was issued.<ref name=\"bisexualityreport\">{{cite web|first=Amandine |last=Scherrer |url=http://www.open.ac.uk/ccig/news/the-bisexuality-report-is-now-available |title=The Bisexuality Report is now available - News - Centre for Citizenship, Identities and Governance (CCIG) - Open University |publisher=Open.ac.uk |date=2012-02-14 |accessdate=2015-08-05}}</ref> This report, led by Meg Barker (Senior Lecturer in Psychology, OU), Rebecca Jones (Lecturer, Health & Social Care, OU), Christina Richards, and Helen Bowes-Catton and Tracey Plowman (of BiUK) summarizes national and international evidence and brings out recommendations for bisexual inclusion in the future.<ref name=\"bisexualityreport\" />\n\n==2013==\n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Passed and came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in New Zealand|New Zealand]], [[Same-sex marriage in Uruguay|Uruguay]], [[Same-sex marriage in France|France]], [[LGBT rights in Brazil|Brazil]], the U.S. states of [[Same-sex marriage in Delaware|Delaware]], [[Same-sex marriage in Rhode Island|Rhode Island]], [[Same-sex marriage in Minnesota|Minnesota]], [[Same-sex marriage in New Jersey|New Jersey]], [[Same-sex marriage in Hawaii|Hawaii]] and [[Same-sex marriage in New Mexico|New Mexico]], the [[Same-sex marriage in the Confederated Tribes of the Colville Reservation|Confederated Tribes of the Colville Reservation]], the [[Same-sex marriage in the Little Traverse Bay Bands of Odawa Indians|Little Traverse Bay Bands of Odawa Indians]], the [[Same-sex marriage in the Pokagon Band of Potawatomi Indians|Pokagon Band of Potawatomi Indians]], the [[Same-sex marriage in the Cheyenne and Arapaho Tribes|Cheyenne and Arapaho Tribes]], the [[Same-sex marriage in the Leech Lake Band of Ojibwe|Leech Lake Band of Ojibwe]], the [[Same-sex marriage in the Grand Portage Band of Chippewa|Grand Portage Band of Chippewa]] and the [[Same-sex marriage in the Iipay Nation of Santa Ysabel|Iipay Nation of Santa Ysabel]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldonline.com/2013/06/24/4971450/california-native-american-tribe.html|title=California Native American Tribe Announces Support of Same Sex Marriage: Santa Ysabel Tribe First in California to Make Proclamation|date=2013-06-24|publisher=Rock Hill Herald Online|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130628034639/http://www.heraldonline.com/2013/06/24/4971450/california-native-american-tribe.html|archive-date=28 June 2013|url-status=dead|accessdate=2013-06-25|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pokagonband-nsn.gov/sites/default/files/assets/group/tribal-council/form/2013/marriage-code-3-9-13-1369-1173.pdf|title=POKAGON BAND OF POTAWATOMI INDIANS MARRIAGE CODE|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwmt.com/news/features/featured/stories/west-michigan-couple-have-first-samesex-wedding-pokagon-tribal-court-1278.shtml|title=West Michigan couple have first same-sex wedding in Pokagon Tribal Court|date=2013-06-21|publisher=WWMT Newschannel 3|accessdate=2013-06-25|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130627233914/http://wwmt.com/news/features/featured/stories/west-michigan-couple-have-first-samesex-wedding-pokagon-tribal-court-1278.shtml|archivedate=27 June 2013|df=dmy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wenatcheeworld.com/news/2013/sep/07/colvilles-recognize-same-sex-marriage/|title=Colvilles recognize same sex marriage|publisher=|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/marriage-equality/2013/03/15/michigan-native-american-tribe-recognizes-same-sex-marriage|title=Michigan Native American Tribe Recognizes Same-Sex Marriage|last=Rudolph|first=Christopher|date=15 March 2013|work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|accessdate=16 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/gay-couples-hitched-minnesota-rhode-island-134316870.html|title=Gay couples get hitched in Minnesota, Rhode Island|date=1 August 2013|work=[[Yahoo News]]|accessdate=3 August 2013}}</ref> \n** '''Restored''': [[Same-sex marriage in California|California]]\n** '''Passed''': [[Same-sex marriage in the United Kingdom|England and Wales]] and US state of [[Same-sex marriage in Illinois|Illinois]]\n** '''Passed but then overturned''': [[Same-sex marriage in the Australian Capital Territory|Australian Capital Territory]]\n** '''Came into effect''': U.S. State of [[Same-sex marriage in Maryland|Maryland]]\n** '''Recognition''': The Supreme Court of the United States ruled Section 3 of [[Defense of Marriage Act]] unconstitutional, thus giving same-sex marriage federal recognition.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/26/supreme-court-doma-decision_n_3454811.html | work=Huffington Post | title=Supreme Court Rules DOMA Unconstitutional | date=26 June 2013 | first1=Ryan J. | last1=Reilly | first2=Sabrina | last2=Siddiqui}}</ref> US state of Oregon\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and came into effect''': Mexican state of [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Mexico|Campeche]]\n** '''Came into effect''': U.S. State of [[LGBT rights in Colorado|Colorado]]\n* '''Limited Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and came into effect''': [[LGBT rights in Costa Rica|Costa Rica]]\n* '''Same-sex couple adoption legalisation''': [[Same-sex marriage in New Zealand|New Zealand]] and [[Same-sex marriage in France|France]]\n* '''Recriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in India|India]]\n* '''Anti-discrimination legislation''':\n** '''For sexual orientation and gender identity''': [[LGBT rights in Cyprus|Cyprus]] and [[LGBT rights in Puerto Rico|Puerto Rico]]\n** '''For gender identity''': US state of [[LGBT rights in Delaware|Delaware]]; and '''gender expression''': Canadian provinces of [[Newfoundland and Labrador]] and [[Prince Edward Island]]\n* '''Anti-discrimination executive action''':  US state of [[LGBT rights in Virginia|Virginia]]\n* '''First Pride Marches:''' In '''[[Ukraine]];'''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-22667015|title=Ukraine stages first gay pride march|date=25 May 2013|work=BBC News}}</ref> '''[[Montenegro]];'''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/10/20/montenegro-gay-pride-parade_n_4131778.html|title=Montenegro's First Gay Pride Parade Takes Place Under Heavy Security|last=Wong|first=Curtis|date=2013-10-20|publisher=Huffingtonpost.com|accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref> and '''[[Curacao]]'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaycuracao.com/eng/curacao_pride.php|title=GAYCURA\u00c7AO.COM - We live and let live!|publisher=Gaycuracao.com|accessdate=2014-01-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023001355/http://www.gaycuracao.com/eng/curacao_pride.php|archive-date=23 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* '''Politics:'''\n** '''[[Kathleen Wynne]]''' became the first openly LGBT premier of a Canadian province, namely Ontario, after defeating Sandra Pupatello in the third round of voting of the Ontario Liberal party's leadership race on 26 January 2013. Sworn in on 11 February 2013, she is the party's first openly LGBT leader and Ontario's first female premier.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n** '''[[Xavier Bettel]]''', '''first openly gay''' Prime Minister of Luxembourg, assumes office 4 December.\n** '''[[Etienne Schneider]]''', '''first openly gay''' Deputy Prime Minister of Luxembourg, assumes office 4 December.\n** '''[[Luxembourg]]''' becomes the first country in the world to have an openly gay Prime Minister [[Xavier Bettel]] and an openly gay Deputy Prime Minister [[Etienne Schneider]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2013/11/14/luxembourg-to-become-first-country-to-have-gay-prime-minister-and-gay-deputy-pm/ |title=Luxembourg to 