sh\" Rose''' became the first openly lesbian two-star general in the U.S. Air Force, and the highest ranking openly gay officer in the entire U.S. military at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thinkprogress.org/lgbt/2013/06/10/2127481/the-morning-pride-june-10-2013/ |title=The Morning Pride: June 10, 2013 |website=ThinkProgress |date=2013-06-10 |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n* '''New Jersey''' became the second state, after California, to sign a ban on therapy that claims to convert gay people into heterosexual.<ref name=\"washingtonblade.com\" /><ref name=\"news.yahoo.com\" />\n* '''[[Russia]]'s government adopted a federal bill banning the distribution of \"propaganda of non-traditional sexual relations\" to minors. The law imposes heavy fines for using the media or internet to promote \"non-traditional relations\".'''\n* San Francisco's first '''Project Homeless Connect''' for lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender people was held.<ref>{{cite news|first=Kevin |last=Fagan |url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/S-F-tackles-dual-challenge-being-homeless-and-4876509.php |title=S.F. tackles dual challenge - being homeless and gay |newspaper=SFGate |date=2013-10-07 |accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref>\n* '''BiLaw''', the first American national organization of bisexual lawyers, law professors, law students, and their allies, was founded.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://law.indianatech.edu/faculty/professor-marcus-speaks-at-harvard-law-school/ |title=Professor Marcus Speaks at Harvard Law School - Indiana Tech Law School : Indiana Tech Law School |publisher=Law.indianatech.edu |accessdate=2015-07-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716012405/http://law.indianatech.edu/faculty/professor-marcus-speaks-at-harvard-law-school/ |archivedate=16 July 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= Advocate Contributors |url=http://www.advocate.com/commentary/2015/03/04/op-ed-how-were-asking-supreme-court-end-bi-erasure |title=Op-ed: How We're Asking the Supreme Court to End Bi Erasure |publisher=Advocate.com |date=2015-03-04 |accessdate=2015-07-15}}</ref>\n\n==2014==\n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Passed and came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in the United Kingdom|Scotland]], US states of [[Same-sex marriage in Oregon|Oregon]], [[Same-sex marriage in Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania]], [[Same-sex marriage in Utah|Utah]], [[Same-sex marriage in Oklahoma|Oklahoma]], [[Same-sex marriage in Virginia|Virginia]], [[Same-sex marriage in Wisconsin|Wisconsin]], [[Same-sex marriage in Indiana|Indiana]], [[Same-sex marriage in Colorado|Colorado]], [[Same-sex marriage in Nevada|Nevada]], [[Same-sex marriage in Idaho|Idaho]], [[Same-sex marriage in West Virginia|West Virginia]], [[Same-sex marriage in North Carolina|North Carolina]], [[Same-sex marriage in Alaska|Alaska]], [[Same-sex marriage in Arizona|Arizona]], [[Same-sex marriage in Wyoming|Wyoming]], [[Same-sex marriage in Kansas|Kansas]], [[Same-sex marriage in South Carolina|South Carolina]], [[Same-sex marriage in Montana|Montana]], the Mexican state of [[Same-sex marriage in Coahuila|Coahuila]], the [[Same-sex marriage in the Puyallup Tribe of Indians|Puyallup Tribe of Indians]], the [[Same-sex marriage under United States tribal jurisdictions#ac du Flambeau Band of Lake Superior Chippewa|Lac du Flambeau of Lake Superior Chippewa]], the [[Same-sex marriage under United States tribal jurisdictions#Fort McDermitt Paiute and Shoshone Tribes of the Fort McDermitt Indian Reservation|Fort McDermitt Paiute and Shoshone Tribes of the Fort McDermitt Indian Reservation]], the [[Same-sex marriage in the Fort McDowell Yavapai Nation|Fort McDowell Yavapai Nation]], the [[Same-sex marriage in the Pascua Yaqui Tribe|Pascua Yaqui Tribe]], the [[Same-sex marriage in the Salt River Pima-Maricopa Indian Community|Salt River Pima-Maricopa Indian Community]], the [[Same-sex marriage in the San Carlos Apache Tribe|San Carlos Apache Tribe]], the [[Same-sex marriage under United States tribal jurisdictions#Wind River Indian Reservation|Wind River Indian Reservation]], the [[Same-sex marriage under United States tribal jurisdictions#Blackfoot Tribe|Blackfoot Tribe]] and the [[Same-sex marriage under United States tribal jurisdictions#Keweenaw Bay Indian Community|Keweenaw Bay Indian Community]]\n** '''Passed''': [[Same-sex marriage in Luxembourg|Luxembourg]]\n** '''Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in the United Kingdom|England and Wales]] and US state of [[Same-sex marriage in Illinois|Illinois]]\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and came into effect''': [[LGBT rights in Gibraltar|Gibraltar]] (with joint adoption), [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Malta|Malta]] (with joint adoption) and [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Croatia|Croatia]]\n** '''Passed''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Estonia|Estonia]]\n* '''Same-sex couple adoption legislation''': [[LGBT rights in Andorra|Andorra]], the Mexican state of [[Same-sex marriage in Coahuila|Coahuila]]\n* '''Decriminalization of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Northern Cyprus|Northern Cyprus]] and [[LGBT rights in Palau|Palau]]\n* '''Criminalization of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Brunei|Brunei]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.humanrightsfirst.org/press-release/brunei-adopts-penal-code-provision-calling-death-stoning-same-sex-acts|title=Brunei Adopts Penal Code Provision Calling for Death by Stoning for Same-Sex Acts|work=Human Rights First}}</ref> \n* '''Banning of same-sex marriage:''' [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Nigeria|Nigeria]]<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://freedomhouse.org/article/nigerian-same-sex-marriage-ban-violates-lgbti-rights |title=Nigerian Same Sex Marriage Ban Violates LGBTI Rights |publisher=Freedom House |date=2013-06-05 |accessdate=2018-12-20}}</ref>\n* '''Anti-discrimination law for gender identity:''' Canadian province [[Saskatchewan]] \n* '''Family and Relationships:'''\n** '''Anna Guillot and Chrissy Kelly''', who were married in New York in 2012, became the first same-sex couple in Mississippi to create a public record of their marriage.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/marriage-equality/2014/03/25/miss-couple-creates-first-record-same-sex-marriage|title=Miss. Couple Creates First Record of Same-Sex Marriage|last=Ring|first=Trudy|date=2014-03-25|publisher=Advocate.com|accessdate=2014-05-18}}</ref> However, this did not give their marriage legal standing in Mississippi.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n** The marriage of '''Giuseppe Chigiotti''' and '''Stefano Bucci''' became the first overseas same-sex marriage to be legally recognized in Italy; the two were married in New York in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/first-overseas-same-sex-marriage-legally-recognized-italy100414|title=First overseas same-sex marriage legally recognized in Italy|date=2014-04-10|publisher=Gay Star News|accessdate=2014-05-18}}</ref>\n** For the first time, an Italian court granted permission for '''the adoption of a child living with a gay couple.''' The child was the biological daughter of one of the women in the couple, and her partner was allowed to legally become her co-parent through adoption.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/italian-court-allows-child-be-legally-adopted-gay-couple300814#sthash.enRhxQ6c.dpuf|title=Italian court allows a child to be legally adopted by gay couple|work=Gay Star News|accessdate=6 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006133440/http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/italian-court-allows-child-be-legally-adopted-gay-couple300814#sthash.enRhxQ6c.dpuf|archivedate=6 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** Berlin, Germany unveiled the '''world's first cemetery for lesbians.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.theweek.com/article.php?id=259428|title=Berlin opens world's first lesbian-only cemetery|date=2014-04-04|publisher=M.theweek.com|first=Meghan|last=DeMaria|accessdate=2014-05-18}}</ref>\n** '''Umma Azul''' was the first child of a lesbian couple to be baptized by the Catholic Church in Argentina.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/04/05/world/americas/argentina-baby-baptism-lesbian-couple/|title=Lesbians' baby baptized by Catholic Church in Argentina - CNN.com|date=7 April 2014|work=CNN}}</ref>\n** '''Emilia Maria Jesty''', daughter of a lesbian couple, was the first child born in Tennessee to have a woman listed on the birth certificate as her \"father.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/features/sns-rt-us-usa-courts-samesexmarriage-20140409,0,1020017.story|title=Gay marriage first in Tenn.: Woman listed as father on birth certificate|last=Biskupic|first=Joan|date=9 April 2014|work=Chicago Tribune}}</ref>\n** The U.S. Department of Veterans Affairs agreed to give survivor benefits to the first-known same-sex war widow, '''Tracy Dice Johnson''', whose wife Donna Johnson died in a suicide bombing attack in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.washingtonpost.com/blogs/federal-eye/wp/2014/05/19/group-va-awards-survivor-benefits-to-first-known-gay-war-widow/|title=Group: VA awards survivor benefits to first-known gay war widow|work=Washington Post|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n** Both lesbian parents were listed on their children's birth certificates in Australia, which is the first time an '''Australian birth certificate''' indicates that both members of a same-sex couple were the legal parents of a child at birth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/world/2014/05/30/australian-first-both-lesbian-parents-named-birth-certificate|title=Australian First: Both Lesbian Parents Named on Birth Certificate|first=Thom|last=Senzee|work=Advocate.com|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n** '''The U.S. Naval Academy Chapel's first-ever same-sex wedding''' was held for David Bucher, a 49-year-old Academy graduate who works at the Pentagon, and partner Bruce Moats.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/u-s-naval-academy-hosts-first-same-sex-wedding-maryland-n102276|title=U.S. Naval Academy Hosts First Same-Sex Wedding for Maryland Couple|last=Balding|first=Justin|date=2014-05-10|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=2014-05-18}}</ref>\n* '''Trans:'''\n** The U.S. '''[[Equal Employment Opportunity Commission]]''' filed the first [[Title VII]] action taken by the federal government on behalf of transgender workers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/federal-agency-sues-companies-over-anti-transgender-discrimination|title=EEOC sues companies over anti-transgender discrimination|work=MSNBC|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref> The lawsuits were filed for Amiee Stephens and Brandi Branson, both transgender women.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/federal-government-sues-companies-over-anti-transgender-disc|title=Federal Government Sues Companies Over Anti-Transgender Discrimination Claims|work=BuzzFeed|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n** '''Meghan Stabler''' became the first openly transgender woman to be named ''Working Mother'' magazine's Working Mother of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tmcnet.com/usubmit/2014/10/15/8068797.htm|title=Meghan Stabler Named First Transgender Working Mother of the Year|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019104841/http://www.tmcnet.com/usubmit/2014/10/15/8068797.htm|archivedate=19 October 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** '''[[Laverne Cox]]''' was on the cover of the 9 June 2014 issue of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', and was interviewed for the article \"The Transgender Tipping Point\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewire.com/culture/2014/05/laverne-cox-is-the-first-transgender-person-on-the-cover-of-time/371798/|title=Laverne Cox Is the First Transgender Person on the Cover of Time|first=Eric|last=Levenson|work=The Wire|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/135480/transgender-tipping-point/?pcd=hp-magmod|title=The Transgender Tipping Point|date=29 May 2014|work=TIME.com|first=Katy|last=Steinmetz|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref> She also became the first openly transgender person to be nominated for an [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy]] in an acting category: Outstanding Guest Actress in a Comedy Series for her role as Sophia Burset in ''[[Orange Is the New Black]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2014/07/10/emmy-nominees-list/12428631/|title=2014 Primetime Emmy nominees|date=2014-07-10|publisher=Usatoday.com|accessdate=2014-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.extratv.com/2014/07/10/2014-emmy-awards-orange-is-the-new-blacks-laverne-cox-is-first-transgender-nominee/|title=2014 Emmy Awards: 'Orange Is the New Black's' Laverne Cox Is First Transgender Nominee|date=2014-07-10|publisher=ExtraTV.com|accessdate=2014-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2009/jan/23/angela-morley-obituary-wally-stott|title=Obituary: Angela Morley &#124; Television & radio|newspaper=The Guardian|first=Gavin|last=Gaughan|accessdate=2014-07-19}}</ref>\n** ''[[Transgender Studies Quarterly]]'', the first non-medical academic journal devoted to transgender issues, began publication, with [[Susan Stryker]] and [[Paisley Currah]] as coeditors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/transgender/2014/05/27/duke-univ-press-debuts-academic-journal-transgender-studies|title=Duke Univ. Press Debuts Academic Journal for Transgender Studies|first=Mitch|last=Kellaway|work=Advocate.com|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n** '''[[Mills College]]''' became the first single-sex college in the U.S. to adopt a policy explicitly welcoming transgender students, '''[[Mount Holyoke]]''' became the first [[Seven Sisters (colleges)|Seven Sisters]] college to accept transgender students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/transgender/2014/09/03/watch-first-seven-sisters-schools-admit-trans-women|title=WATCH: First of 'Seven Sisters' Schools to Admit Trans Women|work=Advocate.com|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n** '''[[Blake Brockington]]''' became the first openly transgender high school [[homecoming king]] in [[North Carolina]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.takepart.com/article/2015/03/26/anguish-north-carolina-s-first-openly-trans-prom-king|title=The Anguish of North Carolina's First Transgender Prom King|last=King|first=Jamilah|date=2015-03-25|publisher=TakePart|accessdate=2015-05-01}}</ref>\n** Nina Chaubal and Greta Gustava Martela cofounded [[Trans Lifeline]], '''the first U.S. suicide hotline dedicated to transgender people.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/health/2014/11/25/new-suicide-hotline-dedicated-trans-people-now-open-calls|title=New Suicide Hotline Dedicated to Trans People Now Open for Calls|last=Kellaway|first=Mitch|date=2014-11-25|publisher=Advocate.com|accessdate=2015-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2015/10/13/First-transgender-suicide-hotline-overcomes-growing-pains.html|title=Suicide Hotline Is Lifeline for Transgender Youth &#124; Al Jazeera America|last=Ryan|first=Hugh|date=|publisher=America.aljazeera.com|accessdate=2015-10-14}}</ref>\n** '''[[Tona Brown]]''' became the first African-American openly transgender woman to perform at Carnegie Hall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dot429.com/articles/4533-violinist-tona-brown-to-make-history-as-the-first-african-american-transgender-woman-to-perform-at-carnegie-concert-hall|title=Violinist Tona Brown to make history as first black transgender woman to perform at Carnegie Hall &#124; Articles|date=2014-05-29|publisher=dot429|author=429magazine|accessdate=2015-11-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208055204/http://dot429.com/articles/4533-violinist-tona-brown-to-make-history-as-the-first-african-american-transgender-woman-to-perform-at-carnegie-concert-hall|archive-date=8 December 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n** The '''Transgender Trends''' panel was the first panel on that subject ever held at San Diego Comic-Con.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tor.com/blogs/2014/08/sdcc-2014-diversity-panels|title=San Diego Comic-Con: The Diversity Conversation|publisher=|author=Karin L Kross|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n** The San Francisco Police academy graduated its first openly transgender police officer, '''Mikayla Connell.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ktvu.com/news/news/local/san-francisco-police-department-adds-first-transge/ng4DL/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819071909/http://www.ktvu.com/news/news/local/san-francisco-police-department-adds-first-transge/ng4DL/|url-status=dead|title=San Francisco Police academy graduates first transgender officer &#124; www.ktvu.com<!-- Bot generated title -->|archivedate=19 August 2014}}</ref>\n** The 100 block of Turk Street in San Francisco was renamed Vicki Mar Lane after trans activist '''Vicki Marlane'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://beyondchron.org/trans-activist-vicki-marlane-honored-with-street-name-in-tenderloin/|title=Beyond Chron - Trans Activist Vicki Marlane Honored With Street Name in Tenderloin - Beyond Chron|work=Beyond Chron|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n** '''[[Lea T]]''' became the face of American hair-care brand [[Redken]], thus making her the first openly transgender model to front a global cosmetics brand.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fashionista.com/2014/11/lea-t-redken-campaign|title=Transgender Model Lea T Lands Big Redken Contract|last=Vingan|first=Alyssa|date=4 November 2014|quote=Now, Lea T has received her most groundbreaking campaign yet: She's signed on to be a brand muse for global haircare brand Redken, with print and digital campaigns set for a January 2015 release.|newspaper=Fashionista.com|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.harpersbazaar.com/fashion/fashion-models/lea-t-redken|title=Transgender Model Lea T Is Redken's Newest Face|last=Friedman|first=Megan|date=4 November 2014|newspaper=[[Harper's Bazaar]]|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/shortcuts/2014/nov/05/lea-t-the-transgender-hair-care-model-whos-shifting-our-perception-of-beauty-norms|title=Lea T, the transgender hair-care model who's shifting our perception of beauty norms|first=Morwenna|last=Ferrier|work=the Guardian|accessdate=7 November 2014}}</ref>\n** A national [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] campaign featured an openly transgender person, '''Jennifer Barge''', as its spokesperson for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/commentary/2014/11/11/op-ed-why-ad-featuring-transgender-woman-means-so-much|title=Op-ed: Why An Ad Featuring A Transgender Woman Means So Much|work=Advocate.com|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref>\n** '''[[Chris Mosier]]''' became the first openly transgender man inducted into the National Gay and Lesbian Sports Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/40-under-40-emerging-voices/2014/08/19/40-under-40-chris-mosier-wants-trans-people-feel-comfortable|title=40 Under 40: Chris Mosier Wants Trans People to Feel Comfortable Playing the Sport They Love|first=Annie|last=Hollenbeck|work=Advocate.com|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://chicago.gopride.com/news/article.cfm/articleid/57288969|title=National Gay and Lesbian Sports Hall of Fame names 2014 Inductees|website=GoPride.com|last1=News Release|accessdate=3 June 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140602025211/http://chicago.gopride.com/news/article.cfm/articleid/57288969|archivedate=2 June 2014|df=dmy}}</ref>\n** '''Kinnon MacKinnon''' became the first openly transgender man to earn a gold in powerlifting at the Gay Games in the 2014 Games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/transgender/2014/09/17/photos-meet-first-trans-man-win-gay-games-gold-powerlifting|title=PHOTOS: Meet the First Trans Man to Win a Gay Games Gold in Powerlifting|work=Advocate.com|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n** [[BBC2]] commissioned '''Britain's first transgender sitcom''', called Boy Meets Girl, which follows the developing relationship between Leo, a 26-year-old man and Judy, a 40-year-old transgender woman.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/bbc2-commissions-britains-first-transgender-sitcom-boy-meets-girl-9683788.html|title=BBC2 commissions Britain's first transgender sitcom Boy Meets Girl|last=Sherwin|first=Adam|date=21 August 2014|work=The Independent|location=London|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n** '''ICEIS Rain''' became the first openly [[two-spirit]] person to perform at the [[Aboriginal Peoples Choice Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/transgender/2014/09/13/watch-meet-trailblazing-two-spirit-performer-iceis-rain|title=WATCH: Meet Trailblazing Two-Spirit Performer ICEIS Rain|work=Advocate.com|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n** '''Padmini Prakash''' became India's first openly transgender television news anchor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2014/09/22/padmini-prakash-is-indias-first-transgender-news-anchor/|title=Padmini Prakash is India's first transgender news anchor|date=22 September 2014|work=Washington Post|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n** '''Denmark''' became the first European country to remove the Gender Identity Disorder diagnosis as a necessary requirement in the gender recognition process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lgbt-ep.eu/press-releases/denmark-becomes-europes-leading-country-on-legal-gender-recognition/|title=Denmark becomes Europe's leading country on legal gender recognition &#124; The European Parliament Intergroup on LGBTI Rights|date=2014-06-12|publisher=Lgbt-ep.eu|accessdate=2015-04-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212093918/http://www.lgbt-ep.eu/press-releases/denmark-becomes-europes-leading-country-on-legal-gender-recognition/|archive-date=12 February 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** '''Malta''' became the first European state to add recognition of gender identity to its constitution as a protected category.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/38027/transgender_europe_applauds_malta_for_naming_gender_identity|title=Transgender Europe applauds Malta for naming gender identity|last=Dalli|first=Miriam|date=16 April 2014|accessdate=16 April 2014|newspaper=Malta Today}}</ref>\n** The '''first openly transgender woman got married in Malta'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://transgriot.blogspot.com/2015/12/joanne-cassar-gets-married-in-malta.html|title=TransGriot|publisher=|first=Monica|last=Roberts}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20140324/local/Smiles-all-round-at-Malta-s-first-transgender-wedding.511882|title=Smiles all round at Malta's first transgender wedding|author=Allied Newspapers Ltd|work=Times of Malta}}</ref>\n** At least 1,000 openly transgender Bangladeshis held '''Bangladesh's first pride march''', to mark one year since the government recognized them as a third gender.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nst.com.my/node/51502|title=Transgender Bangladeshis hold first-ever pride march|work=NST Online|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref>\n* '''Sports:'''\n** The [[2014 Winter Olympics]] in Sochi sparked worldwide [[LGBT rights protests surrounding the 2014 Winter Olympics|protests]] over host country Russia's crackdown on LGBT rights. [[Gus Kenworthy]] won the silver medal in men's freestyle skiing. \n** '''[[Conner Mertens]]''', [[Willamette University]]'s kicker, became the first active college football player to come out as LGBT; he came out as bisexual.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.out.com/entertainment/sports/2014/01/28/gay-college-football-player-conner-mertens-come-out-willamette-university|title=First Active College Football Player to Come Out: Willamette U's Conner Mertens - Out Magazine|accessdate=14 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140430043234/http://www.out.com/entertainment/sports/2014/01/28/gay-college-football-player-conner-mertens-come-out-willamette-university|archivedate=30 April 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** UMass basketball player '''[[Derrick Gordon]]''' came out, thus becoming the first openly gay player in Division I college men's basketball.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaab/2014/04/09/umass-basketball-player-gordon-comes-out-as-gay/7501827/|title=UMass basketball player Gordon comes out as gay|date=9 April 2014|work=USA Today|first1=Scott|last1=Gleeson}}</ref>\n** '''[[Michael Sam]]''' was drafted by the [[St. Louis Rams]] and thus became the first openly gay player to be drafted into the [[National Football League]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/11/sports/football/michael-sam-picked-by-st-louis-rams-in-nfl-draft.html|title=In Historic Pick, Rams Take Michael Sam in Final Round of Draft|last=Belson|first=Ken|date=2014-04-10|work=New York Times}}</ref>\n** The Arizona Interscholastic Association Executive Board approved '''the first transgender student-athlete to play in a winter sport in Arizona.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/high-school/2014/10/22/aia-approves-first-transgender-athlete-play-sport/17718485/|title=AIA approves first transgender athlete to play a sport|date=22 October 2014|publisher=|author=Richard Obert, azcentral sports}}</ref>\n** '''Edward Sarafin''', a backup offensive lineman at Arizona State, became the first active Division I football player to come out as gay.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/14/sports/ncaafootball/asu-lineman-says-he-is-gay.html?_r=0|title=At A.S.U., Division I Football Has First Openly Gay Player|date=13 August 2014|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n** Professional strongman Rob Kearney came out as gay, thus becoming '''the first openly gay man actively competing in professional, international strongman competitions.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ww