[Tim Cook]]''', the CEO of [[Apple Inc.]], came out as gay, thus becoming the first openly gay CEO on the [[Fortune 500]] list.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2014/10/tim-cook-proud-to-be-gay/|title=Tim Cook Tells the World 'I'm Proud to Be Gay' - WIRED|work=WIRED|accessdate=30 October 2014|first=Issie|last=Lapowsky|date=30 October 2014}}</ref>\n* A contingent of the group OutVets became the '''first LGBT organization in history to march in Boston's Veterans Day parade.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/gay-boston-veterans-march-parade|title=Gay vets reach milestone in Boston, still struggle nationally|work=MSNBC|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref>\n* The [[Bisexual Resource Center]], based in Boston, Massachusetts, declared March 2014 as the first '''Bisexual Health Awareness Month''', with the theme \"Bi the Way, Our Health Matters Too!\"; it included the first social media campaign to address disparities in physical and mental health facing the bisexual community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glaad.org/blog/bi-way-our-health-matters-too-its-bisexual-health-awareness-month|title=\"Bi the way, our health matters too!\" \u2013 It's Bisexual Health Awareness Month!|date=2014-03-03|publisher=GLAAD|accessdate=2014-04-05}}</ref>\n* '''[[Queen Elizabeth II]]''' praised the [[London Lesbian and Gay Switchboard]] for their 40-year history making it the first time the Crown has ever publicly supported the LGBT community. They received a comment from the Queen saying: \"Best wishes and congratulations to all concerned on this most special anniversary.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.passportmagazine.com/blog/archives/35130-here-here-queen-elizabeth-makes-first-gesture-of-goodwill-to-the-lgbt-community/|title=Hear Hear Queen Elizabeth Makes First Gesture of Goodwill to the LGBT Community|date=2014-03-07|work=Passport Magazine|accessdate=2014-04-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019104841/http://www.passportmagazine.com/blog/archives/35130-here-here-queen-elizabeth-makes-first-gesture-of-goodwill-to-the-lgbt-community/|archivedate=19 October 2015|df=dmy}}</ref>\n\n==2015==\n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Passed and came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in the United States|United States]] [nationwide],<ref>{{cite web|title=Obergefell et al. v. Hodges, Director, Ohio, Department of Health, et al.|url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/14pdf/14-556_3204.pdf|website=supremecourt.gov|accessdate=26 June 2015}}</ref>  the US state of [[Same-sex marriage in Florida|Florida]], the [[Same-sex marriage under United States tribal jurisdictions#Central Council of the Tlingit and Haida Tribes of Alaska|Central Council of the Tlingit and Haida Tribes of Alaska]], the [[Same-sex marriage under United States tribal jurisdictions#Oneida Nation of Wisconsin|Oneida Nation of Wisconsin]], the [[Same-sex marriage in the Confederated Tribes of Siletz Indians|Confederated Tribes of Siletz Indians]], the Mexican states of [[Same-sex marriage in Chihuahua|Chihuahua]], [[Same-sex marriage in Guerrero|Guerrero]] and [[Same-sex marriage in Nayarit|Nayarit]]\n** '''Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Luxembourg|Luxembourg]] (with joint adoption)\n** '''Passed''': [[Same-sex marriage in Finland|Finland]]\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and came into effect''': [[LGBT rights in Chile|Chile]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/chiles-same-sex-civil-unions-officially-comes-into-force/ |title=Chile's same-sex civil unions officially comes into force |publisher=Gay Star News |date=2014-06-20 |accessdate=2015-10-23}}</ref> [[LGBT rights in Ecuador|Ecuador]] (expansion)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonblade.com/2015/04/23/ecuadorian-lawmakers-approve-civil-unions-bill/ |title=Ecuadorian lawmakers approve civil unions bill |publisher=Washingtonblade.com |date=2015-04-23 |accessdate=2015-05-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asambleanacional.gob.ec/es/system/files/ro_ley_reformatoria_al_codigo_civil_ro_2do._supl_526_del_19-06-2015.pdf|format=PDF|title=LEY REFORMATORIA AL C\u00d3DIGO CIVIL|website=Asamblenacional.gob.ec|accessdate=26 December 2018}}</ref>\n** '''Passed''':[[LGBT rights in Cyprus|Cyprus]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://in-cyprus.com/civil-unions-become-law/ |title=Civil unions become law |publisher=in-cyprus |date=2015-11-26 |accessdate=2015-12-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151127055351/http://in-cyprus.com/civil-unions-become-law/ |archivedate=27 November 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref> [[LGBT rights in Greece|Greece]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/204577/article/ekathimerini/news/greek-parliament-approves-law-on-same-sex-civil-partnerships |title=Greek Parliament approves law on same-sex civil partnerships |publisher=ekathimerini.com |date=2015-12-22 |accessdate=2015-12-23}}</ref>\n* '''Same-sex couple adoption legislation''': [[LGBT rights in Austria|Austria]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2015/01/14/austrian-court-strikes-down-ban-on-gay-adoption/|title=Austrian court strikes down ban on gay adoption|work=PinkNews}}</ref> [[LGBT rights in Ireland|Ireland]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2015/04/02/irish-senators-approve-same-sex-adoption-bill/ |title=Irish senators approve same-sex adoption bill \u00b7 PinkNews |publisher=Pinknews.co.uk |accessdate=2015-04-22}}</ref>\n* '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Mozambique|Mozambique]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/mozambique-decriminalize-homosexuality-june-29-southeast-african-nation-latest-1948203#.|title=Mozambique To Decriminalize Homosexuality June 29: Southeast African Nation Is Latest Country In Africa To Legalize Being Gay|first=Bruce|last=Wright|date=2 June 2015|work=International Business Times}}</ref>\n* '''Anti-discrimination law for gender identity and gender expression:''' Canadian province of [[Alberta]].\n* '''Politics:''' \n** '''Madhu Kinnar''' became India's first openly transgender person to be elected mayor; she was elected mayor of [[Chhattisgarh]]'s Raigarh Municipal Corporation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/andreborges/madhu-kinnar-was-just-elected-indias-first-transgender-mayor|title=Madhu Kinnar Was Just Elected India's First Transgender Mayor|first=Andre|last=Borges|work=BuzzFeed}}</ref>\n** Health Minister [[Leo Varadkar]] of Ireland came out as gay, thus becoming '''the first openly gay government member in the history of Ireland.'''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2015/01/18/irish-cabinet-member-tells-nation-gay-becomes-ireland-1st-openly-gay-government/|title=Irish Cabinet member tells nation he's gay, becomes Ireland's 1st openly gay government member|work=Fox News|date=18 January 2015|access-date=15 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924190853/http://www.foxnews.com/world/2015/01/18/irish-cabinet-member-tells-nation-gay-becomes-ireland-1st-openly-gay-government/|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** Canadian politician '''[[Wade MacLauchlan]]''' won the leadership of the governing [[Prince Edward Island Liberal Party]] on 21 February, and was formally sworn in as Canada's second out LGBT, and first out gay male, provincial premier on 23 February. His party subsequently won the [[2015 Prince Edward Island general election|provincial election]] on 4 May, thus also making him the province's first out LGBT member of the [[Legislative Assembly of Prince Edward Island]].\n** '''[[Michael Connolly (Canadian politician)|Michael Connolly]], [[Ricardo Miranda]] and [[Estefania Cortes-Vargas]]''' won election to the [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta]] as the province's first three openly LGBT MLAs. Cortes-Vargas later came out as genderqueer, and is thus the first out trans person to serve in any Canadian legislature.\n** '''Nepal''' adopted its first democratic constitution, which is the first in Asia to specifically protect the rights of lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender communities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-09-21/nepal-adopts-constitution-born-of-bloodshed2c-compromise/6790466|title=Nepal constitution born of bloodshed, compromise - ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation)|date=|publisher=Abc.net.au|accessdate=2015-09-20}}</ref>\n** '''Tamara Adrian''' was elected to the [[Venezuelan National Assembly]], thus becoming the first openly transgender Venezuelan to be elected to their national legislature, as well as the first openly transgender person in the entire Western Hemisphere to do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://transgriot.blogspot.com/2015/12/tamara-adrian-elected-to-venezuelan.html|title=TransGriot|publisher=|first=Monica|last=Roberts}}</ref> \n** '''US Politics:'''\n*** '''Aisha Moodie-Mills''' became the new president and CEO of the Victory Fund, which made her the first woman, first black woman, first lesbian, and first black lesbian to become the head of a national leading [[LGBT]] organization.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afterellen.com/tv/423309-morning-brew-gillian-anderson-would-date-a-woman-again|title=Morning Brew - Gillian Anderson would date a woman again|last=Bendix|first=Trish|date=2015-03-27|publisher=AfterEllen|accessdate=2015-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/leading-national-lgbt-organization-names-first-wom#.qa8wBvKrq|title=Leading National LGBT Organization Names First Woman, First Black President - BuzzFeed News|date=2013-07-24|publisher=Buzzfeed.com|accessdate=2015-04-17}}</ref>\n*** Pennsylvania State Representative [[Mark B. Cohen]] introduced the first transgender rights bills in Pennsylvania's history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.phillymag.com/g-philly/2015/02/10/rep-mark-cohen-introduces-two-transgender-rights-bills|title=ep. Mark Cohen Introduces Two Transgender Rights Bills|date=10 February 2015|first=Josh|last=Middleton|work=G Philly}}</ref>\n*** '''[[Kate Brown]]''' became the first openly bisexual governor in the United States, as governor of Oregon.<ref name=\"autogenerated5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/politics/meet-americas-first-openly-bisexual-governor/ar-AA9nbjD?ocid=ansnewshp11|title=Meet America's First Openly Bisexual Governor|website=MSN|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612140828/http://www.msn.com/en-us/news/politics/meet-americas-first-openly-bisexual-governor/ar-AA9nbjD?ocid=ansnewshp11|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"oregonlive1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/politics/index.ssf/2015/02/live_updates_kate_brown_become.html|title=Live updates: Kate Brown becomes Oregon governor|date=18 February 2015|work=OregonLive.com|accessdate=2015-02-18}}</ref><ref name=\"Willamette Week\">{{cite news|url=http://www.wweek.com/portland/blog-32833-gov_john_kitzhaber_announces_his_resignation.html|title=Gov. John Kitzhaber Announces His Resignation|date=13 February 2015|newspaper=Willamette Week|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref>\n*** [[Jackie Biskupski]] was elected as '''the first openly gay mayor of Salt Lake City.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/nov/18/jackie-biskupski-elected-as-salt-lake-citys-first-openly-gay-mayor|title=Jackie Biskupski elected as Salt Lake City's first openly gay mayor|work=the Guardian}}</ref>\n*** '''Nancy VanReece''' won the Metro Council District 8 seat in Nashville, thus becoming the first out lesbian elected to a legislative body in Tennessee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outandaboutnashville.com/story/nancy-vanreece-tennessees-first-out-lesbian|title=Nancy VanReece is Tennessee's first out lesbian elected to legislative body &#124; Out & About Nashville|date=|publisher=Outandaboutnashville.com|accessdate=2015-09-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180805143103/https://www.outandaboutnashville.com/story/nancy-vanreece-tennessees-first-out-lesbian|archive-date=5 August 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tennessean.com/story/news/2015/09/10/nancy-vanreece-leads-district-8-early-returns/71963000/|title=Nancy VanReece claims victory in District 8|date=2015-09-10|publisher=Tennessean.com|accessdate=2015-09-14}}</ref>\n*** '''[[Robby Mook]]''' became the first openly gay manager of a major presidential campaign ([[Hillary Clinton]]'s campaign.)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2015/04/robby-mook-hillary-clinton-campaign-manager-profile|title=Robby Mook just took the hardest job in politics: saving the Clintons from themselves.|last=Kroll|first=Andy|last2=Caldwell|first2=Patricia|date=9 April 2015|work=Mother Jones|accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.out.com/news-opinion/2015/4/20/five-things-we-know-about-robby-mook-hillary-clintons-openly-gay-campaign|title=Five Things We Know About Robby Mook, Hillary Clinton's Openly Gay Campaign Manager &#124; Out Magazine|last=McDonald|first=James|publisher=Out.com|accessdate=2015-07-03}}</ref>\n*** [[Randy Berry]] is appointed the '''first Special Envoy for the Human Rights of LGBT Persons.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2015/02/23/388482554/u-s-appoints-first-ever-special-envoy-for-lgbt-rights|title=U.S. Appoints First-Ever Special Envoy For LGBT Rights : The Two-Way|publisher=NPR|first=Eyder|last=Peralta|accessdate=2015-02-24}}</ref>\n*** President Barack Obama became the first president to use the words \"lesbian,\" \"bisexual\", and \"transgender\" in a '''[[State of the Union]] speech'''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/01/20/politics/obama-transgender-sotu/|title=Obama makes historic 'transgender' reference in SOTU - CNN.com|date=21 January 2015|work=CNN|author=Alexandra Jaffe, CNN}}</ref>\n*** President Obama appointed [[Raffi Freedman-Gurspan]] to serve as an Outreach and Recruitment Director in the Presidential Personnel Office, making her '''the first openly transgender appointee to work inside the White House.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/transgender/2015/08/18/obama-appoints-first-trans-woman-white-house-post|title=Obama Appoints First Trans Woman to White House Post|publisher=Advocate.com|first=Bil|last=Browning|accessdate=2015-08-18}}</ref>\n* '''Arts and Culture:'''\n** '''Cambodia''' got its first LGBT magazine, ''Q Cambodia.''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.advocate.com/world/2015/06/04/cambodia-gets-its-first-lgbt-magazine|title=Cambodia Gets Its First LGBT Magazine|publisher=}}</ref>\n** '''Jamaica''' held its first LGBT Pride celebrations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.antillean.org/emancipendence-and-pride-jamaicas-first-official-lgbt-celebrations-signal-turning-tides-876/|title=Jamaica's first LGBT Pride celebrations signal turning tides|publisher=Antillean.org|accessdate=2015-08-09}}</ref>\n** '''[[Zoey Tur]]''' joined ''[[Inside Edition|INSIDE EDITION]]'' as a Special Correspondent during February, thus becoming the first openly transgender television reporter on national TV in America.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rothaussrothaus |first=Steve |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/gay-south-florida/article8951132.html#storylink=cpy |title=Transgender TV news reporter Zoey Tur, formerly Chopper Bob, joins \u2018Inside Edition\u2019 &#124; The Miami Herald The Miami Herald |publisher=Miamiherald.com |date=2015-01-29 |accessdate=2015-02-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2015/02/05/is-americas-transgender-community-ready-for-closeup/22805587/ |title=Is transgender community ready for close-up? |publisher=Usatoday.com |date=2015-01-31 |accessdate=2015-02-06}}</ref>\n** '''[[Thomas Roberts (news anchor)|Thomas Roberts]]''' became the first openly gay evening news anchor on network television when he anchored NBC's \"Nightly News\" for a day.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/thomas-roberts-becomes-firs