l|last=Withers|publisher=|date=2018-01-23}}</ref>\n** [[Laverne Cox]] became '''the first openly transgender person to appear on the cover of any ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'' magazine (specifically, Cosmopolitan South Africa's February 2018 issue).'''.<ref name=\"Wong\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/laverne-cox-cosmopolitan-magazine_us_5a660054e4b0e5630071cc41|title=Laverne Cox Makes History As Cosmopolitan's First Transgender Cover Girl|last=Wong|first=Curtis M.|date=2018-01-22|work=Huffington Post|access-date=2018-01-23}}</ref>\n** [[Paris Lees]] became '''the first openly transgender woman featured in British ''[[Vogue (British magazine)|Vogue]]''.'''<ref name=\"bbc.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-42572561|title=First openly trans woman in British Vogue|date=24 January 2018|publisher=|via=www.bbc.com|work=BBC News}}</ref> \n** Holland, '''the first openly gay K-pop singer''', debuted his first single, \"Neverland.\"<ref name=\"losangelesblade.com\"/>\n** '''[[Dee Rees]]''' and [[Virgil Williams]] were nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay]] for ''[[Mudbound (film)|Mudbound]]'', which made Rees the first queer black woman to be nominated for any Academy Award in a writing category; she was a lesbian.<ref>{{cite news|first=Libby |last=Hill |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-oscars-2018-nominations-90th-dee-rees-becomes-first-black-woman-1516736943-htmlstory.html |title=Dee Rees becomes first black woman Oscar-nominated for adapted screenplay with 'Mudbound' |newspaper=Latimes.com |accessdate=2018-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Rachel |last=Withers |url=https://slate.com/culture/2018/01/a-round-up-of-this-years-history-making-firsts.html |title=The 2018 Oscar nominees include these historic firsts |magazine=Slate |date= 2018-01-23|accessdate=2018-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=GLAAD|url=http://www.glaad.org/blog/glaad-interviews-pariah-director-dee-rees|title=GLAAD Interviews 'Pariah' Director Dee Rees|first=Amita|last=Swadhin|date=29 December 2011}}</ref>\n** '''[[Rachel Morrison]]''' became the first woman ever nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography]], and thus, as she was a lesbian, the first lesbian as well.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/in-contention/oscars-first-female-cinematographer-mudbound-cinematographer-rachel-morrison-1202673355|title=Oscars: 'Mudbound' Cinematographer Is First Female Nominated \u2013 Variety|last=Tapley|first=Kristopher|date=2017-09-12|magazine=Variety.com|accessdate=2018-01-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afterellen.com/movies/41505-lesbian-cinematographer-rachel-morrison-brings-us-a-non-issue|title=Lesbian cinematographer Rachel Morrison brings us \"A Non-Issue?\"|work=[[AfterEllen]]|first=Trish|last=Bendix|date=9 December 2008}}</ref>\n** Canadian [[Eric Radford]] became '''the first openly gay man to win a gold medal at any Winter Olympics.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/gay-athletes-make-history-winter-olympics-n847121 |title=Gay athletes make history at Winter Olympics |publisher=Nbcnews.com |date= |accessdate=2018-02-12}}</ref>\n** '''Jhon Botia Miranda''' was consecrated as a pastor by Bishop Juan Cardona and thus became '''the first openly gay pastor consecrated in the Colombian Methodist Church,''' as well as the first in all of Latin America in the Methodist Church.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rmnetwork.org/colombianmethodistgaypastor/|title=Colombian Methodist Church Welcomes Gay Pastor - RMN+|date=14 March 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n** ''[[Love, Simon]]'' was released as '''the first film ever released by a [[major film studio|major studio]] to focus on a gay teenage romance.'''<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/10/31/love-simon-first-look/ |title='Love, Simon': Your first look at 2018's major studio gay teen romance |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=2018-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://variety.com/2018/scene/vpage/love-simon-premiere-gay-teen-romantic-comedy-1202722636/ |title='Love, Simon' Stars Say Gay Teen Romance Will Save Lives |last=Lang |first=Brent |date=2018-03-09 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=2018-03-11}}</ref>\n** '''Todd Harrity''' came out as gay, thus becoming the first openly gay professional male squash player in the world.<ref>{{cite web|last=Godlewski |first=Nina |url=http://www.newsweek.com/squash-todd-harrity-twitter-instagram-gay-out-906180 |title=Who Is Todd Harrity? Professional Squash's First Openly Gay Male Athlete |magazine=Newsweek |date=2017-06-25 |accessdate=2018-05-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Todd |last=Harrity |url=https://twitter.com/toddharrity/status/990241327815233536 |title=Todd Harrity on Twitter |publisher=Twitter.com |date=2018-04-28 |accessdate=2018-05-02}}</ref>\n** [[Raquel Pennington]] faced [[Amanda Nunes]] on 12 May 2018 at [[UFC 224]] in a [[UFC Women's Bantamweight Championship]] bout.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmadna.nl/amanda-nunes-verdedigt-bantamweight-titel-tegen-raquel-pennington-tijdens-ufc-224/|title=Amanda Nunes verdedigt Bantamweight titel tegen Raquel Pennington tijdens UFC 224|last=DNA|first=MMA|website=mmadna.nl|language=en-US|access-date=2018-02-23}}</ref> Pennington lost the fight via TKO in the fifth round.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2018/05/raquel-pennington-wanted-fight-stopped-after-fourth-but-corner-talked-her-out-of-it|title=Raquel Pennington wanted UFC 224 fight stopped after fourth, but corner talked her out of it|date=2018-05-13|work=MMAjunkie|access-date=2018-05-13|language=en-US}}</ref> This was '''the first event in UFC history to be headlined by two openly gay fighters.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.waypoint.vice.com/amp/en_us/article/a3awvk/ufc-224-amanda-nunes-raquel-pennington-queer|title=UFC's Next Big Event is Headlined By Two Queer Women. It's a Big Deal.|access-date=15 December 2018|archive-url