The Guardian |accessdate=2019-07-08}}</ref>\n** June Eastwood became '''the first openly male-to-female transgender athlete to compete in NCAA Division I cross country; she competed for the University of Montana women's team.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.letsrun.com/news/2019/09/how-did-transgender-runner-june-eastwood-do-in-her-ncaa-division-1-college-debut/|title=How Did Transgender Runner June Eastwood Do in Her NCAA Division 1 College Debut?|date=2019-08-27|publisher=LetsRun.com|accessdate=2019-09-05}}</ref>\n** '''Amanda Sauer-Cook''' became the first openly gay referee to work in a major professional football league, when she served as a center judge for the Alliance of American Football.<ref>\ud83d\udd89{{Cite web|url=https://www.outsports.com/platform/amp/2020/2/6/21126343/xfl-referees-amanda-sauer-cook|title=Openly gay referee Amanda Sauer-Cook will be part of diverse XFL officiating crew|website=www.outsports.com}}</ref>\n\n==2020==\n** '''Rachel Slawson''' became the first openly bisexual contestant to compete for the [[Miss USA]] title.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/miss-usa-competition-include-first-openly-bisexual-contestant-n1120606|title=First openly bisexual contestant to compete in Miss USA's history|last=Aviles|first=Gwen|date=2020-01-22|website=NBC News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n** '''[[Katie Sowers]]''' became the first female and first openly gay offensive assistant in a [[Super Bowl]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Yang|first=Avery|title=49ers' Katie Sowers First Female, Openly gay offensive assistant in Super Bowl History |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2020/01/22/katie-sowers-first-female-openly-gay-coach-super-bowl |website=SI.com|date=22 January 2020|accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref>\n** '''[[Pete Buttigieg]]''' became the first openly gay candidate to win an American presidential primary or caucus.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pete Buttigieg's History-Making Campaign Fell Short, But He Leaves the Race a Star |url=https://time.com/5793275/pete-buttigieg-ends-campaign/ |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=1 March 2020 |accessdate=2 March 2020 |author=Alex Altman}}</ref>\n** '''[[Curdin Orlik]]''' became the first athlete in the sport of [[Schwingen]] to come out as gay, and also the first openly gay male active in Swiss professional sports.<ref name= out>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outsports.com/2020/3/10/21172163/swiss-wrestler-curdin-orlik-comes-out-gay-switzerland|title=Wrestler Curdin Orlik is Switzerland\u2019s first out gay male athlete|first=Jim|last=Buzinski|date=March 10, 2020|website=Outsports}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tagesanzeiger.ch/sport/lieber-bin-ich-frei-als-aengstlich/story/25785471|title=\u00abLieber bin ich frei als \u00e4ngstlich\u00bb|first=Christof|last=Gertsch|via=www.tagesanzeiger.ch}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/03/10/curdin-orlik-coming-out-gay-switzerland-swing-wrestling-queer-lgbt-sport/|title=Swiss wrestling champion Curdin Orlik just made history by coming out as gay|date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n** '''Diana Zurco''' became Argentina\u2019s first openly transgender newscaster.<ref>\ud83d\udd89{{Cite web|url=https://www.advocate.com/transgender/2020/3/23/meet-argentinas-first-transgender-newscaster-diana-zurco|title=Meet Argentina\u2019s First Transgender Newscaster, Diana Zurco|date=March 23, 2020|website=www.advocate.com}}</ref>\n** '''Sebastian Vega''' came out as gay, making him the first openly gay professional basketball player in Argentina.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.trust.org/item/20200319171432-yv79i/|title=Argentina's first openly gay basketball star on coming out|first=Thomson Reuters|last=Foundation|website=news.trust.org}}</ref>\n** '''Camila Prins''' became the first openly transgender woman to lead the drum section of a top samba school in the Carnival parade in Sao Paulo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/brazilian-transgender-dancer-shatters-carnival-parade-taboo-n1142461|title=Brazilian transgender dancer shatters Carnival parade taboo|website=www.nbcnews.com}}</ref>\n** The Philadelphia Police Academy graduated its first openly transgender officer, '''Benson Churgai'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inquirer.com/life/transgender-police-officer-training-academy-lgbtq-benson-churgai-20200228.html|title=Philadelphia Police Academy just graduated its first openly transgender officer|first=Brandon T.|last=Harden|}}</ref>\n** The Pfister Hotel named '''Nykoli Koslow''' as its first openly transgender Artist in Residence.<ref>\ud83d\udd89{{Cite web|url=https://onmilwaukee.com/ent/articles/pfister-artist-in-residence-2020.html|title=Pfister Hotel names Nykoli Koslow as its first transgender Artist in Residence|date=February 24, 2020}}</ref>\n** '''[[Chris Mosier]]'''  became the first openly transgender male athlete to ever compete in an Olympic trial alongside other men; however, he was unable to finish the race due to injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outsports.com/platform/amp/2020/1/27/21083208/chris-mosier-transgender-olympic-trials-tokyo-2020-race-walking |title=Chris Mosier makes history at 2020 Olympic trials, vows to race again |publisher=Outsports |date= |accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n** '''Megan Youngren''' became the first openly transgender athlete to compete at the Olympic marathon trials in U.S. history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/olympics/story/_/id/28810993/megan-youngren-becomes-first-openly-trans-athlete-compete-marathon-trials|title=Megan Youngren becomes first openly trans athlete to compete in marathon trials|date=March 1, 2020|website=ESPN.com}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Timeline of LGBT history]]\n* [[Timeline of LGBT history, 19th century]]\n* [[Timeline of LGBT history, 20th century]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{LGBT history}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Timeline of Lgbt History}}\n[[Category:LGBT timelines| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{very long|date=August 2015}}\n{{Globalize |date=September 2016 |discuss=Talk:Timeline of LGBT history#Globalize }}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n\nThe following is a '''timeline of lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender''' ('''[[LGBT]]''') history in the 21st century.\n\n==2000s==\n{{World homosexuality laws map|align=right|size=350px}}'''2001'''\n* '''Same-sex marriages laws''':\n** '''Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in the Netherlands|The Netherlands]] (with joint adoption)\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Germany|Germany]] (without adoption until Oct 2004, then with step-adoption only)\n** '''Passed''': [[Registered partnership in Finland|Finland]] (without joint adoption until May 2009, then with step-adoption)\n* '''Limited Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[De facto union in Portugal|Portugal]] (without joint adoption) (replaced with marriage in 2010)\n** '''Came into effect''': Swiss canton of [[Geneva]] (without joint adoption)\n* '''Anti-discrimination legislation''': US states of [[Rhode Island]] (private sector, gender identity) and [[Maryland]] (private sector, sexual orientation)\n* '''Equalization of age of consent''': [[LGBT rights in Albania|Albania]], [[LGBT rights in Estonia|Estonia]], [[LGBT rights in Liechtenstein|Liechtenstein]] and [[LGBT rights in the United Kingdom|United Kingdom]].\n* '''Repeal of Sodomy laws''': US state of [[Arizona]]\n* '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': the rest of the United Kingdom's territories{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}\n* '''Homosexuality no longer an illness''': [[Homosexuality in China|China]]\n* '''Marches and Prides''': Protesters disrupt the first Pride march in the [[LGBT rights in Serbia|Serbian]] capital city of [[Belgrade]]\n* The '''first memorial in the United States honoring LGBT veterans''' was dedicated in [[Desert Memorial Park]], Cathedral City, California.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nlgbtvm.org/Home_Page.html|title=National LGBT Veterans Memorial|work=nlgbtvm|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n* '''Helene Faasen and Anne-Marie Thus''', from the Netherlands, became the first two women to legally marry.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/world/worlds-first-legally-wed-lesbian-couple-celebrates-their-10th-wedding-anniversary/story-e6frfkyi-1226030866529|title=World's first legally wed lesbian couple celebrates their 10th wedding anniversary|work=NewsComAu|accessdate=6 October 2014|date=30 March 2011}}</ref>\n* '''[[Pink Triangle Park]]''' was dedicated; it is the first permanent, free-standing memorial in America dedicated to the thousands of [[Persecution of homosexuals in Nazi Germany and the Holocaust|persecuted homosexuals in Nazi Germany during the Holocaust]] of World War II.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ebar.com/news/article.php|title=Bay Area Reporter :: Article.php|website=The Bay Area Reporter / B.A.R. Inc.}}</ref><ref>Plaque which is part of the monument.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2003/06/27/EB291143.DTL |title=Park honors gay, lesbian Holocaust victims, '&#39;San Francisco Chronicle'&#39; June 27, 2003 |publisher=Sfgate.com |date=2003-06-27 |accessdate=2013-02-12}}</ref>\n\n'''2002'''\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': Canadian province of [[Civil unions in Quebec|Quebec]] (with joint adoption)\n** '''Came into effect''': [[Registered partnership in Finland|Finland]] (without joint adoption until May 2009, then with step-adoption)\n** '''Passed''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Argentina|Argentinian]] city of [[Buenos Aires]] (without joint adoption)\n* '''Limited Partnerships laws''':\n** '''Passed''': Swiss canton of [[Zurich]] (without joint adoption)\n* '''Same-sex couple adoption legalisation''': [[South Africa]] (joint and step adoption) and [[Sweden]] (joint and step adoption)\n* '''Anti-discrimination legislation''': US states of [[Alaska]] (public sector, sexual orientation) and [[New York (state)|New York]] (private sector, sexual orientation)\n** Canada's [[Northwest Territories]] updates human rights legislation to formally include sexual orientation, and is the first jurisdiction in Canada to ban discrimination based on [[Transgender rights in Canada|gender identity]]; they all would by 2017.\n* '''Equalization of age of consent''': [[LGBT rights in Austria|Austria]], [[LGBT rights in Bulgaria|Bulgaria]], [[LGBT rights in Cyprus|Cyprus]], [[LGBT rights in Hungary|Hungary]], [[LGBT rights in Moldova|Moldova]], [[LGBT rights in Romania|Romania]] and the Australian state of [[Western Australia]]\n* '''Repeal of Sodomy laws''': [[Romania]], [[Costa Rica]] and the US States of [[Arkansas]] and [[Massachusetts]]\n* '''Other''': openly gay Dutch politician [[Pim Fortuyn]] is assassinated by [[Volkert van der Graaf]]\n* '''[[Parents and Friends of Lesbians and Gays]]''' established its Transgender Network, also known as TNET, as its first official \"Special Affiliate,\" recognized with the same privileges and responsibilities as its regular chapters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.pflag.org/Page.aspx?pid=398 |title=PFLAG: Parents, Families, & Friends of Lesbians and Gays |publisher=community.pflag.org |date=9 April 2013 |accessdate=19 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120620050818/http://community.pflag.org/Page.aspx?pid=398 |archivedate=20 June 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* At the Reform seminary [[Hebrew Union College-Jewish Institute of Religion]] in New York, the Reform rabbi [[Margaret Wenig]] organized the '''first school-wide seminar at any rabbinical school which addressed the psychological, legal, and religious issues affecting people who are intersex or [[transsexual]].'''<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web|url=http://huc.edu/faculty/faculty/MargaretWenig.shtml |title=Rabbi Margaret Moers Wenig, D.D. |publisher=Hebrew Union College |accessdate=2013-07-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130623080230/http://huc.edu/faculty/faculty/MargaretWenig.shtml |archivedate=23 June 2013 }}</ref>\n'''2003'''\n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Belgium|Belgium]] (without joint adoption until Apr 2006) and the Canadian provinces of [[Same-sex marriage in Ontario|Ontario]] and [[Same-sex marriage in British Columbia|British Columbia]]\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Came into effect''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Argentina|Argentinian]] city of [[Buenos Aires]] (without joint adoption)\n** '''Passed:''': Australian state of [[Domestic partnership in Tasmania|Tasmania]] (step adoption only)\n* '''Limited Partnerships laws''':\n** '''Came into effect''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Austria|Austria]] (without joint adoption)(replaced with registered partnerships 2010) and [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Croatia|Croatia]] (without registration or adoption)\n* '''Anti-discrimination legislation''':[[Bulgaria]] ( all sectors, sexual orientation), [[United Kingdom]] (excluding religious organisations, sexual orientation), US states of [[Arizona]] (public sector, sexual orientation), [[Kentucky]] (public sector, sexual orientation and gender identity), [[Michigan]] (executive branch of the state government, sexual orientation), [[New Mexico]] (private sector, sexual orientation and gender identity) and [[Pennsylvania]] (public sector, gender identity)\n* '''End to ban on gay people in the military''': [[LGBT rights in Russia|Russia]]\n* '''Equalization of age of consent''': Australian state and territory (resp.) of [[LGBT rights in New South Wales|New South Wales]] and [[Northern Territory]]\n* '''Repeal of Sodomy laws''': [[Armenia]]\n* '''Repeal of the concept of [[Buggery]] in law''': [[United Kingdom]]\n* '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Iraq|Iraq]], [[LGBT rights in Armenia|Armenia]] and [[LGBT rights in the United States|United States]] [nationwide]\n* '''Recriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Belize|Belize]]\n* [[Section 28]] was repealed in [[England and Wales]] and [[Northern Ireland]]. \n* [[Gene Robinson]] became the first openly gay Bishop in the Episcopal church in the USA.\n*  '''[[Reuben Zellman]]''' became the first openly transgender person accepted to the [[Hebrew Union College-Jewish Institute of Religion]], where he was ordained in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forward.com/articles/14854/transgender-jews-now-out-of-closet-seeking-commun-/#ixzz25FOl5U4v |title=Transgender Jews Now Out of Closet, Seeking Communal Recognition \u2013 |publisher=Forward.com |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref><ref>[http://www.jewishmosaic.org/page/load_page/50] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070506220137/http://www.jewishmosaic.org/page/load_page/50|date=6 May 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bethelberkeley.org/aboutus/rabbi-zellman |title=Rabbi Zellman |publisher=bethelberkeley.org |accessdate=2013-10-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007023144/http://www.bethelberkeley.org/aboutus/rabbi-zellman |archive-date=7 October 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* In 2003, the '''[[Committee on Jewish Law and Standards]]''' approved a rabbinic ruling that concluded that [[sex reassignment surgery]] (SRS) is permissible as a treatment of [[gender dysphoria]], and that a transgender person's sex status under Jewish law is changed by SRS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishmosaic.org/page/file/17 |title=Status of Transsexuals |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721041507/http://www.jewishmosaic.org/page/file/17 |archivedate=21 July 2011 }}</ref>\n* '''Legal recognition of indeterminate gender''': [[Alex MacFarlane]] became the first person reported to obtain a birth certificate and passport, in [[Australia]], showing indeterminate gender.\n* In 2003 the Reform rabbi [[Margaret Wenig]] organized the '''first school-wide seminar at the [[Reconstructionist Rabbinical College]] which addressed the psychological, legal, and religious issues affecting people who are intersex or [[transsexual]].'''<ref name=\"autogenerated2\" />\n* [[Jennifer Finney Boylan]]'s autobiography, ''She's Not There: A Life in Two Genders'', was '''the first book by an openly [[transgender]] American to become a bestseller.'''<ref name=\"GLAAD bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.glaad.org/about/board/jenniferboylan |title=Professor Jennifer Finney Boylan (Maine) (May 2011 \u2013 Present) |publisher=GLAAD |accessdate=2012-12-26}}</ref>\n* '''''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]''''' showed girlfriends Willow Rosenberg and Tara Maclay in bed together, which though not a sex scene was considered the first scene of its kind for a broadcast network series.<ref name=\"nytimes1\">{{cite news|first=Maya |last=Salam |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/29/arts/television/lesbian-tv-shows.html |title=The Very (Very) Slow Rise of Lesbianism on TV - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date= |accessdate=2019-12-09}}</ref> \n* '''The first lesbian sex scene in broadcast TV history''' occurred, on ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Frost |first=Karen |url=https://www.afterellen.com/tv/474467-long-road-lesbian-sex-sensuality-network-tv#UjXTCyxhuYzGUkMG.99 |title=The Long Road to Lesbian Sex & Sensuality on Network TV |publisher=AfterEllen |date=2017-08-19 |accessdate=2019-06-03}}</ref>\n* '''[[Patrick Harvie]]''' became the first openly bisexual [[Member of the Scottish Parliament]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/17665293.30-years-of-stonewall-the-fight-for-lgbt-rights/ |title=30 years of Stonewall: The fight for LGBT rights |publisher=HeraldScotland |date= |accessdate=2019-06-04}}</ref>\n'''2004'''\n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': Canadian provinces of [[Same-sex marriage in Manitoba|Manitoba]] (with adoption), [[Same-sex marriage in Newfoundland and Labrador|Newfoundland and Labrador]], [[Same-sex marriage in Nova Scotia|Nova Scotia]], [[Same-sex marriage in Quebec|Quebec]] (with adoption), and [[Same-sex marriage in Saskatchewan|Saskatchewan]], and the Canadian territory of [[Same-sex marriage in Yukon|Yukon]], US State of [[Same-sex marriage in Massachusetts|Massachusetts]]\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': Brazilian State of [[Rio Grande do Sul]], [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Luxembourg|Luxembourg]] (without joint adoption) and US state of [[Domestic partnership in Maine|Maine]]\n** '''Came into effect:''': Australian state of [[Tasmania]] (step adoption only)\n** '''Passed''': [[civil unions in New Zealand|New Zealand]] (without joint adoption)\n* '''Limited Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in New Jersey|New Jersey]]\n* '''Same-sex couple adoption legalisation''': [[Germany]] (Step Adoption)\n* '''Banning of Same-sex marriage''': [[Australia]], US states of [[Mississippi]], [[Missouri]], [[Montana]], [[Oregon]] and [[Utah]]\n* '''Banning of Same-sex marriage and civil unions''': US states of [[Arkansas]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[Kentucky]], [[Louisiana]], [[Michigan]], [[North Dakota]], [[Ohio]], [[Oklahoma]], [[Virginia]] and [[Wisconsin]]\n* '''Anti-discrimination legislation''': [[Portugal]], US States of [[Indiana]] (public sector, gender identity), [[Louisiana]] (public sector, sexual orientation) and [[Maine]]\n* '''Equalization of age of consent''': [[Lithuania]]\n* '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Cape Verde|Cape Verde]], [[LGBT rights in the Marshall Islands|Marshall Islands]] and [[LGBT rights in San Marino|San Marino]]\n* ''[[The L Word]]'' featured '''television\u2019s first ensemble cast of lesbian characters.'''<ref name=\"nytimes1\"/>\n* The first all-transgender performance of the '''[[Vagina Monologues]]''' was held. The monologues were read by eighteen notable transgender women, and a new monologue revolving around the experiences and struggles of transgender women was included.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baltimoregaylife.com/item/451-vagina-monologues |title=\u2018V\u2019 is for Victory, Valentine and Vagina |publisher=Baltimore Gay Life |date=2 February 2012 |accessdate=15 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120806183929/http://www.baltimoregaylife.com/item/451-vagina-monologues |archivedate=6 August 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* '''[[Del Martin and Phyllis Lyon]]''' became the first same-sex couple to be legally married in the United States,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2004/02/12/GAYMARRIAGE.TMP |work=The San Francisco Chronicle |title=Lesbian couple wedded at SF City Hall Women had been together for five decades |date=13 February 2004 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080521071039/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=%2Fc%2Fa%2F2004%2F02%2F12%2FGAYMARRIAGE.TMP |archivedate=21 May 2008 |df=dmy }}</ref> when San Francisco mayor Gavin Newsom allowed city hall to grant marriage licenses to same-sex couples.<ref>[http://www.newsweek.com/2009/01/16/hoping-that-left-is-right.html SF Mayor Gavin Newsom Risks Career on Gay Marriage]. Newsweek (17 January 2009). Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> However, all same-sex marriages done in 2004 in California were annulled.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/US/12/19/california.proposition/index.html|work=CNN|title=Prop 8 proponents seek to nullify same-sex marriages|date=19 December 2008}}</ref> After the California Supreme Court decision in 2008 that granted same-sex couples in California the right to marry, Del Martin and Phyllis Lyon remarried, and were again the first same-sex couple in the state to marry.<ref>{{cite web |title=First couple in California's 2004 marriages will say vows again on Monday |url=http://www.gaypeopleschronicle.com/stories08/june/0613082.htm |accessdate=2 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/16/us/16cnd-weddings.html?hp|title=Gay Marriages Begin in California|first=Jesse|last=McKinley|date=16 June 2008|work=The New York Times}}</ref> Later in 2008 Prop 8 banned same-sex marriage in California,<ref>[http://www.tuftsdaily.com/editorial-maine-was-asking-the-wrong-people-1.2058087#3 Editorial | Maine was asking the wrong people] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609211433/http://www.tuftsdaily.com/editorial-maine-was-asking-the-wrong-people-1.2058087 |date= 9 June 2011 }}. Tuftsdaily.com (9 November 2009). Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> but the marriages that occurred between the California Supreme Court decision legalizing same-sex marriage and the approval of Prop 8 are still considered valid, including the marriage of Del Martin and Phyllis Lyon.<ref>[http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Justice/2009/0527/p02s01-usju.html California's top court upholds Prop. 8 ban on same-sex marriage]. CSMonitor.com (27 May 2009). Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref> However, Del Martin died in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2008-08-28/news/17122864_1_same-sex-marriage-marriage-licenses-phyllis-lyon |work=The San Francisco Chronicle |first=Rachel |last=Gordon |title=Same-sex Marriage Timeline |date=28 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111054704/http://articles.sfgate.com/2008-08-28/news/17122864_1_same-sex-marriage-marriage-licenses-phyllis-lyon |archivedate=11 January 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* '''[[James McGreevey]]''', then governor of New Jersey, came out as gay, thus becoming the first openly gay state governor in United States history.<ref name=\"aeispeakers.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aeispeakers.com/print.php?SpeakerID=1249 |title=James McGreevey - AEI Speakers Bureau |publisher=Aeispeakers.com |accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref> He resigned soon after.<ref name=\"aeispeakers.com\" />\n* '''Bisi Alimi''' became the first Nigerian to declare his homosexuality on television.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://amanpour.blogs.cnn.com/2014/01/16/meet-the-first-gay-nigerian-to-come-out-on-tv/ | work=CNN | title=Meet the first gay Nigerian to come out on TV | date=16 January 2014}}</ref>\n* '''Luna''', by [[Julie Anne Peters]], was published, and was the first young-adult novel with a transgender character to be released by a mainstream publisher.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://mobile.nytimes.com/2015/06/07/business/media/transgender-childrens-books-fill-a-void-and-break-a-taboo.html?referrer=&_r=0 | work=The New York Times | first=Alexandra | last=Alter | date=7 June 2015 | title=Transgender Children's Books Fill a Void and Break a Taboo}}</ref>\n* The first Trans pride march was held in San Francisco in 2004.<ref name=\"transmarch-2012\">{{cite web|url=http://www.transmarch.org/about |title=About the San Francisco Trans March &#124; San Francisco Trans March |publisher=Transmarch.org |date=2004-06-25 |accessdate=2012-11-06}}</ref>\n* '''[[Karamo Brown]]''' started his career in television on the [[MTV]] reality series ''[[The Real World: Philadelphia]]'' in 2004, becoming the first out gay black man on reality TV.<ref name=Plus>{{Cite news|author=Anderson-Minshall, Jacob|url=https://www.hivplusmag.com/entertainment/2017/7/24/futures-so-bright-hes-got-unshade|title=How Did Karamo Brown find his way back to Hollywood?|date=July 24, 2017|access-date=September 4, 2018|language=en|publisher=Plus}}</ref>\n'''2005'''\n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Canada|Canada]] [nationwide], [[Same-sex marriage in Spain|Spain]] (with joint adoption)\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passes and Came into effect''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Andorra|Andorra]], [[United Kingdom]] (without joint adoption (England and Wales) until December 2005,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ukgaynews.org.uk/Archive/2005dec/3001.html |title=New Adoption Law Gives Gay Couples Joint Rights |work=UK Gay News |date=30 December 2005 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120919092646/http://www.ukgaynews.org.uk/Archive/2005dec/3001.htm |archivedate=19 September 2012 |url-status=dead |accessdate=4 September 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> without joint adoption (Scotland) until Sep 2009, without joint adoption (Northern Ireland)) and US state of [[Same-sex marriage in Connecticut|Connecticut]]\n** '''Came into effect''': [[civil unions in New Zealand|New Zealand]] (without joint adoption) and US state of [[Domestic partnership in California|California]]\n** '''Passed''': [[Registered partnership in Switzerland|Switzerland]] (without adoption) and [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Slovenia|Slovenia]]\n* '''Same-sex couple adoption legalisation''': UK Subdivisions of [[England]] and [[Wales]]\n* '''Banning of Same-sex marriage''': [[Same-sex marriage in Latvia|Latvia]], [[Uganda]] and [[Honduras]]\n* '''Banning of Same-sex marriage and civil unions''': US states of [[Kansas]] and [[Texas]]\n* '''Anti-discrimination legislation''': US States of [[Illinois]] (private sector, sexual orientation and gender identity) and [[Maine]] (private sector, sexual orientation and gender identity){{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}\n* '''Repeal of Sodomy laws''': [[LGBT rights in Puerto Rico|Puerto Rico]]\n* Two gay male teenagers, [[Mahmoud Asgari and Ayaz Marhoni]], are executed in [[Iran]], \n* [[Andr\u00e9 Boisclair]] is chosen leader of the [[Parti Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois]], becoming the first openly gay man elected as the leader of a major political party in North America. \n* [[Pine City, Minnesota]] holds [[East-Central Minnesota Pride]], the first rural LGBT pride in North America.\n* The [[Roman Catholic Church]] issues an instruction prohibiting any individuals who \"present deep-seated homosexual tendencies or support the so-called 'gay culture'\" from joining the priesthood.<ref name=\"seminarydoc\">''[https://www.vatican.va/roman_curia/congregations/ccatheduc/documents/rc_con_ccatheduc_doc_20051104_istruzione_en.html Instruction Concerning the Criteria for the Discernment of Vocations with regard to Persons with Homosexual Tendencies in view of their Admission to the Seminary and to Holy Orders] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080225072042/https://www.vatican.va/roman_curia/congregations/ccatheduc/documents/rc_con_ccatheduc_doc_20051104_istruzione_en.html |date=25 February 2008 }}'', (Vatican Website, 4 November 2005)</ref>\n* '''The Simpsons''' became the first cartoon series to dedicate an entire episode to the topic of same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://news.avclub.com/new-study-suggests-the-simpsons-likes-its-homosexuals-f-1798239020  | work=The AV Club | first=Sean | last=O'Neal | title=New study suggests The Simpsons likes its homosexuals flaming, effecting social change| date=2 July 2013}}</ref>\n* The '''first European Transgender Council Meeting''' was held in Vienna.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tgeu.net/|title=TransGender Europe - TGEU.net|publisher=|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n* '''Publication of the [[Intersex#San Francisco Human Rights Investigation|first human rights report on the situation]] of intersex people,''' by the Human Rights Commission of the City and County of San Francisco.\n* Eli Cohen became '''the first openly gay man to be ordained a rabbi by the Jewish Renewal Movement.'''<ref>{{cite web|last=Scupham |first=Tony |url=http://queerstoryfiles.blogspot.com/2016/04/a-feast-of-firsts-for-passover.html |title=The Queerstory Files: A Feast of Firsts for Passover |publisher=Queerstoryfiles.blogspot.com |date=2016-04-26 |accessdate=2017-06-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://alephstudents.homestead.com/elicohen.html |title=ALEPH Rabbinic Program SENIORS |publisher=Alephstudents.homestead.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-29}}</ref>\n* [[Andrew Goldstein]] was '''the first American male team-sport professional athlete to be openly gay during his playing career.'''<ref name=mll>{{cite news|last1=Zeigler|first1=Cyd|title=Andrew Goldstein Openly Tending Goal For Major League Lacrosse|url=https://www.outsports.com/2013/2/21/4015350/andrew-goldstein-openly-tending-goal-for-major-league-lacrosse|accessdate=2 December 2017|work=Outsports|date=18 June 2006}}</ref> He came out publicly in 2003 and was drafted by his hometown team, the [[Boston Cannons]] of [[Major League Lacrosse]], in 2005. Goldstein played [[goaltender (lacrosse)|goaltender]] for the [[Long Island Lizards]] from 2005 to 2007, appearing in two games in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|title=Andrew Goldstein - MLL|url=http://pointstreak.com/prostats/playerpage.html?playerid=797170&seasonid=1617|website=Pointstreak.com|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref>\n'''2006'''\n[[File:Kim Coco Iwamoto.jpg|upright|thumb|In 2006 [[Kim Coco Iwamoto]] became the first transgender official to win statewide office in Hawaii.]] \n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in South Africa|South Africa]] (with joint adoption)\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Registered partnership in the Czech Republic|Czech Republic]] (without joint adoption)\n** '''Came into effect''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Slovenia|Slovenia]]\n** '''Passed''': Mexican City of [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Mexico|Mexico City]] and US state of [[Recognition of same-sex unions in New Jersey|New Jersey]]\n* '''Limited Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed''': Australian State of [[LGBT rights in South Australia|South Australia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-3200.html|title=South Australia gays get new rights|work=PinkNews.co.uk|accessdate=6 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveu