an Pride|Eastern European Pride]] is held in [[Zagreb]], Croatia\n* Springfield, [[Missouri]] repeals gay soliciting laws.<ref>[http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-13978.html/ Missouri city set to remove anti-gay law] Pink News, 8 September 2009</ref> \n* [[United States Senate]] fails to pass the [[Federal Marriage Amendment]]. \n* The [[2006 World Outgames#International Conference on LGBT Human Rights|International Conference on LGBT Human Rights]] is held in [[Montreal]].\n* The original [[Yogyakarta Principles]] is adopted in [[Yogyakarta]] of Indonesia.\n* Section 28 \"successfully repealed\" in Isle of Man<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stonewall.org.uk/help-advice/whats-my-area|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061105163534/http://www.stonewall.org.uk/information_bank/history__lesbian__gay/89.asp|url-status=dead|title=What's In My Area?|date=6 May 2015|archivedate=5 November 2006|website=Stonewall}}</ref> \n* '''[[Chaya Gusfield]]''' and '''[[Rabbi Lori Klein]]''', both ordained in America, became the first openly lesbian rabbis ordained by the Jewish Renewal movement. Conservative Judaism decided to allow openly lesbian rabbis and cantors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewcy.com/religion-and-beliefs/conservative_judaism_puts_its_money_where_its_mouth_is |title=Conservative Judaism Walks the Walk |publisher=Jewcy.com |accessdate=2014-05-18}}</ref> '''[[Elliot Kukla]]''', who came out as transgender six months before his ordination in 2006, was the first openly transgender person to be ordained by the Hebrew Union College-Jewish Institute of Religion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forward.com/articles/14854/transgender-jews-now-out-of-closet-seeking-commun-/ |title=Transgender Jews Now Out of Closet, Seeking Communal Recognition \u2013 |publisher=Forward.com |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n* '''State Rep. Patricia Todd''', D-Birmingham, became Alabama's first openly gay public official when she was elected in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.al.com/breaking/2013/06/patricia_todd_alabamas_first_o.html |title=Patricia Todd, Alabama's first openly gay state legislator, coming to Huntsville to talk Supreme Court gay marriage rulings &#124; al.com |publisher=Blog.al.com |date=2013-06-28 |accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref>\n* '''[[Kim Coco Iwamoto]]''' became the first transgender official to win statewide office in Hawaii.\n* '''[[Bern\u00e1rd J. Lynch|Bernard Lynch]]''' became the first Catholic priest in the world to undertake a civil partnership in 2006 in the Republic of Ireland (he had previously had his relationship blessed in a ceremony in 1998 by an American Cistercian monk<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/father-bernard-lynch-the-vatican-has-told-them-to-get-rid-of-me-7619004.html|title=Father Bernard Lynch: 'The Vatican has told them to get rid of me'|date=8 April 2012|publisher=|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>). He was subsequently expelled from his religious order in 2011, and went on to legally wed his husband in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/social-affairs/religion-and-beliefs/married-gay-priest-says-catholic-church-has-got-god-s-message-very-wrong-1.2958118|title=Married gay priest says Catholic Church has got God's message 'very wrong'|publisher=|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n'''2007'''\n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Recognition''': [[Same-sex marriage in Aruba, Cura\u00e7ao and Sint Maarten|Aruba, Cura\u00e7ao and Sint Maarten]] (Recognition of Dutch same-sex marriages only)\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': Mexican state of [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Mexico|Coahuila]]\n** '''Came into effect''': Mexican City of [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Mexico|Mexico City]], [[Registered partnership in Switzerland|Switzerland]] (without adoption) and US state of [[Recognition of same-sex unions in New Jersey|New Jersey]]\n** '''Passed''': [[Hungary]] (with adoption), US state of [[Same-sex marriage in New Hampshire|New Hampshire]] and [[Same-sex marriage in Uruguay|Uruguay]] (without adoption until Sep 2008)\n* '''Limited Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': US state of [[Domestic partnership in Washington|Washington]] and [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Colombia|Colombia]]\n** '''Came into effect''': Australian state of [[LGBT rights in South Australia|South Australia]] and US state of [[Domestic partnership in Oregon|Oregon]]\n* '''Anti-discrimination legislation''': [[Equality Act (Sexual Orientation) Regulations|United Kingdom]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts2006/20060003.htm |title=Equality Act 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071119183746/http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts2006/20060003.htm |archivedate=19 November 2007 }}</ref> (sexual orientation) and US states of [[LGBT rights in the United States|Colorado]] (private sector, sexual orientation and gender identity), [[LGBT rights in the United States|Iowa]] (private sector, sexual orientation and gender identity), [[LGBT rights in the United States|Kansas]] (public sector, sexual orientation and gender identity), [[LGBT rights in the United States|Michigan]] (public sector, gender identity), [[LGBT rights in Ohio|Ohio]] (public sector, sexual orientation and gender identity), [[LGBT rights in the United States|Oregon]] (private sector, sexual orientation and gender identity) and [[LGBT rights in the United States|Vermont]] (private sector, gender identity)\n* '''Equalization of age of consent''': [[LGBT rights in Portugal|Portugal]], [[LGBT rights in South Africa|South Africa]], UK territory of [[Jersey]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/jersey/5151592.stm|title=BBC: State votes for consent age drop|publisher=|accessdate=6 October 2014|work=BBC News|date=5 July 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jerseylaw.je/Law/Display.aspx?url=LawsInForce/htm/lawfiles/2007/L-02-2007.htm|archive