nsgender character in prime time.<ref name=\"October Surprises\" /><ref name=\"Advocate 2009-03\" /><ref name=\"Metro UK 2008-03-13\" />\n* On 29 November, the first foreign gay wedding was held in [[Hanoi]], '''[[Vietnam]]''' between a Japanese and an Irish national. The wedding raised much attention in the gay and lesbian community in Vietnam.<ref name=\"vietbao.vn\">{{cite web |url=http://vietbao.vn/The-gioi-giai-tri/Le-ket-hon-dong-gioi-tai-Ha-Noi/50795684/407/ |title=L\u1ec5 k\u1ebft h\u00f4n \u0111\u1ed3ng gi\u1edbi t\u1ea1i H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i |publisher=Vietbao.vn |accessdate=4 August 2009 |language=vi |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080219070103/http://vietbao.vn/The-gioi-giai-tri/Le-ket-hon-dong-gioi-tai-Ha-Noi/50795684/407/ |archive-date=19 February 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* '''[[Jalda Rebling]]''', a German woman born in the Netherlands, became the first openly lesbian cantor ordained by the Jewish Renewal movement.<ref name=\"jta\">{{cite news |last=Axelrod |first=Toby |url=http://www.jta.org/news/article/1999/11/30/14879/Newfemalecantorin |title=New Renewal cantor looks ahead |publisher=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]] |date=1999-11-30 |accessdate=2012-04-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130415065937/http://www.jta.org/news/article/1999/11/30/14879/Newfemalecantorin |archivedate=15 April 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* Rabbi '''[[Toba Spitzer]]''' became the first openly lesbian or gay person to head a [[rabbi|rabbinical assembly]] when she was elected president of the Reconstructionist Rabbinical Assembly at the group's annual convention, held in [[Scottsdale, Arizona]].<ref name=\"radin\">{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/news/globe/city_region/breaking_news/2007/03/first_openly_ga.html |title=First openly gay rabbi elected leader |first=Charles A. |last=Radin |newspaper=The Boston Globe\n|date=13 March 2007}}</ref>\n* '''[[Joy Ladin]]''' became the first openly transgender professor at an Orthodox institution (Stern College for Women of [[Yeshiva University]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Through-Door-Life-Journey-Autobiog/dp/0299287300/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1346529351&sr=1-1&keywords=through+the+door+of+life+a+jewish+journey+between+genders |title=Through the Door of Life: A Jewish Journey between Genders (Living Out: Gay and Lesbian Autobiog): Joy Ladin: 9780299287306: Amazon.com: Books |publisher=Amazon.com |date=2012-03-15 |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sjjcc.org/arts/performance-guest-speakers/ |title=Performance & Guest Speakers |publisher=Sjjcc.org |accessdate=2013-10-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314060544/http://www.sjjcc.org/arts/performance-guest-speakers/ |archivedate=14 March 2013 }}</ref>\n* '''Amaranta G\u00f3mez Regalado''' (for [[M\u00e9xico Posible]]) became the first transsexual person to appear in the Mexican Congress.\n* '''[[Ellen DeGeneres]]''' became the first open lesbian to host the Academy Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://famousdaily.com/history/ellen-degeneres-hosts-academy-awards.html |title=Ellen DeGeneres hosts the 79th Academy Awards as the first openly gay woman |publisher=Famousdaily.com |date=2012-02-25 |accessdate=2012-11-06}}</ref> \n* Ventura Place in [[Studio City]] was renamed Dr. '''[[Betty Berzon]]''' Place in her honor, making it the first street ever officially dedicated to a known lesbian in California.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wehonews.com/z/wehonews/betty-berzon-place-unveiled/ |title=WeHo News - News |accessdate=14 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141222040635/http://www.wehonews.com/z/wehonews/betty-berzon-place-unveiled/ |archivedate=22 December 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Theresa Sparks]] was elected president of the [[San Francisco Police Commission]] by a single vote, making her the first openly transgender person ever to be elected president of any San Francisco commission, as well as San Francisco's highest ranking openly transgender official.<ref name=\"Renne quits\">Selna, Robert; Sward, Susan; Vega, Cecilia M. [http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2007/05/11/BAG3TPP7881.DTL Renne Quits Police Commission], San Francisco Chronicle (11 May 2007), pp. B-9. Retrieved on 13 May 2007.</ref><ref>[http://www.kcbs.com/pages/440257.php?contentType=4&contentId=486609 SF Police Commission Makes History], [[KCBS (AM)|KCBS]] (10 May 2007). Retrieved on 13 May 2007.  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070529044945/http://www.kcbs.com/pages/440257.php?contentType=4&contentId=486609 |date=29 May 2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"Sparks Is First Trans\">McMillan, Dennis. [http://www.sfbaytimes.com/index.php?sec=article&article_id=6411 Sparks Is First Trans Person to Lead Major Commission] [[San Francisco Bay Times]] (17 May 2007). Retrieved on 15 October 2007.</ref>\n'''2008'''\n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': US states of [[Same-sex marriage in California|California]] (May\u2013Nov 2008), [[Same-sex marriage in Connecticut|Connecticut]] and [[Same-sex marriage under United States tribal jurisdictions#Mashantucket Pequot|Mashantucket Pequot]]\n** '''Passed''': [[Same-sex marriage in Norway|Norway]] (with joint adoption)\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': The Australian [[Recognition of same-sex unions in the Australian Capital Territory|Capital Territory]], [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Ecuador|Ecuador]] (without joint adoption), US state of [[Domestic partnership in Washington|Washington]] (expansion of previous legislation)\n** '''Came into effect''': US state of [[Same-sex marriage in New Hampshire|New Hampshire]] and [[Same-sex marriage in Uruguay|Uruguay]] (without joint adoption until Sep 2008)\n* '''Limited Partnership laws''':\n** '''Came into effect''': Australian state of [[LGBT rights in Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] and US state of [[Domestic partnership in Oregon|Oregon]]\n* '''Banning of Same-sex marriage''': US states of [[Same-sex marriage legislation in the United States|Arizona]] and [[Same-sex marriage in California|California]]\n* '''Banning of Same-sex marriage and civil unions''': US state of [[Same-sex marriage legislation in the United States|Florida]]\n* '''Same-sex couple adoption legalisation''': [[Same-sex marriage in Uruguay|Uruguay]]\n* '''Banning of Same-sex adoption''': [[Arkansas Proposed Initiative Act No. 1|Arkansas]] (struck down by the Arkansas Supreme Court in 2011)\n* '''Anti-discrimination legislation''': California{{Citation needed|date=May 2010}}\n* '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Nicaragua|Nicaragua]] and [[LGBT rights in Panama|Panama]]\n* '''Marches and Prides''': the first ever gay pride parade in [[Bulgaria]]\n* Kosovo declares itself to be an independent country with a new constitution that includes mention of \"sexual orientation\", the first of its kind in Eastern Europe{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}} \n* The first two same-sex civil marriages (two men and two women) take place in Greece on the island of [[Tilos]]; the supreme court prosecutor and the minister of Justice claim the marriages are null and void.\n* Portland voters elect openly gay [[Sam Adams (Oregon politician)]] mayor\n* '''[[Annise Parker]]''' was elected as the first openly gay or lesbian mayor of Houston, Texas.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2009-12-14/news/17942843_1_openly-gay-mayor-gay-rights-activists-annise-parker|title=Texas-sized first: Newly-elected Annise Parker hailed for being first openly gay mayor of Houston|date=14 December 2009|work=Daily News|location=New York}}</ref>\n* '''[[Kate Brown]]''' was elected as the [[Oregon Secretary of State]] in the [[2008 Oregon state elections|2008 elections]], becoming America's first openly bisexual statewide officeholder.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.portlandmercury.com/portland/walking-bi/Content?oid=2610445|title=Walking Bi &#124; Queer|last=Ferguson|first=Courtney|newspaper=Portland Mercury|accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n* Silverton, Oregon elected '''[[Stu Rasmussen]]''' as the first openly transgender mayor in America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sturasmussen.com/realityCheck.htm |title=Stu Rasmussen for Mayor - Reality Check |publisher=Sturasmussen.com |accessdate=15 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120420133725/http://www.sturasmussen.com/realityCheck.htm |archivedate=20 April 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-election-diary-the-sex-change-we-can-all-believe-in-1003960.html |title=US election diary: The sex change we can all believe in - Americas - World |newspaper=The Independent |date=9 November 2008 |accessdate=15 May 2012 |location=London}}</ref>\n* '''[[Angie Zapata]]''', a transgender woman, was murdered in [[Greeley, Colorado]]. Allen Andrade was convicted of [[first-degree murder]] and committing a [[bias-motivated crime]], because he killed her after he learned that she was [[transgender]]. This case was the first in the nation to get a conviction for a [[hate crime]] involving a transgender victim.<ref name=\"spellman2009\">{{cite news |first=Jim |last=Spellman |title=Transgender murder, hate crime conviction a first |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2009/CRIME/04/22/transgender.slaying.trial/ |publisher=CNN |date=22 April 2009 |accessdate=}}</ref> Angie Zapata's story and murder were featured on [[Univision]]'s \"[[Aqu\u00ed y Ahora (TV series)|Aqui y Ahora]]\" television show on 1 November 2009.\n* The first ever U.S. Congressional hearing on discrimination against transgender people in the workplace was held, by the House Subcommittee on Health, Employment, Labor, and Pensions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.civilrights.org/lgbt/resources/transgender-hearing.html |title=House Subcommittee Holds First Hearing on Transgender Discrimination - The Leadership Conference on Civil and Human Rights |publisher=Civilrights.org |date=7 February 2008 |accessdate=15 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120720225646/http://www.civilrights.org/lgbt/resources/transgender-hearing.html |archivedate=20 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''[[Rachel Maddow]]''' became the first openly gay or lesbian anchor of a major prime-time news program in the United States when she began hosting ''[[The Rachel Maddow Show (TV series)|The Rachel Maddow Show]]'' on U.S. cable network [[MSNBC]].<ref>[http://www.lesbiatopia.com/2008/09/congrats-to-rachel-maddow-knock-em-dead.html Congrats to Rachel Maddow; Knock 'em Dead Tonight!] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091107213523/http://www.lesbiatopia.com/2008/09/congrats-to-rachel-maddow-knock-em-dead.html |date=7 November 2009 }} Lesbiatopia, 8 September 2008</ref>\n'''2009'''\n[[File:Johanna sigurdardottir official portrait.jpg|upright|thumb|[[J\u00f3hanna Sigur\u00f0ard\u00f3ttir]] became the [[Prime Minister]] of [[Iceland]] in 2009, and thus became the first openly gay [[head of government]] in modern times.]] \n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Sweden|Sweden]]<ref>[http://www.365gay.com/news/sweden-oks-gay-marriage Sweden oks gay marriage] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090403065011/http://www.365gay.com/news/sweden-oks-gay-marriage/ |date=3 April 2009 }} 365GAY, 1 April 2009</ref> (with joint adoption), US states of [[Same-sex marriage in Iowa|Iowa]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.desmoinesregister.com/article/20090403/NEWS/90403010 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120629165642/http://www.desmoinesregister.com/article/20090403/NEWS/90403010 |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 June 2012 |title=Unanimous ruling: Iowa marriage no longer limited to one man, one woman |newspaper=Des Moines Register |accessdate=7 May 2009 |first1=Jeff |last1=Eckhoff |first2=Grant |last2=Schulte |lastauthoramp=yes |date=3 April 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and [[Same-sex marriage in Vermont|Vermont]]<ref>[https://archive.is/20120728180414/http://www.burlingtonfreepress.com/article/20090407/NEWS03/100120038/Vermont-legalizes-gay-marriage Vermont legalizes gay marriage] The Burlington Free Press, 7 April 2009</ref>\n** '''Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Norway|Norway]] (with joint adoption) and the [[Same-sex marriage in the Coquille Indian Tribe|Coquille Indian Tribe]]<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2008-08-23/news/17125334_1_same-sex-marriage-gay-marriage-tribal | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | title=Same-sex marriage opponents' ranks dwindle | date=2008-08-23}}</ref>  In 2009 Kitzen and Jeni Branting married in the Coquille Indian tribe's Coos Bay plankhouse, a 3-year-old meeting hall built in traditional Coquille style with cedar plank walls. They were the first same-sex couple to have their marriage recognized by the tribe, of which Kitzen was a member.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oregonfaithreport.com/2009/05/indian-gay-marriage-law-takes-effect-in-oregon/ |title=Indian gay marriage law takes effect in Oregon |publisher=Oregon Faith Report |date=2009-05-27 |accessdate=2012-11-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pewforum.org/Religion-News/Indian-gay-marriage-law-takes-effect-in-Oregon.aspx |title=Indian gay marriage law takes effect in Oregon |publisher=Pew Forum |date=2009-05-26 |accessdate=2012-11-06}}</ref>\n** '''Passed''':  Mexican City of [[Same-sex marriage in Mexico City|Mexico City]] (with joint adoption), US states and districts of [[Same-sex marriage in New Hampshire|New Hampshire]] (step adoption only), [[Same-sex marriage in Maine|Maine]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.boston.com/news/local/breaking_news/2009/05/gay_marriage_la.html |work=The Boston Globe |title=Gay marriage law signed in Maine, advances in N.H |date=6 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090510085213/http://www.boston.com/news/local/breaking_news/2009/05/gay_marriage_la.html |archivedate=10 May 2009 }}</ref> (never came into effect), [[Same-sex marriage in the District of Columbia|Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=\"Hopkins2009\">{{cite news |title=Catania: Gay Marriage Bill Will Debut Tuesday |last=Hopkins |first=Christopher Dean |date=4 October 2009 |newspaper=The Washington Post |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/dc/2009/10/catania_gay_marriage_bill_will.html}}</ref>\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Hungary|Hungary]] (without joint adoption), [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Colombia|Colombia]]  (expansion of previous rights without joint adoption), US states of [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Nevada|Nevada]] and [[Domestic partnership in Washington|Washington]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apps.leg.wa.gov/billinfo/summary.aspx?bill=5688&year=2009 |title=SB 5688&nbsp;\u2013 2009\u201310&nbsp;\u2013 Expanding the rights and responsibilities of state registered domestic partners. |publisher=Washington State Legislature |accessdate=4 August 2009}}</ref> (expansion of previous rights)\n** '''Passed''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Austria|Austria]] (without joint adoption)\n* '''Limited Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and Came into effect''': US states of [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Colorado|Colorado]] and [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Wisconsin|Wisconsin]]\n* '''Same-sex couple adoption legalisation''': [[LGBT rights in Finland|Finland]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-12468.html |title=Finland allows gay couples to adopt partner's children |newspaper=Pink News |date=24 February 2008 |accessdate=18 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5jitOngc7?url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-12468.html |archivedate=12 September 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> (step adoption), UK Subdivision of [[Scotland]]\n* '''Banning of Same-sex marriage''': [[Same-sex marriage in Maine|Maine]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Mainers vote down gay marriage law |first=Susan M. |last=Cover |newspaper=[[Portland Press Herald]] |date=4 November 2009 |url=http://pressherald.mainetoday.com/story.php?id=293976&ac=PHnws |accessdate=4 November 2009 |quote=The measure is repealed in a close vote, 53\u201347 percent |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100206142719/http://pressherald.mainetoday.com/story.php?id=293976&ac=PHnws |archivedate=6 February 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* '''Anti-discrimination legislation''': [[LGBT rights in Serbia|Serbia]] and US state of [[LGBT rights in Delaware|Delaware]] (private sector, sexual orientation), USA [[Matthew Shepard Act]] (hate crimes). Canadian province [[Alberta]] adds \"sexual orientation\" to human rights legislation\u2014the last jurisdiction in Canada to do so''.''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.assembly.ab.ca/net/index.aspx?p=bills_status&selectbill=044|title=Bill 44: Human Rights, Citizenship and Multiculturalism Amendment Act, 2009 (Blackett)|date=26 May 2009|publisher=Legislative Assembly of Alberta|accessdate=4 August 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090508044617/http://www.assembly.ab.ca/net/index.aspx?p=bills_status&selectbill=044|archivedate=8 May 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* '''End to ban on gay people in the military''': [[LGBT rights in Argentina|Argentina]], [[LGBT rights in the Philippines|Philippines]] and [[LGBT rights in Uruguay|Uruguay]]\n* The '''[[International Transgender Day of Visibility]]''' was founded by Michigan-based transgender activist<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thespec.com/opinion-story/4432181-a-time-to-celebrate/|title=A time to celebrate|date=27 March 2014|newspaper=The Hamilton Spectator|accessdate=31 March 2014}}</ref> Rachel Crandall in 2009<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pridesource.com/article.html?article=34351|title=Transgender Day of Visibility plans erupt locally, nationwide|last=Carreras|first=Jessica|publisher=PrideSource|accessdate=3 April 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130327152446/http://www.pridesource.com/article.html?article=34351|archivedate=27 March 2013|df=dmy}}</ref> as a reaction to the lack of [[LGBT]] holidays celebrating transgender people, citing the frustration that the only well-known transgender-centered holiday was the [[Transgender Day of Remembrance]] which mourned the loss of transgender people to hate crimes, but did not acknowledge and celebrate living members of the transgender community.\n* '''Politics:''' \n** Iceland elects the first openly gay [[head of government]] in the world, [[J\u00f3hanna Sigur\u00f0ard\u00f3ttir]]<ref name=\"time\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1875032,00.html|title=Iceland Picks the World's First Openly Gay PM|first=Jonas|last=Moody|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=30 January 2009|accessdate=31 January 2009}}</ref>\n** [[Annise Parker]] is elected mayor of [[Houston]], [[Texas]], which becomes the largest city in the United States with an openly gay mayor.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/chronicle/6767658.html|title=Houston makes its choice; Parker makes history|date=15 December 2009|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|accessdate=18 January 2010}}</ref>\n** '''Diego Sanchez''' became the first openly transgender person to work on [[Capitol Hill]]; he was hired as a legislative assistant for [[Barney Frank]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edgeboston.com/index.php?ch=news&sc=&sc3=&id=84890|title=HRC Applauds Naming of Diego Sanchez to Key Legislative Staff Position for Chairman Barney Frank|last=Lavers|first=Michael K.|date=18 December 2008|publisher=EDGE Boston|accessdate=15 May 2012}}</ref> Sanchez was also the first transgender person on the Democratic National Committee's (DNC) Platform Committee in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/capital-living/24154-i-was-not-a-pretty-girl-and-i-felt-like-i-was-a-man|title='I was not a pretty girl, and I felt like I was a man'|last=Yager|first=Jordy|date=10 March 2009|publisher=TheHill.com|accessdate=15 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edgeboston.com/index.php?ch=news&sc=glbt&sc3=&id=72406|title=First Black Transsexual Delegate Headed to Dems\u2019 Convention|last=Lavers|first=Michael K.|date=31 March 2008|publisher=EDGE Boston|accessdate=15 May 2012}}</ref>\n** '''Barbra \"Babs\" Siperstein''' was nominated and confirmed as an at-large member of the [[Democratic National Committee]], becoming its first openly transgender member.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jerseycityindependent.com/2011/08/17/trailblazing-transgender-rights-advocate-babs-siperstein-tapped-as-hudson-pride-parade-grand-marshal/|title=Trailblazing Transgender Rights Advocate Babs Siperstein Tapped as Hudson Pride Parade Grand Marshal|date=17 August 2011|publisher=The Jersey City Independent|accessdate=15 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110820212146/http://www.jerseycityindependent.com/2011/08/17/trailblazing-transgender-rights-advocate-babs-siperstein-tapped-as-hudson-pride-parade-grand-marshal/|archive-date=20 August 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Uzi Even and his life partner was the first same-sex male couple in Israel whose right of adoption has been legally acknowledged.<ref name=\"edelman\">{{Cite news|last=Edelman|first=Ofra|title=Gay couple wins right to adopt foster son|work=Haaretz|accessdate=11 March 2009|date=11 March 2009|url=http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/1070060.html}}</ref> \n* Welsh rugby star [[Gareth Thomas (rugby)|Gareth Thomas]] becomes the first known top-level professional male athlete in a team sport to come out while still active.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1168953/index.htm |title=Gareth Thomas... The Only Openly Gay Male Athlete |first=Gary |last=Smith |authorlink=Gary Smith (sportswriter) |magazine=Sports Illustrated |date=3 May 2010 |accessdate=17 February 2011}}</ref> \n* '''[[Carol Ann Duffy]]''' was chosen as the first openly lesbian or gay [[Poet Laureate]] of the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Janet |last=Stobart |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2009/may/02/world/fg-britain-poet2 |title=Britain names first woman as poet laureate - Los Angeles Times |publisher=Articles.latimes.com |date=2007-08-03 |accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref>\n* In October 2009, LGBT activist '''Amy Andre'''<ref name=\"Amy Andre Binet\">{{cite web|url=http://binetusa.blogspot.com/2009/10/out-bisexual-amy-andre-to-head-san.html|title=BiNet USA's Blog: Out Bisexual Amy Andre to Head San Francisco Pride|first=Binet|last=Usa|date=6 October 2009}}</ref> was appointed as executive director of the San Francisco Pride Celebration Committee, making her San Francisco Pride's first openly bisexual woman of color executive director.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.oaklandlocal.com/article/sf-pride-40|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130706205444/http://archive.oaklandlocal.com/article/sf-pride-40|url-status=dead|title=SF Pride at 40 - Oakland Local|date=6 July 2013|archivedate=6 July 2013}}</ref><ref>Adrienne Williams, 19 October 2009. [https://archive.is/20120711215215/http://bisocialnetwork.com/amy-andre-sf-pride/ Interview with Amy Andre: New Bisexual Executive Director of SF Pride], ''BiSocial Network''.</ref>\n* Orthodox Israeli rabbi '''[[Ron Yosef]]''' became in 2009 the first Israeli orthodox [[Rabbi]] to come out, which he did when appearing in Uvda (\"Fact\"), [[Israel]]'s leading investigative television program, in an episode regarding [[conversion therapies]] in Israel.<ref>{{cite video|first=Yermi |last=Brenner |date=2009 |title=Gay Rabbi Comes Out of His Orthodox Closet |publisher=VJ Movement |url=http://www.vjmovement.com/truth/537 |accessdate=26 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112130252/http://www.vjmovement.com/truth/537 |archivedate=12 November 2013 }}</ref> Yosef remains in his position as a pulpit Rabbi.<ref name=\"yn\">{{cite news |first=Nissan |last=Strauchler |date=16 February 2010 |url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3849500,00.html |title=Gay with perfect faith |work=[[Ynetnews]] |accessdate=26 November 2014}}</ref>\n* '''Siddur Sha'ar Zahav''', the first complete prayer book to address the lives and needs of LGBTQ as well as straight Jews, was published.\n\n==2010==\n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Passed and came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Portugal|Portugal]] (without joint adoption), [[Same-sex marriage in Iceland|Iceland]] (with joint adoption) and [[Same-sex marriage in Argentina|Argentina]] (with adoption)<ref>{{cite news|title=Argentina legalizes same-sex marriage|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/americas/07/15/argentina.gay.marriage/index.html?eref=edition&fbid=0D-fErZV88m|publisher=CNN | date=16 July 2010}}</ref>\n** '''Came into effect''': Mexican City of [[Same-sex marriage in Mexico City|Mexico City]] (with joint adoption), US state of [[Same-sex marriage in New Hampshire|New Hampshire]] (step adoption only) and [[Same-sex marriage in the District of Columbia|Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=\"Hopkins2009\"/>\n** '''Recognition''': The Mexican Supreme Court rules that marriages contracted in Mexico City are valid throughout the country, although no other jurisdiction is required to perform them. Australian State of [[Tasmania]] recognises same-marriages performed in other jurisdictions.\n** '''Other''': U.S. state of [[California]], United States District Judge [[Vaughn Walker]] strikes down California's [[Proposition 8]] as violative of the United States Constitution's Fourteenth Amendment's Equal Protection and Due Process Clauses.<ref>{{cite news|title=Prop 8 Ruling: Read the Full Text|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/08/04/prop-8-ruling-read-the-fu_n_671050.html | work=Huffington Post | first=Nick|last=Graham|date=4 August 2010}}</ref>\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Came into effect''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Austria|Austria]] (without adoption and IVF access rights)\n** '''Passed''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Ireland|Ireland]] (without adoption rights)\n* '''Limited Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and came into effect''': Australian state of [[LGBT rights in New South Wales|New South Wales]] (without joint adoption until Sep 2010)\n* '''Same-sex couple adoption legislation''': Australian state of [[LGBT rights in New South Wales|New South Wales]] and [[LGBT rights in Denmark|Denmark]]\n* '''End to ban of same-sex couple adoption''': US states of [[Arkansas]] and [[Florida]]\n* '''End to ban of gay people in the military''': [[LGBT rights in Serbia|Serbia]]\n* '''End to ban of trans people in the military''': [[Australia]]\n* '''Decriminalization of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Fiji|Fiji]]<ref>[http://ilga.org/ilga/en/article/mjLN9SM1Oz Great news from Fiji. Homosexuality is finally legal!] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101101130910/http://ilga.org/ilga/en/article/mjLN9SM1Oz |date=1 November 2010 }} ILGA.org, 26 February 2010</ref>\n* '''Marches and Prides''': the first ever legal gay pride parade in [[Russia]], held in [[St. Petersburg]]\n* Guinness World Records recognized transgender man '''[[Thomas Beatie]]''' as the world's \"First Married Man to Give Birth.\"<ref>\"First Married Man to Give Birth\", Guinness World Records 2010 edition, page 110\"</ref>\n* '''[[Amanda Simpson]]''' became the first openly transgender presidential appointee in America when she was appointed as senior technical adviser in the Commerce Department's Bureau of Industry and Security.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/amanda-simpson-transgender-presidential-appointee-begins-work-commerce/story?id=9477161 |title=Amanda Simpson, First Transgender Presidential Appointee, Begins Work at Commerce Department - ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=5 January 2010 |accessdate=15 May 2012}}</ref>\n* '''[[Kye Allums]]''' became the first openly transgender athlete to play in NCAA basketball.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.cnn.com/2010-11-03/us/transgender.basketball.player_1_transgender-athletics-staff-basketball-team?_s=PM:US |title=First transgender athlete to play in NCAA basketball - CNN |publisher=Articles.cnn.com |date=3 November 2010 |accessdate=15 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111013085241/http://articles.cnn.com/2010-11-03/us/transgender.basketball.player_1_transgender-athletics-staff-basketball-team?_s=PM%3AUS |archivedate=13 October 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lgbtqnation.com/2011/10/lgbt-history-month-kye-allums-first-openly-transgender-athlete/ |title=LGBT History Month: Kye Allums, first openly transgender NCAA athlete \u2013 LGBTQ Nation |publisher=Lgbtqnation.com |date=2013-09-22 |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref> He was a transgender man who played on [[George Washington University]]'s women's team.<ref name=\"kaykay\">{{cite news|url=http://www.startribune.com/sports/gophers/106641518.html?elr=KArksLckD8EQDUoaEyqyP4O:DW3ckUiD3aPc:_Yyc:aUvDEhiaE3miUsZ |title=Ex-Centennial star deals with transgender publicity |newspaper=Star Tribune |first=Joseph |last=White |accessdate=5 November 2010 |date=4 November 2010 }}{{dead link|date=March 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/11/02/at-george-washington-univ_n_777637.html |title=Kye Allums, Transgender George Washington University Basketball Player, Takes The Court |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date= 2 November 2010|accessdate=15 May 2012 |first=Danielle |last=Wienerbronner}}</ref>\n* '''[[Phyllis Frye]]''' became the first openly transgender judge appointed in the United States.<ref name=dallas-voice_20101117>{{cite news | first=John | last=Wright | url=http://www.dallasvoice.com/phyllis-frye-texas-1st-transgender-judge-1052664.html | title=Phyllis Frye becomes Texas\u2019 1st trans judge | work=[[Dallas Voice]] | date=17 November 2010 | accessdate=8 July 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Houston Press\" /><ref name=\"Fox 26\">{{cite web|url=http://www.myfoxhouston.com/dpp/news/local/101117-judge-appointment-angers-pastors|title=Judge Appointment Angers Pastors: First transgender judge in Texas|publisher=FOX 26 TV News|last=McDonald|first=Sally|date=17 November 2010|accessdate=8 July 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Houston Press\">{{cite news|url=http://blogs.houstonpress.com/hairballs/2010/11/phyllis_fryejudge_transgender.php|newspaper=Houston Press|title=Phyllis Frye: Annise Parker Appoints Houston's First Transgender Judge (That We Know Of)|last=Connelly|first=Richard|date=18 November 2011|accessdate=8 July 2011}}</ref>\n* '''Mary Albing''' became the first openly lesbian minister ordained by the [[Evangelical Lutheran Church in America]], serving the Lutheran Church of Christ the Redeemer on the south side of Minneapolis.<ref>[http://www.sdgln.com/news/2010/05/24/video-minneapolis-luthern-church-welcomes-denominations-first-lesbian-pastor VIDEO: Minneapolis Lutheran church welcomes denomination's first lesbian pastor | San Diego Gay and Lesbian News]. Sdgln.com. Retrieved on 30 November 2010.</ref>\n* '''[[Chai Feldblum]]''', who was openly lesbian, became the first openly LGBT person to serve on the [[EEOC]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Ring |first=Trudy |url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/2013/05/24/obama-nominates-lesbian-attorney-second-eeoc-term |title=Obama Nominates Lesbian Attorney for Second EEOC Term |publisher=Advocate.com |date=2013-05-24 |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n* '''Donna Ryu''' became the first Asian-American woman, first Korean-American, and first lesbian to be appointed as a judge of the United States District Court, Northern District of California.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apawla.org/donnaryu |title=Honorable Donna Ryu |publisher=APAWLA |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n\n==2011==\n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Passed and came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in New York|New York]] and the [[Same-sex marriage in the Suquamish Tribe|Suquamish Tribe]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Gardner |first=Steven |title=Suquamish Tribe approves same-sex marriage |newspaper=[[Kitsap Sun]] |date=1 August 2011 |url=http://www.kitsapsun.com/news/2011/aug/01/suquamish-tribe-approves-same-sex-marriage/ |accessdate=2 August 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/60dKJvJfP?url=http://www.kitsapsun.com/news/2011/aug/01/suquamish-tribe-approves-same-sex-marriage/ |archivedate=2 August 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Came into effect''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Ireland|Ireland]] (without adoption rights)<ref>{{cite news|title=Civil Partnership Bill signed into law|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2010/0719/breaking29.html|newspaper=The Irish Times | date=7 July 2010}}</ref>\n** '''Passed and came into effect''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in the Isle of Man|Isle of Man]] (with joint adoption), US State of [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Illinois|Illinois]] (with joint adoption rights), [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Rhode Island|Rhode Island]] and [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Liechtenstein|Liechtenstein]]\n** '''Passed''': US State of [[LGBT rights in Delaware|Delaware]] (came into effect 2013) and [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Hawaii|Hawaii]] (came into effect Jan 2012)\n* '''End to ban on openly gay, lesbian, and bisexual people in the military''': [[LGBT rights in the United States|USA]] (see [[Don't Ask, don't tell]])\n* [[Tony Briffa (politician)|Tony Briffa]], believed to be the '''world's first intersex mayor''', elected in the City of Hobsons Bay in the suburbs of Melbourne, Australia, at the end of November.<ref>{{Citation\n| last = Canning\n| first = Paul\n| title = Australia town believed to have elected world's first intersex mayor\n| journal = World News Australia\n| date = 10 December 2011\n| url = http://www.lgbtqnation.com/2011/12/australia-town-believed-to-have-elected-worlds-first-intersex-mayor/}}</ref>\n* '''[[Elio Di Rupo]]''', '''first openly gay male head of government''', becomes Prime Minister of Belgium, 6 December.\n* '''[[Chaz Bono]]''' appeared on the 13th season of the US version of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]'' in 2011. This was the first time an openly transgender man starred on a major network television show for something unrelated to being transgender.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/society/transgendered/2011/12/28/14-reasons-made-2011-great-trans-people?page=0,11 |title=14 Reasons That Made 2011 Great for Trans People |publisher=Advocate.com |date=2011-12-28 |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n* '''[[Harmony Santana]]''' became the first openly transgender actress to receive a major acting award nomination; she was nominated by the [[Independent Spirit Awards]] as Best Supporting Actress for the movie ''[[Gun Hill Road (film)|Gun Hill Road]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/society/transgendered/2011/12/28/14-reasons-made-2011-great-trans-people?page=0,2 |title=14 Reasons That Made 2011 Great for Trans People |publisher=Advocate.com |date=2011-12-28 |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n* The '''[[Presbyterian Church]] (U.S.A.)''' voted to allow the ordination of openly gay and lesbian ministers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.cnn.com/2011-05-10/us/presbyterian.gay.lesbian.ordination_1_glasspool-lesbian-bishop-lesbian-ministers?_s=PM:US |work=CNN |title=Los Angeles Episcopalians elect lesbian bishop |date=6 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120618200956/http://articles.cnn.com/2011-05-10/us/presbyterian.gay.lesbian.ordination_1_glasspool-lesbian-bishop-lesbian-ministers?_s=PM%3AUS |archivedate=18 June 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''[[Rachel Isaacs]]''' became the first openly lesbian rabbi ordained by the Conservative movement's [[Jewish Theological Seminary of America|Jewish Theological Seminary]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.forward.com/sisterhood-blog/138141/ |title=JTS Ordains Its First Openly Gay Rabbi \u2013 The Sisterhood \u2013 Forward.com |publisher=Blogs.forward.com |date=2011-05-25 |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n* Petty Officer 2nd Class '''Marissa Gaeta''' of California and Petty Officer 3rd Class '''Citlalic Snell''' of Los Angeles became the first same-sex couple chosen to share the first kiss upon a U.S. Navy ship's return.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/nationnow/2011/12/a-public-embrace-between-two-female-sailors-from-california-is-being-hailed-as-the-kiss-heard-round-the-world-by-activists-wh.html|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|title=A public embrace between two female sailors from California is being hailed as the kiss heard around the world by activists | date=22 December 2011}}</ref>\n* '''Brenda Sue Fulton''' was named to the West Point Board of Visitors, making her the first openly gay member of the board that advises the Academy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freep.com/usatoday/article/1738665?odyssey=mod%7Cnewswell%7Ctext%7CFRONTPAGE%7Cp |title=West Point chapel hosts first same-sex marriage &#124; Detroit Free Press |publisher=freep.com |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n* Miss New York, [[Claire Buffie]], became the '''first [[Miss America]] contestant to campaign for the Miss America title on a gay rights platform'''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsfeed.time.com/2013/09/14/miss-kansas-bares-tattoos-and-6-other-memorable-miss-america-moments/|title=Miss Kansas Bares Tattoos and 6 Other Memorable Miss America Moments|work=TIME.com|accessdate=14 March 2015|date=14 September 2013}}</ref>\n* '''Jaiyah \"Johnny\" Saelua''' became the first openly transgender international footballer to play in the World Cup when she took the field for American Samoa in Oceania's first round of World Cup qualifiers for Brazil 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/aug/29/jaiyah-saelua-transgender-footballer-interview|title=Jaiyah Saelua: interview with the world's first transgender football international - Football - theguardian.com|first=Pete|last=Smith|work=the Guardian|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n* A resolution submitted by [[South Africa]] requesting a study on discrimination and sexual orientation (A/HRC/17/L.9/Rev.1) passed, 23 to 19 with 3 abstentions, in the '''UN [[Human Rights Council]]''' on 17 June 2011.<ref name=\"UN Human Rights Council\">{{cite news |url=http://www.ohchr.org/EN/NewsEvents/Pages/DisplayNews.aspx?NewsID=11167&LangID=E |title=UN Human Rights Council |date=17 June 2011 |accessdate=17 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110624081557/http://www.ohchr.org/EN/NewsEvents/Pages/DisplayNews.aspx?NewsID=11167&LangID=E |archivedate=24 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> This is the first time that any United Nations body approved a resolution affirming the rights of LGBT people.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5gpjOuYqR_9HwpkxaT7bS6f0x_glA?docId=3e1fdafae97c40f393a3d245c0df9fe4|title=UN group backs gay rights for the 1st time ever|author=Jordans, Frank|date=2011-05-17|accessdate=2011-05-17|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> \n* '''[[Fred Karger]]''' began his unsuccessful run for the 2012 Republican nomination for President, which made him America's first openly gay Republican presidential candidate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.salon.com/2011/03/23/gay_republican_president|title=Fred Karger, gay Republican, for president|publisher=|accessdate=30 October 2014}}</ref>\n* '''San Francisco\u2019s Human Rights Commission released a report on bisexual visibility''', titled \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20141010222618/http://sf-hrc.org/sites/sf-hrc.org/files/migrated/FileCenter/Documents/HRC_Publications/Articles/Bisexual_Invisiblity_Impacts_and_Recommendations_March_2011.pdf Bisexual Invisibility: Impacts and Regulations]\"; this was the first time any governmental body released such a report.<ref name=\"advocate 2011\">{{cite news|title= The Biggest Bisexual News Stories of 2011|url=http://www.advocate.com/news/daily-news/2011/09/23/biggest-bisexual-news-stories-2011|date=23 September 2011 |first=Diane|last=Anderson-Minshall}}</ref>\n* '''[[Sandra Lawson]]''' became the first openly gay African-American and the first African-American admitted to the [[Reconstructionist Rabbinical College]].<ref name=\"lawson\">{{cite web|url=https://whyy.org/articles/rabbi-is-latest-of-many-titles-for-philly-woman/|title=Rabbi is latest of many titles for Philly woman|website=WHYY|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref><ref name=\"apbspeakers1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.apbspeakers.com/speaker/sandra-lawson/ |title=Book Sandra Lawson for Speaking, Events and Appearances |publisher=APB Speakers |date= |accessdate=2019-06-03}}</ref>\n\n==2012==\n[[File:Rep Kyrsten Sinema, Official Portrait.jpg|upright|thumb|[[Kyrsten Sinema]] became the first openly bisexual person elected to the U.S. Congress in 2012.]] \n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Passed and came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Denmark|Denmark]], Mexican state of [[Same-sex marriage in Quintana Roo|Quintana Roo]], U.S. states of [[Same-sex marriage in Maine|Maine]] and [[Same-sex marriage in Washington State|Washington]], the [[Same-sex marriage under United States tribal jurisdictions#Port Gamble S'Klallam Tribe|Port Gamble S'Klallam Tribe]], \n** '''Passed''': U.S. state of [[Same-sex marriage in Maryland|Maryland]]\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Came into effect''': U.S. State of [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Hawaii|Hawaii]]\n* '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Lesotho|Lesotho]] and [[LGBT rights in S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe|S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe]]\n* '''Anti-discrimination legislation''':\n** '''For sexual orientation and gender identity''': [[LGBT rights in Chile|Chile]]\n** The [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development|U.S. Dept. of Housing and Urban Development]]'s [[Office of Fair Housing and Equal Opportunity]] issued a regulation to prohibit LGBT discrimination in federally assisted housing programs. The new regulations ensure that the Department's core housing programs are open to all eligible persons, regardless of sexual orientation or gender identity.\n** For '''gender identity:''' Canadian provinces of [[Manitoba]]; and '''gender expression:''' [[Ontario]]\n* '''Family and Relationships:'''\n** The first gay Israeli couple was granted a divorce by an Israeli family court. The divorce of Tel Aviv University Professor [[Avi Even]], the first openly gay Knesset member, and Dr. Amit Kama was granted on Sunday by the Ramat Gan Family Court, according to [[Haaretz]], which ordered the Interior Minister to register their status as divorced.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thejewishweek.com/news/breaking-news/israel-grants-first-gay-divorce |title=Israel Grants First Gay Divorce |newspaper=The Jewish Week |accessdate=2013-10-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007071208/http://www.thejewishweek.com/news/breaking-news/israel-grants-first-gay-divorce |archivedate=7 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n** Taiwan's first same-sex Buddhist wedding was held for '''Fish Huang''' and her partner '''You Ya-ting''', with Buddhist master Shih Chao-hui presiding over the ritual.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/China/Taiwan-gets-its-first-same-sex-Buddhist-wedding/Article1-911937.aspx|title=Taiwan gets its first same-sex Buddhist wedding|date=2012-08-11|newspaper=Hindustan Times|accessdate=2013-10-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131010225722/http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/China/Taiwan-gets-its-first-same-sex-Buddhist-wedding/Article1-911937.aspx|archivedate=10 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** The '''first same-sex marriage at the U.S. Military Academy''' was held for a young lieutenant and her partner (Ellen Schick and Shannon Simpson) at the Old Cadet Chapel in West Point's cemetery.<ref name=\"boston.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.boston.com/news/nation/2012/12/02/west-point-chapel-hosts-its-first-same-sex-wedding/sHjOTBBa2hweA3KxjU3m9O/story.html|title=West Point Chapel hosts its first same sex wedding|accessdate=2013-10-05|newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130823023451/http://www.boston.com/news/nation/2012/12/02/west-point-chapel-hosts-its-first-same-sex-wedding/sHjOTBBa2hweA3KxjU3m9O/story.html|archivedate=23 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://outservemag.com/2012/12/first-gay-weddings-held-at-west-point/|title=First Gay Weddings Held at West Point &#124; OutServe Magazine|date=2012-12-01|publisher=Outservemag.com|first=David|last=Small|accessdate=2013-10-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131006165540/http://outservemag.com/2012/12/first-gay-weddings-held-at-west-point/|archivedate=6 October 2013|df=dmy}}</ref> Navy Chief '''Elny McKinney''' and '''Anacelly McKinney''' became the first known same-sex couple to marry on a U.S. military base. They were wed at Naval Base Point Loma in San Diego.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/military/2012/09/18/11-firsts-after-repeal-dadt?page=0,5|title=11 Firsts After The Repeal of DADT|last=Garcia|first=Michelle|date=2012-09-18|publisher=Advocate.com|accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n** The '''first same-sex couple became engaged in the White House''' (Ben Schock and Matthew Phelps).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rt.com/usa/news/gay-white-house-couple-321/|title=Gay Marine proposes in the White House \u2014 RT USA|date=2012-12-18|publisher=Rt.com|accessdate=2013-10-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117073054/http://rt.com/usa/news/gay-white-house-couple-321/|archivedate=17 January 2013|df=dmy}}</ref>\n** Air Force Col. '''Ginger Wallace''' became the first known out member of the U.S. military to have their same-sex partner participate in the pinning ceremony tradition that had been reserved for spouses and family members. Her partner of 10 years, Kathy Knopf, pinned colonel wings on Wallace days after the two attended President Obama's State of The Union address as a guest of the First Lady.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/military/2012/09/18/11-firsts-after-repeal-dadt?page=0,4|title=11 Firsts After The Repeal of DADT|last=Garcia|first=Michelle|date=2012-09-18|publisher=Advocate.com|accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n* '''Arts and Culture:'''\n** '''Kate McKinnon''' became [[Saturday Night Live]]'s first openly [[lesbian]] cast member; [[Danitra Vance]] never disclosed her sexual orientation publicly, but was revealed to be a lesbian when she died.<ref name=\"shewired\">{{cite news|url=http://www.shewired.com/box-office/2012/04/08/snls-first-out-lesbian-featured-player-kate-mckinnon-makes-splash-penelope|title=SNL's First Out Lesbian Featured Player Kate McKinnon Makes Splash with Penelope Cruz Pantene Sketch|last=Gilchrist|first=Tracy E.|date=8 April 2012|accessdate=10 April 2012|newspaper=SheWired}}</ref><ref>Danitra Vance's sexual orientation was not revealed until [https://www.nytimes.com/1994/08/23/obituaries/danitra-vance-35-an-actress-worked-at-shakespeare-festival.html her death in 1994].</ref>\n** On 28 June 2012 '''[[Diana King]]''' declared \"Yes I am a Lesbian\" to her fans from her official Facebook page, thus becoming the first Jamaican artist to ever publicly come out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.outmusicawards.com/pages/honorees.html|title=OUTmusic Awards The Biggest Night of the LGBT Music Industry|publisher=Outmusicawards.com|accessdate=2013-10-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007002002/http://www.outmusicawards.com/pages/honorees.html|archivedate=7 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/notes/dianaking/yes-i-am-a-lesbian/10151076275753885|title=Yes!! I Am A Lesbian|publisher=Facebook.com|accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n** '''Katie Ricks''' became the first open lesbian ordained by the [[Presbyterian Church]] (U.S.A.)<ref>[http://www.advocate.com/news/2012/04/16/katie-ricks-presbyterians-ordain-their-first-out-lesbian Katie Ricks: Presbyterians Ordain Their First Out Lesbian]. ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]].'' retrieved 6 June 2012.</ref>\n** '''Emily Aviva Kapor''', an American rabbi who had been ordained privately by a \"[[Conservadox]]\" rabbi in 2005, began living as a woman in 2012, thus becoming the first openly transgender female rabbi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forward.com/articles/180230/emily-aviva-kapor-creating-a-jewish-community-for/|title=Emily Aviva Kapor: Creating a Jewish Community for Trans Women|date=15 July 2013|publisher=The Forward|accessdate=25 October 2013}}</ref>\n**  '''Rainbow Jews''', an oral history project showcasing the lives of Jewish bisexual, lesbian, gay, and transgender people in the [[United Kingdom]] from the 1950s until the present, was launched.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rainbowjews.com/about-us/|title=About us|publisher=Rainbow Jews|accessdate=2014-04-05}}</ref> It is the United Kingdom's first archive of Jewish bisexual, lesbian, gay, and transgender history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haaretz.com/jewish-world/jewish-world-features/.premium-1.573723|title=Trove of Jewish LGBT history goes on display in U.K.|date=2014-12-02|publisher=Haaretz.com|accessdate=2014-04-05}}</ref>\n** ''[[ParaNorman]]'', released in 2012, had the '''first openly gay character in a mainstream animated film.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://diversity.nbcuni.com/in_the_news/paranorman-screenwriterco-director-chris-butler-on-writing-the-first-gay-character-in-a-mainstream-animated-film|title=\"ParaNorman\" Screenwriter/Co-Director Chris Butler on Writing the First Gay Character in a Mainstream Animated Film - diversity.nbcuni.com|work=diversity.nbcuni.com|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://parentpreviews.com/movie-reviews/paranorman|title=Parent Guide for \"ParaNorman\" On Home Video|publisher=|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref>\n* '''Politics:'''\n** '''US Politics:'''\n*** '''[[Barack Obama]]''' became the first [[President of the United States|U.S. president]] to publicly announce support for same-sex marriage on 9 May.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://firstread.msnbc.msn.com/_news/2012/05/09/11621156-obama-i-think-same-sex-couples-should-be-able-to-get-married?lite |agency=MSNBC |title=Obama: 'I think same sex couples should be able to get married' |first=Michael |last=O'Brien |date=9 May 2012 |accessdate=9 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120510060229/http://firstread.msnbc.msn.com/_news/2012/05/09/11621156-obama-i-think-same-sex-couples-should-be-able-to-get-married?lite |archivedate=10 May 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>Jackie Calmes and Peter Baker (9 May 2012). [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/10/us/politics/obama-says-same-sex-marriage-should-be-legal.html?hp Obama Says Same-Sex Marriage Should Be Legal] ''nytimes.com'' Retrieved 9 May 2012.</ref>\n*** '''Marlene Pray''' joined the Doylestown, Pennsylvania City Council in 2012, though she resigned in 2013; she was the first openly bisexual office holder in Pennsylvania.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://amplifyyourvoice.org/u/jordan/2012/01/04/marlene-pray-becomes-first-openly-bisexual-office-holder-in-pa |title=Marlene Pray Becomes First Openly Bisexual Office Holder In PA - Amplify |publisher=Amplifyyourvoice.org |date=2012-01-04 |accessdate=2013-10-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007063401/http://amplifyyourvoice.org/u/jordan/2012/01/04/marlene-pray-becom