tist in the [[US National Academy of Sciences]] in 2013.<ref name=\"trans\">{{cite news|url=http://transnews.org/2013/05/11/first-transgender-scientist-selected-for-national-academy-of-science-membership/|title=Neurobiologist Becomes First Transgender Scientist Selected For U.S. National Academy of Science Membership|date=11 May 2013|work=Transnews|publisher=Trans Media Network|author1=Trans News Editors|accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref>\n** For the first time, the California Department of Education's list of recommended books for grades Pre-K-through-12 included a book with a transgender theme, '''I Am J''' by Cris Beam.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scpr.org/blogs/education/2013/03/22/13033/first-book-with-transgender-theme-makes-it-on-ca-s/|title=First book with transgender theme makes it on CA schools reading list &#124; Pass / Fail &#124; 89.3 KPCC|date=2013-03-22|publisher=Scpr.org|accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n** '''California''' enacted America's first law protecting transgender students; the law, called the School Success and Opportunity Act, declares that every public school student in California from kindergarten to 12th grade must be \"permitted to participate in sex-segregated school programs and activities, including athletic teams and competitions, and use facilities consistent with his or her gender identity, irrespective of the gender listed on the pupil's records.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/aug/12/california-enact-nations-first-law-protecting-tran/|title=California enacts nation's first law protecting transgender students|last=Wetzstein|first=Cheryl|date=12 August 2013|publisher=Washingtontimes.com|accessdate=13 August 2013}}</ref>\n** '''[[Jennifer Pritzker]]''' came out as transgender in 2013 and thus became the world's first openly transgender billionaire.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/briansolomon/2013/09/16/jennifer-pritzker-becomes-first-transgender-billionaire/|title=Jennifer Pritzker becomes first transgender billionaire|last=Solomon|first=Brian|work=Forbes|accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n** A six-year-old girl named '''Luana''', who was born a boy, became the first transgender child in Argentina to have her new name officially changed on her identity documents.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/southamerica/argentina/10339296/Six-year-old-becomes-first-transgender-child-in-Argentina-to-change-identity.html|title=Six-year-old becomes first transgender child in Argentina to change identity|last=Bowater|first=Donna|date=27 September 2013|newspaper=Telegraph|location=London|accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref> She is believed to be the youngest to benefit from the country's new Gender Identity Law, which was approved in May 2012.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\" />\n** '''[[Jennifer Finney Boylan]]''' was chosen as the first openly transgender co-chair of [[GLAAD]]'s National Board of Directors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/media/2013/11/08/glaad-appoints-first-transgender-cochair|title=GLAAD Appoints First Transgender Cochair|last=Reynolds|first=Daniel|date=2013-11-08|publisher=Advocate.com|accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref>\n** On 31 October 2013 '''[[Paris Lees]]''' became the first openly transgender panellist to appear on the BBC's ''[[Question Time (TV series)|Question Time]]'' programme, drawing praise from commentators who included former Deputy Prime Minister [[John Prescott]] and the Labour Party deputy leader [[Harriet Harman]].<ref name=\"PNQTDebut\">{{cite news|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2013/11/01/harriet-harman-and-john-prescott-heap-praise-on-paris-lees-in-question-time-debut/|title=Harriet Harman and John Prescott heap praise on Paris Lees in Question Time debut|last=Roberts|first=Scott|date=1 November 2013|accessdate=7 November 2013|newspaper=[[Pink News]]}}</ref>\n** '''Stephen Alexander''', of Rhode Island, became the first high school coach to come out publicly as transgender.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.outsports.com/2013/11/12/5095154/transgender-coach-stephen-alexander-profile-glocester-rhode-island|title=Transition game: America's first publicly out transgender high school coach is opening minds in the conservative rural town of Glocester, R.I.|publisher=Outsports|accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref>\n** On 1 November '''Audrey Gauthier''' was elected president of CUPE 4041, representing Air Transat flight attendants based in Montreal.<ref name=\"TransNews.org\">{{cite web|url=http://transnews.org/2013/11/21/trans-person-elected-president-union-local/|title=Canadian First: Trans Person Elected President of a Union Local|work=TransNews.org}}</ref> She thus became the first openly transgender person elected president of a union local in Canada.<ref name=\"TransNews.org\" />\n** Publication of the '''[[Intersex#Senate Committee inquiry, Australia|first parliamentary report on the human rights and health of intersex people]],''' published by the [[Australian Senate]] on 25 October.\n** '''[[Kristin Beck]]''', formerly Chris Beck, came out as the first openly transgender retired [[Navy SEAL]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://lgbtweekly.com/2013/06/13/what-kristin-becks-narrative-means-to-trans-open-service/|title=What Kristin Beck's narrative means to trans open service|date=13 June 2013|first=Autumn|last=Sandeen|accessdate=13 June 2013|journal=LGBT Weekly|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104205348/http://lgbtweekly.com/2013/06/13/what-kristin-becks-narrative-means-to-trans-open-service/|archive-date=4 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* '''Family and Relationships:'''\n** For the first time the U.S. Department of Veterans Affairs decided to allow the same-sex spouse of a military veteran to be buried in a U.S. national cemetery. VA Secretary [[Eric Shinseki]] gave permission for retired Air Force officer '''Linda Campbell''', 66, to bury the ashes of her same-sex spouse '''Nancy Lynchild''' at Willamette National Cemetery in Oregon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2013/02/va-grants-first-burial-rights-for-same-sex-couple/ |title=VA Grants First Burial Rights For Same-Sex Couple - ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=2013-02-15 |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n** '''Rehana Kausar''' and '''Sobia Kamar''', both from Pakistan, became the first Muslim lesbian couple to enter into civil partnership in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/local-news/muslim-lesbian-couple-defy-death-4015955|title=Muslim lesbian couple defy death threats to tie the knot in civil ceremony|date=2013-05-26|newspaper=Birmingham Mail|accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n** '''Julian Marsh''' and '''Traian Povov''' become the first married gay couple to have a green card application approved.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/29/gay-couple-green-card_n_3522323.html|title=Gay Couple Receives Green Card After DOMA Ruling|last=Reilly|first=Mollie|date=29 June 2013|work=Huffington Post}}</ref>\n** '''Master Sgt. Angela Shunk''' and her wife, '''Tech. Sgt. Stacey Shunk''', became the first same-sex couple to receive an assignment together under the U.S. Air Force's Join Spouse program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lgbtqnation.com/2013/09/usaf-lesbian-couple-first-to-receive-joint-spouse-assignment/|title=USAF lesbian couple first to receive \u2018Join Spouse\u2019 assignment \u2013 LGBTQ Nation|date=2013-09-22|publisher=Lgbtqnation.com|accessdate=2013-10-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104155901/http://www.lgbtqnation.com/2013/09/usaf-lesbian-couple-first-to-receive-joint-spouse-assignment/|archive-date=4 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* '''Arts and Culture:'''\n** The first same-sex kiss ever on a Eurovision stage occurred at the 2013 [[Eurovision Song Contest]] when '''[[Krista Siegfrids]]''', who sang \"Marry Me\", ended her semi-final performance by kissing one of her female dancers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/historic-lesbian-kiss-occurs-eurovision-song-contest160513 |title=Historic lesbian kiss occurs at Eurovision Song Contest |publisher=Gay Star News |date=2013-05-16 |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n** '''Guy Erwin''' became the first openly gay bishop to be elected by the [[Evangelical Lutheran Church in America]];  he was elected to the Southwest California Synod of the ELCA.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/05/31/rev-guy-erwin-lutheran-gay-bishop_n_3369794.html|title=First Openly Gay Lutheran Bishop Elected|last=Raushenbush|first=Paul|date=31 May 2013|work=Huffington Post}}</ref>\n** The Bi Writers Association, which promotes bisexual writers, books, and writing, announced the winners of its first '''Bisexual Book Awards'''.<ref name=\"glaad.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.glaad.org/blog/bi-writers-association-announces-recipients-bisexual-book-awards|title=Bi Writers Association announces recipients of Bisexual Book Awards|last=Heffernan|first=Dani|date=2013-06-06|publisher=GLAAD|accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref> An awards ceremony was held at the [[Nuyorican Poets Caf\u00e9]] in New York City.<ref name=\"glaad.org\" />\n** The [[Directors Guild Of America]] elected '''[[Paris Barclay]]''' as its first black and first openly gay president.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/26/directors-guild-of-america-president_n_3504529.html|title=DGA Elects First Black, Openly Gay President|last=Matthew|first=Jacobs|date=26 June 2013|work=Huffington Post}}</ref>\n** '''[[Same Love]]''', a hit single from [[Macklemore]] & [[Ryan Lewis]], became the first Top 40 song in the U.S. to promote and celebrate same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/01/arts/music/stars-align-for-a-gay-marriage-anthem.html?pagewanted=all|title=Stars Align for a Gay Marriage Anthem|last=McKinley Jr|first=James C.|date=30 June 2013|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n** Movie director '''[[Kim Jho Gwang-soo]]''' and his partner '''Kim Seung-hwan''' became the first South Korean gay couple to publicly wed, although it was not a legally recognized marriage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontopmag.com/article.aspx?id=16507&MediaType=1&Category=24|title=First South Korean Gay Couple To Publicly Wed Plans Challenge To Marriage Law - On Top Magazine &#124; Gay news & entertainment|date=2013-09-25|publisher=Ontopmag.com|accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref>\n** '''[[Harvey Milk]]''' was chosen as the first openly [[LGBT]] political official to be featured on an American postage stamp.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/10/10/harvey-milk-stamp_n_4080196.html|title=Harvey Milk To Be Honored With U.S. Postage Stamp|date=10 October 2013|publisher=Huffingtonpost.com|author=Post by Harvey Milk Foundation.|accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref>\n** '''[[Andy Herren]] became the first openly gay winner of the American version of the \"Big Brother\" reality show.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://voices.suntimes.com/arts-entertainment/the-daily-sizzle/lake-views-andy-herren-becomes-first-openly-gay-winner-of-big-brother/|title=Andy Herren wins Big Brother, becomes first openly gay winner of CBS reality show &#124; Voices|date=2013-09-18|publisher=Voices.suntimes.com|accessdate=2014-01-18|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219203248/http://voices.suntimes.com/arts-entertainment/the-daily-sizzle/lake-views-andy-herren-becomes-first-openly-gay-winner-of-big-brother/|archivedate=19 February 2014|df=dmy}}</ref>'''\n** The '''first televised Romanian same-sex wedding''' was held.<ref name=\"advocate.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/marriage-equality/wedding-channel/2013/09/13/first-televised-romanian-same-sex-wedding-gets|title=First Televised Romanian Same-Sex Wedding Gets High Ratings|last=Ring|first=Trudy|date=2013-09-13|publisher=Advocate.com|accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref> It was between two men, and was done on the reality show Four Weddings and a Challenge.<ref name=\"advocate.com\" />\n** '''Q Radio''', which went on the airwaves in September, claims to be India's first radio station which caters to the country's lesbians, gays, bisexuals and transgender people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/tasneemnashrulla/india-gets-its-first-radio-station-for-the-lgbt-community|title=India Gets Its First Radio Station For The LGBT Community|date=2013-10-04|publisher=Buzzfeed.com|first=Tasneem|last=Nashrulla|accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref>\n** '''Mark C. Goldman''' became the first openly gay president of the American Conference of Cantors, a Reform Jewish organization.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://accantors.org/acc/node/1074|title=Reform Cantors Conference Installs First Openly Gay President|accessdate=14 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402224540/http://accantors.org/acc/node/1074|archivedate=2 April 2015|df=dmy}}</ref>\n** Rabbi '''[[Deborah Waxman]]''' was elected as the President of the [[Reconstructionist Rabbinical College]].<ref name=\"thejewishweek.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thejewishweek.com/news/national-news/reconstructionists-pick-first-woman-lesbian-denominational-leader|title=Reconstructionists Pick First Woman, Lesbian As Denominational Leader|newspaper=The Jewish Week|author=JTA|accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://forward.com/articles/185252/trailblazing-reconstructionist-deborah-waxman-reli/?p=all|title=Trailblazing Reconstructionist Deborah Waxman Relishes Challenges of Judaism \u2013|publisher=Forward.com|accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref> As the President, she is believed to be the first woman and first lesbian to lead a Jewish congregational union, and the first female rabbi and first lesbian to lead a Jewish seminary; RRC is both a congregational union and a seminary.<ref name=\"thejewishweek.com\" /><ref>{{cite journal|title=RRC Announces New President Elect|url=http://www.rrc.edu/sites/default/files/ORPHAN_PDFs/RRC_WaxmanPresidentElect-ForPress3.pdf?hero=1615|accessdate=2014-04-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014112828/http://www.rrc.edu/sites/default/files/ORPHAN_PDFs/RRC_WaxmanPresidentElect-ForPress3.pdf?hero=1615|archive-date=14 October 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n* Dr. '''[[Saul Levin]]''' was named on 15 May 2013 as the new chief executive officer and medical director of the [[American Psychiatric Association]], making him the first known openly gay person to head the APA.<ref>{{cite web |last=Chibbaro |first=Lou |url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2013/05/21/gay-washington-dc-psychiatrist-saul-levin-named-head-of-american-psychiatric-association-apa/ |title=Gay DC psychiatrist Saul Levin named head of APA &#124; LGBT News : Washington Blade \u2013 America's Leading Gay News Source |publisher=Washingtonblade.com |date=2013-05-21 |accessdate=2013-10-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160421174725/http://www.washingtonblade.com/2013/05/21/gay-washington-dc-psychiatrist-saul-levin-named-head-of-american-psychiatric-association-apa/ |archivedate=21 April 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* Major General '''Patricia \"Trish\" Rose''' became the first openly lesbian two-star general in the U.S. Air Force, and the highest ranking openly gay officer in the entire U.S. military at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thinkprogress.org/lgbt/2013/06/10/2127481/the-morning-pride-june-10-2013/ |title=The Morning Pride: June 10, 2013 |website=ThinkProgress |date=2013-06-10 |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>\n* '''New Jersey''' became the second state, after California, to sign a ban on therapy that claims to convert gay people into heterosexual.<ref name=\"washingtonblade.com\" /><ref name=\"news.yahoo.com\" />\n* '''[[Russia]]'s government adopted a federal bill banning the distribution of \"propaganda of non-traditional sexual relations\" to minors. The law imposes heavy fines for using the media or internet to promote \"non-traditional relations\".'''\n* San Francisco's first '''Project Homeless Connect''' for lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender people was held.<ref>{{cite news|first=Kevin |last=Fagan |url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/S-F-tackles-dual-challenge-being-homeless-and-4876509.php |title=S.F. tackles dual challenge - being homeless and gay |newspaper=SFGate |date=2013-10-07 |accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref>\n* '''BiLaw''', the first American national organization of bisexual lawyers, law professors, law students, and their allies, was founded.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://law.indianatech.edu/faculty/professor-marcus-speaks-at-harvard-law-school/ |title=Professor Marcus Speaks at Harvard Law School - Indiana Tech Law School : Indiana Tech Law School |publisher=Law.indianatech.edu |accessdate=2015-07-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716012405/http://law.indianatech.edu/faculty/professor-marcus-speaks-at-harvard-law-school/ |archivedate=16 July 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= Advocate Contributors |url=http://www.advocate.com/commentary/2015/03/04/op-ed-how-were-asking-supreme-court-end-bi-erasure |title=Op-ed: How We're Asking the Supreme Court to End Bi Erasure |publisher=Advocate.com |date=2015-03-04 |accessdate=2015-07-15}}</ref>\n\n==2014==\n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Passed and came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in the United Kingdom|Scotland]], US states of [[Same-sex marriage in Oregon|Oregon]], [[Same-sex marriage in Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania]], [[Same-sex marriage in Utah|Utah]], [[Same-sex marriage in Oklahoma|Oklahoma]], [[Same-sex marriage in Virginia|Virginia]], [[Same-sex marriage in Wisconsin|Wisconsin]], [[Same-sex marriage in Indiana|Indiana]], [[Same-sex marriage in Colorado|Colorado]], [[Same-sex marriage in Nevada|Nevada]], [[Same-sex marriage in Idaho|Idaho]], [[Same-sex marriage in West Virginia|West Virginia]], [[Same-sex marriage in North Carolina|North Carolina]], [[Same-sex marriage in Alaska|Alaska]], [[Same-sex marriage in Arizona|Arizona]], [[Same-sex marriage in Wyoming|Wyoming]], [[Same-sex marriage in Kansas|Kansas]], [[Same-sex marriage in South Carolina|South Carolina]], [[Same-sex marriage in Montana|Montana]], the Mexican state of [[Same-sex marriage in Coahuila|Coahuila]], the [[Same-sex marriage in the Puyallup Tribe of Indians|Puyallup Tribe of Indians]], the [[Same-sex marriage under United States tribal jurisdictions#ac du Flambeau Band of Lake Superior Chippewa|Lac du Flambeau of Lake Superior Chippewa]], the [[Same-sex marriage under United States tribal jurisdictions#Fort McDermitt Paiute and Shoshone Tribes of the Fort McDermitt Indian Reservation|Fort McDermitt Paiute and Shoshone Tribes of the Fort McDermitt Indian Reservation]], the [[Same-sex marriage in the Fort McDowell Yavapai Nation|Fort McDowell Yavapai Nation]], the [[Same-sex marriage in the Pascua Yaqui Tribe|Pascua Yaqui Tribe]], the [[Same-sex marriage in the Salt River Pima-Maricopa Indian Community|Salt River Pima-Maricopa Indian Community]], the [[Same-sex marriage in the San Carlos Apache Tribe|San Carlos Apache Tribe]], the [[Same-sex marriage under United States tribal jurisdictions#Wind River Indian Reservation|Wind River Indian Reservation]], the [[Same-sex marriage under United States tribal jurisdictions#Blackfoot Tribe|Blackfoot Tribe]] and the [[Same-sex marriage under United States tribal jurisdictions#Keweenaw Bay Indian Community|Keweenaw Bay Indian Community]]\n** '''Passed''': [[Same-sex marriage in Luxembourg|Luxembourg]]\n** '''Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in the United Kingdom|England and Wales]] and US state of [[Same-sex marriage in Illinois|Illinois]]\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and came into effect''': [[LGBT rights in Gibraltar|Gibraltar]] (with joint adoption), [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Malta|Malta]] (with joint adoption) and [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Croatia|Croatia]]\n** '''Passed''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Estonia|Estonia]]\n* '''Same-sex couple adoption legislation''': [[LGBT rights in Andorra|Andorra]], the Mexican state of [[Same-sex marriage in Coahuila|Coahuila]]\n* '''Decriminalization of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Northern Cyprus|Northern Cyprus]] and [[LGBT rights in Palau|Palau]]\n* '''Criminalization of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Brunei|Brunei]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.humanrightsfirst.org/press-release/brunei-adopts-penal-code-provision-calling-death-stoning-same-sex-acts|title=Brunei Adopts Penal Code Provision Calling for Death by Stoning for Same-Sex Acts|work=Human Rights First}}</ref> \n* '''Banning of same-sex marriage:''' [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Nigeria|Nigeria]]<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://freedomhouse.org/article/nigerian-same-sex-marriage-ban-violates-lgbti-rights |title=Nigerian Same Sex Marriage Ban Violates LGBTI Rights |publisher=Freedom House |date=2013-06-05 |accessdate=2018-12-20}}</ref>\n* '''Anti-discrimination law for gender identity:''' Canadian province [[Saskatchewan]] \n* '''Family and Relationships:'''\n** '''Anna Guillot and Chrissy Kelly''', who were married in New York in 2012, became the first same-sex couple in Mississippi to create a public record of their marriage.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/marriage-equality/2014/03/25/miss-couple-creates-first-record-same-sex-marriage|title=Miss. Couple Creates First Record of Same-Sex Marriage|last=Ring|first=Trudy|date=2014-03-25|publisher=Advocate.com|accessdate=2014-05-18}}</ref> However, this did not give their marriage legal standing in Mississippi.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n** The marriage of '''Giuseppe Chigiotti''' and '''Stefano Bucci''' became the first overseas same-sex marriage to be legally recognized in Italy; the two were married in New York in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/first-overseas-same-sex-marriage-legally-recognized-italy100414|title=First overseas same-sex marriage legally recognized in Italy|date=2014-04-10|publisher=Gay Star News|accessdate=2014-05-18}}</ref>\n** For the first time, an Italian court granted permission for '''the adoption of a child living with a gay couple.''' The child was the biological daughter of one of the women in the couple, and her partner was allowed to legally become her co-parent through adoption.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/italian-court-allows-child-be-legally-adopted-gay-couple300814#sthash.enRhxQ6c.dpuf|title=Italian court allows a child to be legally adopted by gay couple|work=Gay Star News|accessdate=6 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006133440/http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/italian-court-allows-child-be-legally-adopted-gay-couple300814#sthash.enRhxQ6c.dpuf|archivedate=6 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** Berlin, Germany unveiled the '''world's first cemetery for lesbians.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.theweek.com/article.php?id=259428|title=Berlin opens world's first lesbian-only cemetery|date=2014-04-04|publisher=M.theweek.com|first=Meghan|last=DeMaria|accessdate=2014-05-18}}</ref>\n** '''Umma Azul''' was the first child of a lesbian couple to be baptized by the Catholic Church in Argentina.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/04/05/world/americas/argentina-baby-baptism-lesbian-couple/|title=Lesbians' baby baptized by Catholic Church in Argentina - CNN.com|date=7 April 2014|work=CNN}}</ref>\n** '''Emilia Maria Jesty''', daughter of a lesbian couple, was the first child born in Tennessee to have a woman listed on the birth certificate as her \"father.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/features/sns-rt-us-usa-courts-samesexmarriage-20140409,0,1020017.story|title=Gay marriage first in Tenn.: Woman listed as father on birth certificate|last=Biskupic|first=Joan|date=9 April 2014|work=Chicago Tribune}}</ref>\n** The U.S. Department of Veterans Affairs agreed to give survivor benefits to the first-known same-sex war widow, '''Tracy Dice Johnson''', whose wife Donna Johnson died in a suicide bombing attack in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.washingtonpost.com/blogs/federal-eye/wp/2014/05/19/group-va-awards-survivor-benefits-to-first-known-gay-war-widow/|title=Group: VA awards survivor benefits to first-known gay war widow|work=Washington Post|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n** Both lesbian parents were listed on their children's birth certificates in Australia, which is the first time an '''Australian birth certificate''' indicates that both members of a same-sex couple were the legal parents of a child at birth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/world/2014/05/30/australian-first-both-lesbian-parents-named-birth-certificate|title=Australian First: Both Lesbian Parents Named on Birth Certificate|first=Thom|last=Senzee|work=Advocate.com|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n** '''The U.S. Naval Academy Chapel's first-ever same-sex wedding''' was held for David Bucher, a 49-year-old Academy graduate who works at the Pentagon, and partner Bruce Moats.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/u-s-naval-academy-hosts-first-same-sex-wedding-maryland-n102276|title=U.S. Naval Academy Hosts First Same-Sex Wedding for Maryland Couple|last=Balding|first=Justin|date=2014-05-10|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=2014-05-18}}</ref>\n* '''Trans:'''\n** The U.S. '''[[Equal Employment Opportunity Commission]]''' filed the first [[Title VII]] action taken by the federal government on behalf of transgender workers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/federal-agency-sues-companies-over-anti-transgender-discrimination|title=EEOC sues companies over anti-transgender discrimination|work=MSNBC|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref> The lawsuits were filed for Amiee Stephens and Brandi Branson, both transgender women.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/federal-government-sues-companies-over-anti-transgender-disc|title=Federal Government Sues Companies Over Anti-Transgender Discrimination Claims|work=BuzzFeed|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n** '''Meghan Stabler''' became the first openly transgender woman to be named ''Working Mother'' magazine's Working Mother of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tmcnet.com/usubmit/2014/10/15/8068797.htm|title=Meghan Stabler Named First Transgender Working Mother of the Year|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019104841/http://www.tmcnet.com/usubmit/2014/10/15/8068797.htm|archivedate=19 October 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** '''[[Laverne Cox]]''' was on the cover of the 9 June 2014 issue of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', and was interviewed for the article \"The Transgender Tipping Point\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewire.com/culture/2014/05/laverne-cox-is-the-first-transgender-person-on-the-cover-of-time/371798/|title=Laverne Cox Is the First Transgender Person on the Cover of Time|first=Eric|last=Levenson|work=The Wire|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/135480/transgender-tipping-point/?pcd=hp-magmod|title=The Transgender Tipping Point|date=29 May 2014|work=TIME.com|first=Katy|last=Steinmetz|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref> She also became the first openly transgender person to be nominated for an [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy]] in an acting category: Outstanding Guest Actress in a Comedy Series for her role as Sophia Burset in ''[[Orange Is the New Black]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2014/07/10/emmy-nominees-list/12428631/|title=2014 Primetime Emmy nominees|date=2014-07-10|publisher=Usatoday.com|accessdate=2014-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.extratv.com/2014/07/10/2014-emmy-awards-orange-is-the-new-blacks-laverne-cox-is-first-transgender-nominee/|title=2014 Emmy Awards: 'Orange Is the New Black's' Laverne Cox Is First Transgender Nominee|date=2014-07-10|publisher=ExtraTV.com|accessdate=2014-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2009/jan/23/angela-morley-obituary-wally-stott|title=Obituary: Angela Morley &#124; Television & radio|newspaper=The Guardian|first=Gavin|last=Gaughan|accessdate=2014-07-19}}</ref>\n** ''[[Transgender Studies Quarterly]]'', the first non-medical academic journal devoted to transgender issues, began publication, with [[Susan Stryker]] and [[Paisley Currah]] as coeditors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/transgender/2014/05/27/duke-univ-press-debuts-academic-journal-transgender-studies|title=Duke Univ. Press Debuts Academic Journal for Transgender Studies|first=Mitch|last=Kellaway|work=Advocate.com|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n** '''[[Mills College]]''' became the first single-sex college in the U.S. to adopt a policy explicitly welcoming transgender students, '''[[Mount Holyoke]]''' became the first [[Seven Sisters (colleges)|Seven Sisters]] college to accept transgender students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/transgender/2014/09/03/watch-first-seven-sisters-schools-admit-trans-women|title=WATCH: First of 'Seven Sisters' Schools to Admit Trans Women|work=Advocate.com|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n** '''[[Blake Brockington]]''' became the first openly transgender high school [[homecoming king]] in [[North Carolina]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.takepart.com/article/2015/03/26/anguish-north-carolina-s-first-openly-trans-prom-king|title=The Anguish of North Carolina's First Transgender Prom King|last=King|first=Jamilah|date=2015-03-25|publisher=TakePart|accessdate=2015-05-01}}</ref>\n** Nina Chaubal and Greta Gustava Martela cofounded [[Trans Lifeline]], '''the first U.S. suicide hotline dedicated to transgender people.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/health/2014/11/25/new-suicide-hotline-dedicated-trans-people-now-open-calls|title=New Suicide Hotline Dedicated to Trans People Now Open for Calls|last=Kellaway|first=Mitch|date=2014-11-25|publi