 this is '''the first time a norte\u00f1o group has ever written a gay love song.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/realidades-mw0002741060/releases|title=Realidades - Los Tigres del Norte &#124; Releases|date=2014-10-07|website=AllMusic|accessdate=2015-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/arts-entertainment/music/2015/03/21/los-tigres-del-norte-are-making-gay-norte-o-history|title=Los Tigres del Norte Are Making Gay Norte\u00f1o History|date=2015-03-21|publisher=Advocate.com|first=Yezmin|last=Villarreal|accessdate=2015-03-25}}</ref>\n* '''Politics:'''\n** The '''UN Human Rights Council''' adopted a second resolution related to sexual orientation and gender identity on 26 September 2014.<ref name=\"MSNBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/un-passes-resolution-behalf-lgbt-citizens-around-the-globe|title=UN passes resolution on behalf of LGBT citizens around the globe|work=MSNBC|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Rappler\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/70315-philippines-unhrc-lgbt-resolution|title=PH votes yes to landmark UN reso on gay rights|work=Rappler|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref> It passed by a vote of 25-14 and is the first time in the Council's history that it adopted a resolution on LGBT rights with the majority of its members.<ref name=\"MSNBC\" /><ref name=\"Rappler\" />\n** [[Lynne Brown]] was appointed as the '''first openly gay cabinet minister in South Africa, which also makes her the first openly gay person to be appointed to a [[cabinet post]] in any African government.'''<ref name=\"Guardian\">[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/may/26/south-africa-appoints-gay-minister-lynne-brown \"South Africa appoints first lesbian to cabinet\"], by David Smith, ''[[The Guardian]]'', Monday 26 May 2014.</ref> [[Zakhele Mbhele]] became the '''first openly gay person to serve in South Africa's parliament, which also makes him the first openly gay black member of parliament in any African nation'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/world/2014/05/30/south-africa-gets-its-first-openly-gay-parliamentarian|title=South Africa Gets Its First Openly Gay Parliamentarian|first=Thom|last=Senzee|work=Advocate.com|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n** '''[[Petra De Sutter]]''' became the first openly transgender person to serve in Belgium's Parliament, specifically its Senate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ebar.com/news/article.php?sec=news&article=69881|title=The Bay Area Reporter Online - Belgium appoints<br />its first transgender MP|work=Bay Area Reporter|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n** '''Luisa Revilla Urcia''' became the first openly transgender person elected to a public office in Peru when she won a seat on the local council in La Esperanza in the province of Trujillo in northwestern Peru.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2014/10/10/peruvian-voters-elect-countrys-first-trans-council-member/|title=Peruvian voters elect country's first trans council member|date=10 October 2014|work=Washington Blade|accessdate=14 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014164835/http://www.washingtonblade.com/2014/10/10/peruvian-voters-elect-countrys-first-trans-council-member/|archivedate=14 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Later, '''[[Carlos Bruce]]''' came out and thus became the first openly gay member of Congress in Peru.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/regions/americas/peru/140523/peruvian-congressman-gay-civil-union-bill|title=Insults, applause, ridiculousness, Peru's first openly gay congressman has seen it all|work=GlobalPost|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n** '''[[Edgars Rink\u0113vi\u010ds]]''' became the first lawmaker in Latvia to announce he is gay, which also makes him the most prominent openly gay politician in a former Soviet Bloc state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaystarnews.com/articles/all#sthash.gtmRuBSD.dpuf|title=Gay Star News - Gay, lesbian, bisexual and transgender global news, entertainment, travel and features|accessdate=8 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141108034929/http://www.gaystarnews.com/articles/all#sthash.gtmRuBSD.dpuf|archivedate=8 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** Poland elected its first openly gay city mayor ('''[[Robert Biedro\u0144]]''', elected mayor of S\u0142upsk.)\n** Matthew Muir was sworn in as '''the first openly gay judge to sit on New Zealand's High Court bench.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/new-zealand-appoints-its-first-openly-gay-high-court-judge-matthew-muir061214#sthash.oB5S5vd8.dpuf|title=New Zealand appoints its first openly gay High Court judge Matthew Muir|work=Gay Star News|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref>\n** The Labor government in Victoria, Australia appointed '''Martin Foley''' as Minister of equality, marking the first time an Australian government has ever had a dedicated Minister overseeing gay, lesbian, bisexual, transgender and intersex issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gayexpress.co.nz/2014/12/australias-first-minister-equality-appointed-victoria/|title=Australia's First Minister of Equality Appointed in Victoria|work=express Online|accessdate=7 December 2014}}</ref>\n** '''Andrew Barr''' became the first openly gay state government leader in Australia after he was sworn in as chief minister of the Australian Capital Territory (ACT).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/australia-elects-first-gay-state-leader111214#sthash.SlQUYyvt.dpuf|title=Australia elects first gay state leader|work=Gay Star News|accessdate=13 December 2014}}</ref>\n** US Politics: \n*** [[Maite Oronoz Rodriguez]] became the '''first openly gay person to be nominated for a seat on Puerto Rico's Supreme Court''', and was confirmed for the seat later that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/first-puerto-rico-lesbian-lawyer-nominated-seat-supreme-court070614|title=A first for Puerto Rico 