 Politics:'''\n*** '''Aisha Moodie-Mills''' became the new president and CEO of the Victory Fund, which made her the first woman, first black woman, first lesbian, and first black lesbian to become the head of a national leading [[LGBT]] organization.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afterellen.com/tv/423309-morning-brew-gillian-anderson-would-date-a-woman-again|title=Morning Brew - Gillian Anderson would date a woman again|last=Bendix|first=Trish|date=2015-03-27|publisher=AfterEllen|accessdate=2015-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/leading-national-lgbt-organization-names-first-wom#.qa8wBvKrq|title=Leading National LGBT Organization Names First Woman, First Black President - BuzzFeed News|date=2013-07-24|publisher=Buzzfeed.com|accessdate=2015-04-17}}</ref>\n*** Pennsylvania State Representative [[Mark B. Cohen]] introduced the first transgender rights bills in Pennsylvania's history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.phillymag.com/g-philly/2015/02/10/rep-mark-cohen-introduces-two-transgender-rights-bills|title=ep. Mark Cohen Introduces Two Transgender Rights Bills|date=10 February 2015|first=Josh|last=Middleton|work=G Philly}}</ref>\n*** '''[[Kate Brown]]''' became the first openly bisexual governor in the United States, as governor of Oregon.<ref name=\"autogenerated5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/politics/meet-americas-first-openly-bisexual-governor/ar-AA9nbjD?ocid=ansnewshp11|title=Meet America's First Openly Bisexual Governor|website=MSN|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612140828/http://www.msn.com/en-us/news/politics/meet-americas-first-openly-bisexual-governor/ar-AA9nbjD?ocid=ansnewshp11|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"oregonlive1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/politics/index.ssf/2015/02/live_updates_kate_brown_become.html|title=Live updates: Kate Brown becomes Oregon governor|date=18 February 2015|work=OregonLive.com|accessdate=2015-02-18}}</ref><ref name=\"Willamette Week\">{{cite news|url=http://www.wweek.com/portland/blog-32833-gov_john_kitzhaber_announces_his_resignation.html|title=Gov. John Kitzhaber Announces His Resignation|date=13 February 2015|newspaper=Willamette Week|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref>\n*** [[Jackie Biskupski]] was elected as '''the first openly gay mayor of Salt Lake City.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/nov/18/jackie-biskupski-elected-as-salt-lake-citys-first-openly-gay-mayor|title=Jackie Biskupski elected as Salt Lake City's first openly gay mayor|work=the Guardian}}</ref>\n*** '''Nancy VanReece''' won the Metro Council District 8 seat in Nashville, thus becoming the first out lesbian elected to a legislative body in Tennessee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outandaboutnashville.com/story/nancy-vanreece-tennessees-first-out-lesbian|title=Nancy VanReece is Tennessee's first out lesbian elected to legislative body &#124; Out & About Nashville|date=|publisher=Outandaboutnashville.com|accessdate=2015-09-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180805143103/https://www.outandaboutnashville.com/story/nancy-vanreece-tennessees-first-out-lesbian|archive-date=5 August 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tennessean.com/story/news/2015/09/10/nancy-vanreece-leads-district-8-early-returns/71963000/|title=Nancy VanReece claims victory in District 8|date=2015-09-10|publisher=Tennessean.com|accessdate=2015-09-14}}</ref>\n*** '''[[Robby Mook]]''' became the first openly gay manager of a major presidential campaign ([[Hillary Clinton]]'s campaign.)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2015/04/robby-mook-hillary-clinton-campaign-manager-profile|title=Robby Mook just took the hardest job in politics: saving the Clintons from themselves.|last=Kroll|first=Andy|last2=Caldwell|first2=Patricia|date=9 April 2015|work=Mother Jones|accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.out.com/news-opinion/2015/4/20/five-things-we-know-about-robby-mook-hillary-clintons-openly-gay-campaign|title=Five Things We Know About Robby Mook, Hillary Clinton's Openly Gay Campaign Manager &#124; Out Magazine|last=McDonald|first=James|publisher=Out.com|accessdate=2015-07-03}}</ref>\n*** [[Randy Berry]] is appointed the '''first Special Envoy for the Human Rights of LGBT Persons.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2015/02/23/388482554/u-s-appoints-first-ever-special-envoy-for-lgbt-rights|title=U.S. Appoints First-Ever Special Envoy For LGBT Rights : The Two-Way|publisher=NPR|first=Eyder|last=Peralta|accessdate=2015-02-24}}</ref>\n*** President Barack Obama became the first president to use the words \"lesbian,\" \"bisexual\", and \"transgender\" in a '''[[State of the Union]] speech'''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/01/20/politics/obama-transgender-sotu/|title=Obama makes historic 'transgender' reference in SOTU - CNN.com|date=21 January 2015|work=CNN|author=Alexandra Jaffe, CNN}}</ref>\n*** President Obama appointed [[Raffi Freedman-Gurspan]] to serve as an Outreach and Recruitment Director in the Presidential Personnel Office, making her '''the first openly transgender appointee to work inside the White House.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/transgender/2015/08/18/obama-appoints-first-trans-woman-white-house-post|title=Obama Appoints First Trans Woman to White House Post|publisher=Advocate.com|first=Bil|last=Browning|accessdate=2015-08-18}}</ref>\n* '''Arts and Culture:'''\n** '''Cambodia''' got its first LGBT magazine, ''Q Cambodia.''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.advocate.com/world/2015/06/04/cambodia-gets-its-first-lgbt-magazine|title=Cambodia Gets Its First LGBT Magazine|publisher=}}</ref>\n** '''Jamaica''' held its first LGBT Pride celebrations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.antillean.org/emancipendence-and-pride-jamaicas-first-official-lgbt-celebrations-signal-turning-tides-876/|title=Jamaica's first LGBT Pride celebrations signal turning tides|publisher=Antillean.org|accessdate=2015-08-09}}</ref>\n** '''[[Zoey Tur]]''' joined ''[[Inside Edition|INSIDE EDITION]]'' as a Special Correspondent during February, thus becoming the first openly transgender television reporter on national TV in America.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rothaussrothaus |first=Steve |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/gay-south-florida/article8951132.html#storylink=cpy |title=Transgender TV news reporter Zoey Tur, formerly Chopper Bob, joins \u2018Inside Edition\u2019 &#124; The Miami Herald The Miami Herald |publisher=Miamiherald.com |date=2015-01-29 |accessdate=2015-02-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2015/02/05/is-americas-transgender-community-ready-for-closeup/22805587/ |title=Is transgender community ready for close-up? |publisher=Usatoday.com |date=2015-01-31 |accessdate=2015-02-06}}</ref>\n** '''[[Thomas Roberts (news anchor)|Thomas Roberts]]''' became the first openly gay evening news anchor on network television when he anchored NBC's \"Nightly News\" for a day.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/thomas-roberts-becomes-first-openly-gay-evening-news-anchor-on-network-tv_55ac128ee4b065dfe89e9a25|title=Thomas Roberts Becomes First Openly Gay Evening News Anchor On Network TV|date=2015-06-25|publisher=Huffingtonpost.com|author=Alana Horowitz Senior Editor, The Huffington Post|accessdate=2015-07-20}}</ref>\n** '''[[Lance Bass]] and Michael Turchin''' became the first same-sex couple to exchange vows on cable television.<ref>{{cite web|last=Drake |first=Aaron|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/marriage-equality/wedding-channel/2015/02/06/photos-relive-lance-bass-wedding-instagram|title=PHOTOS: Relive the Lance Bass Wedding Via Instagram|publisher=The Advocate|date=6 February 2015}}</ref>\n** Screenwriter Jason Rothenberg of ''[[The 100 (TV series)|The 100]]'' confirmed that that TV show's lead character, Clarke Griffin (played by Eliza Taylor) was bisexual; this makes her '''the first openly bisexual lead character on the CW network.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/bisexuality/2015/02/26/cw-has-first-bisexual-lead-character|title=CW Has First Bisexual Lead Character|publisher=Advocate.com|first=Eliel|last=Cruz|accessdate=2015-02-28}}</ref>\n** St. Patrick's Day Parades: The first gay groups '''(Boston Pride and OutVets)''' marched in Boston's St. Patrick's Day parade;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lgbtqnation.com/2015/03/first-time-in-history-gay-groups-march-in-boston-st-patricks-day-parade/|title=Historic first: Gay groups march in Boston St. Patrick's Day parade \u2013 LGBTQ Nation|publisher=Lgbtqnation.com|accessdate=2015-03-16}}</ref> '''OUT@NBCUniversal''', an organization of gay employees of [[NBCUniversal]], became the first gay group to march in the New York City St. Patrick's Day parade;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/first-gay-group-marches-nyc-st-patrick-day-161504393--finance.html;_ylt=A0LEVzfEughV1GQADotx.9w4|title=First gay group marches in NYC St. Patrick's Day parade, protests seek more - Yahoo News|last=Malo|first=Sebastien|publisher=News.yahoo.com|accessdate=2015-03-17|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019104840/http://news.yahoo.com/first-gay-group-marches-nyc-st-patrick-day-161504393--finance.html%3B_ylt%3DA0LEVzfEughV1GQADotx.9w4|archivedate=19 October 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and '''The D.C. Center for the LGBT Community''' became the first gay group to march in the Washington, D.C. St. Patrick's Day parade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wjla.com/articles/2015/03/gay-groups-march-at-last-in-boston-and-d-c-st-patrick-s-day-parades-112330.html|title=Gay groups march at last in Boston and D.C. St. Patrick's Day parades|publisher=WJLA.com|author=|date=15 March 2015 |accessdate=2015-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishcentral.com/news/Gays-to-march-for-first-time-in-Washington-DC-St-Patricks-Day-Parade.html|title=Gays to march for first time in Washington DC St. Patrick's Day Parade|date=2015-02-09|publisher=IrishCentral.com|first=Jane|last=Walsh|accessdate=2015-03-18}}</ref>\n** The National Executive Board of the '''Boy Scouts''' ratified a resolution that removed the national restriction on openly gay adult leaders and employees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scoutingnewsroom.org/blog/boy-scouts-of-america-amends-adult-leadership-policy/|title=Boy Scouts of America Amends Adult Leadership Policy|date=2015-07-27|publisher=Scoutingnewsroom.org|accessdate=2015-08-10|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160902071556/http://scoutingnewsroom.org/blog/boy-scouts-of-america-amends-adult-leadership-policy/|archivedate=2 September 2016}}</ref> '''Pascal Tessier''' became the first openly gay adult Boy Scout in the nation to be hired as a summer camp leader when he was hired by the Boy Scouts\u2019 New York chapter, Greater New York Councils.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fingerlakesdailynews.com/news/details.cfm?clientid=16&id=169992#.VShNBelASM8|title=The Boy Scouts' New York Chapter Make Precedential Hire|date=2015-04-05|publisher=Finger Lakes Daily News|accessdate=2015-04-10|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150417113335/http://fingerlakesdailynews.com/news/details.cfm?clientid=16&id=169992#.VShNBelASM8|archivedate=17 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** In February 2015, [[Patricia Vel\u00e1squez]] released her memoir ''Straight Walk'', discussing her struggles growing up in poverty in Venezuela and how her relationship with [[Sandra Bernhard]] made her realize she was a lesbian.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2015/02/01/supermodel-sandra-bernhard-made-me-realize-i-was-a-lesbian/|title=Supermodel: Sandra Bernhard made me realize I'm a lesbian|last=Callahan|first=Maureen|date=1 February 2015|work=New York Post}}</ref> This makes her the '''world's first openly lesbian Latina supermodel.'''<ref>[http://www.advocate.com/arts-entertainment/books/2015/04/09/story-behind-coming-out-world-s-first-latina-lesbian-supermodel How Patricia Velasquez Was Inspired To Come Out as The World's First Latina Lesbian Supermodel]. Advocate.com (2014-12-20). Retrieved on 2015-04-11.</ref>\n**In April 2015, the '''Rev. \u00c1ngel David Marrero''' is ordained as a pastor in the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America and thus becomes '''the first openly gay (Caribbean) Latino''' ordained in this denomination.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elmundoboston.com/angel-marrero-soy-un-sacerdote-luterano-abiertamente-homosexual|title=\u00c1ngel Marrero: \"Soy un sacerdote abiertamente homosexual\"|publisher=El Mundo Boston|date=13 April 2017 |accessdate=2018-11-10}}</ref>\n** '''[[Andreja Pejic]]''' became the first openly transgender model profiled by ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'', in its May 2015 issue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/news/163205_vogue_profiles_first_ever_transgender_model_andreja_pejic/|title=Vogue Profiles First-Ever Transgender Model Andreja Pejic|publisher=Etonline.com|accessdate=2015-04-22}}</ref>\n** '''[[Laverne Cox]]''' (among others) posed nude for the ''[[Allure (magazine)|Allure]]'' annual \"Nudes\" issue, becoming the first openly transgender actress to do so.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/121653/bruce-jenner-interview-cox-photos-not-transgender-tipping-point|title=Bruce Jenner Interview, Cox Photos Not a Transgender Tipping Point|last=Sasson|first=Eric|magazine=The New Republic|accessdate=2015-04-28}}</ref> She also became the first openly transgender person to have a wax figure of herself at [[Madame Tussauds]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Laverne-Cox-meets-her-was-duplicate-in-wax-6352039.php|title=Laverne Cox meets her duplicate in wax - SFGate|last=Spotswood|first=Beth|publisher=M.sfgate.com|accessdate=2015-06-27}}</ref> She also won a '''Daytime Emmy Award''' in Outstanding Special Class Special as Executive Producer for ''Laverne Cox Presents: The T Word.''<ref name=\"Townsend\">{{cite web|url=https://www.glaad.org/blog/laverne-cox-makes-history-daytime-creative-arts-emmy-win|title=Laverne Cox makes history with Daytime Creative Arts Emmy win|last=Townsend|first=Megan|date=2015-04-25|publisher=GLAAD|accessdate=2017-07-21}}</ref><ref name=\"Out\">{{cite web|url=http://www.out.com/popnography/2015/4/27/laverne-cox-wins-daytime-emmy|title=Laverne Cox Wins Daytime Emmy|date=2015-04-27|publisher=Out.com|accessdate=2016-07-08}}</ref> This made her the '''first openly transgender woman to win a Daytime Emmy as an Executive Producer'''; as well, ''The T Word'' is the first trans documentary to win a Daytime Emmy.<ref name=\"Townsend\" />\n** '''[[Caitlyn Jenner]]''' became the first openly transgender woman on the cover of ''Vanity Fair''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theroot.com/articles/culture/2015/06/_8_transgender_women_of_color_who_are_using_their_visibility_to_empower.html|title=8 Transgender Women of Color Who Are Using Their Visibility to Empower Transgender People of Color|last=Master|first=Samantha|publisher=The Root|accessdate=2015-06-04|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150617090250/http://www.theroot.com/articles/culture/2015/06/_8_transgender_women_of_color_who_are_using_their_visibility_to_empower.html|archivedate=17 June 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** [[Fun Home (musical)|Fun Home]], '''the first Broadway musical with a lesbian protagonist''', premiered on Broadway.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/03/31/fun-home-broadway-_n_6955634.html|title='Fun Home' Brings Lesbian Protagonist To Broadway For The First Time|date=2015-03-31|publisher=Huffingtonpost.com|author=03/31/2015 12:02 pm EDT|accessdate=2015-05-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorkcitytheatre.com/theaters/circleinthesquaretheater/fun-home.php|title=Circle in the Square New York, NY - Fun Home - tickets, information, reviews|publisher=Newyorkcitytheatre.com|accessdate=2015-05-31}}</ref>\n** The '''first American federally approved monument honoring LGBT veterans''' was dedicated; it is located at the [[Abraham Lincoln National Cemetery]] in Elwood, Illinois.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abc7chicago.com/society/monument-to-lgbt-veterans-dedicated-in-elwood/741262/|title=Monument to LGBT veterans dedicated in Elwood|publisher=abc7chicago.com|accessdate=2015-05-26}}</ref>\n** On 29 May 2015, the '''[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]''' announced it would officially consider designating the Stonewall Inn as a landmark, the first city location to be considered based on its LGBT cultural significance alone.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://gaycitynews.nyc/exclusive-stonewall-inn-appears-headed-city-landmark-status-gay-first/|title=EXCLUSIVE: Stonewall Inn Appears Headed for City Landmark Status - A Gay First|date=29 May 2015|magazine=Gay City News|last1=Humm|first1=Andy|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref> On 23 June 2015, the New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission unanimously approved the designation of the Stonewall Inn as a city landmark, making it the first landmark honored for its role in the fight for gay rights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2015/06/23/landmark-hearing-stonewall-inn/|title=Stonewall Inn Designated A New York City Landmark \"CBS New York|date=1987-07-01|publisher=Newyork.cbslocal.com|author=Jim Smith reports|accessdate=2015-06-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150623205732/http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2015/06/23/landmark-hearing-stonewall-inn/|archive-date=23 June 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n** The '''[[Royal Vauxhall Tavern]]''' became the first ever building in the UK to be given a special \"listing\" status based on its LGBT history; it was accorded Grade II listed status by the UK's Department of Culture, Media and Sport.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2015/09/09/this-london-pub-just-made-gay-history-but-can-it-be-saved.html|title=This London Pub Just Made Gay History\u2014but Can It Be Saved?|website=The Daily Beast|first=Tim|last=Teeman|accessdate=2015-09-10}}</ref>\n** The UK-based bisexual women's website Biscuit created the '''Purple List'''; the first known list of its kind, the Purple List seeks to recognize bisexuals who have contributed to fighting biphobia and increasing bisexual visibility.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shewired.com/news/2015/07/29/14-women-heroes-biscuit-magazines-1st-annual-purple-list-recognizing-bisexual-achiev|title=14 Women Heroes Of Biscuit Mag's 1st Annual 'Purple List,' Recognizing Bisexual Achievement|last=Dingle|first=Charlotte|date=2015-07-29|publisher=SheWired|accessdate=2015-08-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisbiscuit.co.uk/biscuit-purple-list-2015/|title=The Biscuit Purple List 2015 &#124; Biscuit|date=2015-07-24|publisher=Thisisbiscuit.co.uk|author=Biscuit|accessdate=2015-08-05}}</ref>\n** [[Jacob Anderson-Minshall]] became '''the first openly transgender author to win a Goldie award from the [[Golden Crown Literary Society]]'''; he shared the award for best creative non-fiction book with [[Diane Anderson-Minshall]] for ''Queerly Beloved: A Love Story Across Genders''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/arts-entertainment/books/2015/07/28/historic-night-golden-crown-literary-awards|title=Historic Night at Golden Crown Literary Awards|date=2015-07-28|publisher=Advocate.com|author=Advocate.com Editors|accessdate=2015-08-06}}</ref>\n** '''[[Audrey Middleton]]''' became the U.S. television show Big Brother's first openly transgender houseguest.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/big-brother-transgender-houseguest-audrey-middleton-5-things-to-know-2015246|title=Big Brother Transgender Houseguest Audrey Middleton: 5 Things to Know - Us Weekly|last=Corneau|first=Allison|date=2014-07-31|magazine=Usmagazine.com|accessdate=2015-06-24}}</ref>\n** [[Scott Turner Schofield]] became '''the first openly transgender actor to play a major role on daytime television''', as the character Nick on the show ''[[The Bold and the Beautiful]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsmax.com/TheWire/scott-turner-schofield-bold-and-the-beautiful-transgender/2015/04/29/id/641441/#ixzz3YhwOaxtv|title='The Bold and the Beautiful' Casts Transgender Actor Scott Turner Schofield|publisher=Newsmax.com|accessdate=2015-04-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inquisitr.com/2050754/bold-and-beautiful-spices-up-transgender-storyline-first-transgender-actor-cast-as-mayas-old-friend/|title=\u2018Bold And Beautiful\u2019 Spices Up Transgender Storyline: First Transgender Actor Cast As Maya's Old Friend|publisher=Inquisitr.com|first=Heather|last=Tooley|accessdate=2015-04-29}}</ref> On the same show, the character '''[[Maya Avant]]''' (played by [[Karla Mosley]]) became the first transgender bride to be married on daytime television when she married Rick Forrester (played by [[Jacob Young]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newnownext.com/daytime-tvs-first-transgender-bride-gets-hitched-on-the-bold-and-the-beautiful/08/2015/|title=Daytime TV's First Transgender Bride Gets Hitched On \"The Bold and the Beautiful\"|last=Tharrett|first=Matthew|publisher=NewNowNext|accessdate=2015-08-12}}</ref>\n** '''[[Hari Nef]]''' became the first openly transgender model signed to IMG.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.takepart.com/article/2015/08/16/otherstories|title=Fashion Shoot's All-Transgender Crew Breaks Another Barrier|publisher=TakePart|accessdate=2015-08-17}}</ref>\n** '''Andrew Guy''' became Australia's first openly transgender TV host, as a guest presenter on ''[[The Project (Australian TV program)|The Project]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/the-project-welcomes-australias-first-transgender-tv-host-andrew-guy-20150908-gjhach.html|title=The Project welcomes Australia's first transgender TV host, Andrew Guy|date=8 September 2015|newspaper=Smh.com.au|first=Michael|last=Lallo|accessdate=2015-09-08}}</ref>\n** The '''first Scottish LGBTI Awards''' were held.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/all-the-winners-of-the-first-scottish-lgbti-awards/|title=All the winners of the first Scottish LGBTI Awards|date=11 September 2015|publisher=Gay Star News|first=Tris|last=Reid-Smith|accessdate=2015-09-13}}</ref>\n** '''[[Neil Patrick Harris]]''' became the first openly gay man to host the [[Academy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mobi.iafrica.com/movies/2015/02/23/neil-patrick-harris-wows-as-oscars-host/|title=Neil Patrick Harris wows as Oscars host|publisher=iafrica.com|date=23 February 2015|accessdate=2015-02-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223144809/http://mobi.iafrica.com/movies/2015/02/23/neil-patrick-harris-wows-as-oscars-host/|archive-date=23 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n** The first Oscar campaigns for openly transgender actresses supported by a movie producer were launched for actresses '''Kitana Kiki Rodriguez and Mya Taylor''' of the movie ''[[Tangerine (film)|Tangerine]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spectrum.suntimes.com/culture-lifestyle/10/155/3706/magnolia-pictures-pushes-oscars-nod-trans-actresses|title=Magnolia Pictures pushes Oscars nod for trans actresses &#124; Spectrum|publisher=Spectrum.suntimes.com|accessdate=2015-10-07|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019104841/http://spectrum.suntimes.com/culture-lifestyle/10/155/3706/magnolia-pictures-pushes-oscars-nod-trans-actresses|archivedate=19 October 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** ''[[EastEnders]]'' chose Riley Carter Millington as '''the first openly transgender actor in UK TV soap history'''; he played \u2018Kyle\u2019, a man who has transitioned from female to male, which Riley did in real life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/eastenders-introduce-first-transgender-actor-6598842|title=EastEnders to introduce the first transgender actor in TV soap history as 'Kyle' appears in Walford - Mirror Online|last=Jefferies|first=Mark|date=2015-10-08|publisher=Mirror.co.uk|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref> Shortly after, ''[[Hollyoaks]]'' cast transgender actress Annie Wallace.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/hollyoaks-reveals-first-transgender-actress-6612824|title=Hollyoaks reveals first transgender actress as Hayley Cropper inspiration joins soap - Mirror Online|last=McGeorge|first=Alistair|date=2015-10-03|publisher=Mirror.co.uk|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref>\n** '''[[Inga Beale]]''',  CEO of [[Lloyd's of London]], became the first woman and the first openly bisexual person to be named number one in the OUTstanding & FT Leading LGBT executive power list.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/oct/20/lloyds-of-london-inga-beale-first-woman-top-lgbt-power-list|title=Lloyd's of London boss is first woman to top LGBT power list &#124; Business|date=2015|newspaper=The Guardian|first=Julia|last=Kollewe|accessdate=2015-10-20}}</ref>\n** '''Loiza Lamers''' won \"[[Holland's Next Top Model]]\", making her the first openly transgender winner of the \"Top Model\" franchise.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/transgender-model-wins-hollands-next-top-model_562fb47ae4b0c66bae59ab27|title=Transgender Model Wins 'Holland's Next Top Model'|date=2015-06-01|publisher=Huffingtonpost.com|accessdate=2015-10-28}}</ref>\n** '''[[Mya Taylor]]''' won the [[Gotham Independent Film Awards 2015|Gotham Award for Breakthrough Actor]], making her the first openly transgender actress to win a Gotham award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bet.com/news/celebrities/2015/12/01/mya-taylor-becomes-the-first-transgendera-actress-to-win-a-gotham-award.html|title=Mya Taylor Becomes the First Transgender Actress to Win a Gotham Award|date=1 December 2015|work=BET.com}}</ref>\n** In March 2015 '''Rabbi [[Denise Eger]] became the first openly gay president of the [[Central Conference of American Rabbis]]''', which is the largest and oldest rabbinical organization in North America.<ref name=\"Cutler\">Tess Cutler, [http://www.jewishjournal.com/religion/article/rabbi_denise_eger_seeks_to_open_doors_wider_to_all_jews \"Rabbi Denise Eger seeks to open doors wider to all Jews\"], ''[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles]]'', 4 March 2015.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jta.org/2015/03/16/news-opinion/united-states/reform-rabbis-install-first-openly-gay-president-denise-eger|title=Reform rabbis install first openly gay president, Denise Eger &#124; Jewish Telegraphic Agency|publisher=Jta.org|accessdate=2015-03-16}}</ref>\n**  '''[[Abby Stein]]''' came out as transgender and thus became the first openly transgender woman (and the first woman) to have been ordained by an ultra-Orthodox institution, having received her rabbinical degree in 2011 from Yeshiva Viznitz in South Fallsburg, N.Y. However, this was before she was openly transgender, and she is no longer working as a rabbi as of 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejewishweek.com/special-sections/36-under-36/abby-stein-24|title=36 Under 36 - Abby Stein|date=24 May 2016|newspaper=The Jewish Week|author=Amy Sara Clark|accessdate=12 November 2016}}</ref> She is also the first openly transgender woman raised in a [[Hasidic]] community, and is a direct descendant of Hasidic Judaism's founder the [[Baal Shem Tov]].<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/jewish/news/1.687051 \"Descendant of Hasidic Judaism Founder Comes Out as Transgender\"], [[Jewish Telegraphic Agency|JTA]], 19 November 2015</ref>\n*  '''Family/Relationships:'''\n** '''Thomas Sawicki and his boyfriend Shawn Brier''' became the first male same-sex couple chosen to share the first kiss upon a U.S. Navy ship's return.<ref>{{cite web|author=<!--ARTICLE IN BLOGLAND--> Heather Culver |url=http://www.nbcsandiego.com/news/local/San-Diego-Couple-Shares-First-Ever-Male-Same-Sex-Ceremonial-First-Kiss-291344541.html |title=San Diego Couple Shares First-Ever Male Same-Sex Ceremonial First Kiss &#124; NBC 7 San Diego |publisher=Nbcsandiego.com |date=2015-02-09 |accessdate=2015-02-13}}</ref>\n** '''Mikhail Ivan Gallatinov and Mark Goodwin''' became the first couple to have a same-sex wedding in a UK prison after marrying at Full Sutton Prison in East Yorkshire.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.frontiersmedia.com/frontiers-blog/2015/04/02/two-murderers-become-first-same-sex-couple-to-marry-in-uk-prison/|title=Two Murderers Become First Same-Sex Couple to Marry in UK Prison|date=2015-04-02|publisher=Frontiers Media|accessdate=2015-04-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150415012248/http://www.frontiersmedia.com/frontiers-blog/2015/04/02/two-murderers-become-first-same-sex-couple-to-marry-in-uk-prison/|archive-date=15 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n** '''Argentina''' became Latin America's first nation to recognize same-sex partners and a biological parent on a child's birth certificate; specifically, it allowed a lesbian couple and their son's biological father, who donated sperm for their pregnancy, to be included on the child's birth certificate.<ref name=\"advocate1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/world/2015/05/03/argentina-makes-history-three-parent-birth-certificate|title=Argentina Makes History With Three-Parent Birth Certificate|publisher=Advocate.com|first=Thom|last=Senzee|accessdate=2015-05-04}}</ref> The child's name is Antonio and his two mothers are Susana Guichal and Valeria Gaete, and his father is Hernan Melazzi.<ref name=\"advocate1\" />\n** When '''President Obama''' declared May to be [[National Foster Care Month]] in 2015, he became the first president to explicitly say gender identity should not prevent anyone from adopting or becoming a foster parent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/transgender/2015/05/01/obama-calls-end-discriminatory-parenting-laws|title=Obama Calls for End to Discriminatory Parenting Laws|publisher=Advocate.com|first=Dawn|last=Ennis|accessdate=2015-05-04}}</ref>\n** '''Shawn MacIver and James Moccia''' became the first openly gay couple to graduate from a police academy together when they graduated from the Boston Police Academy<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boston.cbslocal.com/2015/06/17/first-openly-gay-couple-joins-boston-police-force/|title=First Openly Gay Couple Joins Boston Police Force|publisher=CBS Boston|accessdate=2015-06-18}}</ref>\n** Tokyo's Shibuya ward passed a local ordinance granting same-sex couples the right to partnership certificates; this makes it '''the first place in Japan \u2014 or anywhere in East Asia \u2014 to recognize same-sex partnerships.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/parallels/2015/05/11/404822093/the-first-place-in-east-asia-to-welcome-same-sex-marriage|title=The First Place In East Asia To Welcome Same-Sex Marriage : Parallels|date=11 May 2015|publisher=NPR|accessdate=2015-05-12}}</ref>\n** Ireland became '''the first country to legalize same-sex marriage by popular vote.'''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global/live/2015/may/23/counting-underway-for-irelands-referendum-on-marriage-equality|title=Ireland becomes first country to legalise same-sex marriage by popular vote - as it happened &#124; Society|date=1970-01-01|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=2015-05-23}}</ref>\n* '''Trans:''' \n** On 12 February 2015, ''[[USA Today]]'' reported that the commandant of Fort Leavenworth wrote in a 5 February memo, \"After carefully considering the recommendation that (hormone treatment) is medically appropriate and necessary, and weighing all associated safety and security risks presented, I approve adding (hormone treatment) to Inmate [Chelsea] Manning's treatment plan.\" According to ''USA Today'', [[Chelsea Manning]] remains a soldier, and '''the decision to administer hormone therapy is a first for the U.S. Army.'''<ref>{{cite news|author=Tom Vanden Brook |title=Military approves hormone therapy for Chelsea Manning |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2015/02/12/chelsea-manning-hormone-therapy/23311813/ |date=12 February 2015 |accessdate=12 February 2015 |newspaper=USA Today}}</ref>\n** In a first for the state, '''California's Department of Corrections''' was ordered by a federal judge to grant a transgender prisoner (Michelle-Lael Norsworthy) access to gender-affirming surgery.<ref>{{cite web|first= Mitch |last= Kellaway |url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/transgender/2015/04/06/federal-judge-california-must-provide-trans-inmate-access-gender-aff |title=Federal Judge: California Must Provide Trans Inmate with Access to Gender-Affirming Surgery |publisher=Advocate.com |date=2015-04-06 |accessdate=2015-04-10}}</ref>\n** The inaugural '''White House Trans Women Of Color [[Women's History Month]] Briefing''' was held.<ref>{{cite web|last=Roberts |first=Monica |url=http://transgriot.blogspot.com/2015/03/historic-day-for-trans-woc-at-white.html |title=TransGriot: Historic Day For Trans WOC At The White House |publisher=Transgriot.blogspot.com |date=2015-03-31 |accessdate=2015-04-10}}</ref>\n** The '''U.S. Justice Department''' announced that it had filed its first civil lawsuit on behalf of a transgender person (Rachel Tudor); the lawsuit was ''United States of America v. Southeastern Oklahoma State University and the Regional University System of Oklahoma'', filed in federal court in that state.<ref>{{cite web|first= Dawn |last= Ennis |url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/2015/03/31/history-oklahoma-feds-sue-school-trans-discrimination |title=History in Oklahoma: Feds Sue School for Trans Discrimination |publisher=Advocate.com |date=2015-03-31 |accessdate=2015-04-10}}</ref>\n** '''Maka Brown''', an 18-year-old senior at the Salt Lake School for Performing Arts, was crowned Utah's first openly transgender prom queen.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/transgender-teen-crowned-prom-queen-utah-school-article-1.2205500 |title=Transgender teen crowned prom queen at Utah school |newspaper=NY Daily News |accessdate=2015-05-01 |location=New York |date=30 April 2015}}</ref>\n** ''[http://www.hrc.org/resources/entry/schools-in-transition-a-guide-for-supporting-transgender-students-in-k-12-s Schools In Transition: A Guide for Supporting Transgender Students in K-12 Schools]'' was introduced; it is '''a first-of-its-kind publication for school administrations, teachers, and parents about how to provide safe and supportive environments for all transgender students in kindergarten through twelfth grade.'''<ref name=\"lgbtweekly1\">{{cite web|url=http://lgbtweekly.com/2015/08/03/groundbreaking-guide-helps-schools-provide-supportive-environments-for-transgender-students/|title=Groundbreaking guide helps schools provide supportive environments for transgender students|date=2011-02-14|publisher=LGBT Weekly|accessdate=2015-08-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150804145903/http://lgbtweekly.com/2015/08/03/groundbreaking-guide-helps-schools-provide-supportive-environments-for-transgender-students/|archive-date=4 August 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n** Philadelphia flew the '''[[transgender pride flag]]''' above City Hall for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/transgender/2015/06/04/philadelphia-raises-transgender-pride-flag-first-time|title=Philadelphia Raises the Transgender Pride Flag for the First Time|publisher=}}</ref>\n** '''[[Manabi Bandopadhyay]]''', India's first openly transgender college principal, began work; she worked as the principal of the [[Krishnagar Women's College]] in Nadia district.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.webindia123.com/news/Articles/India/20150609/2613362.html|title=India's first transgender college principal starts work|publisher=}}</ref>\n** '''A transgender man's [[phalloplasty]] became the first ever seen on camera''', in the Channel 4 documentary ''Girls to Men''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/transgender-male-penis-construction-filmed-6627302|title=Transgender male has penis construction filmed in world first for groundbreaking Channel 4 documentary - Mirror Online|last=Corner|first=Natalie|date=|publisher=Mirror.co.uk|accessdate=2015-10-14}}</ref>\n** The '''first U.S. congressional forum on anti-transgender violence''' was held.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrc.org/blog/entry/hrc-president-chad-griffin-testifies-at-first-ever-congressional-forum-on-a|title=HRC President Chad Griffin Testifies at First-Ever Congressional Forum on Anti-Transgender Violence &#124; Human Rights Campaign|date=|publisher=Hrc.org|accessdate=2015-11-18}}</ref>\n** The (American) Department of Veterans Affairs opened its '''first clinic for transgender service members'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.huffpost.com/us/entry/5643e4c5e4b08cda34877647|title=Veterans Affairs Opens First Clinic For Transgender Service Members|date=2015-08-25|publisher=M.huffpost.com|accessdate=2015-11-26}}</ref>\n** '''Aydian Dowling''' became the first openly transgender man on the cover of ''[[Men's Health (magazine)|Men's Health]]'' magazine, as part of a special collector's edition.\n* '''Intersex:'''\n** In April 2015, '''Malta''' became the first country in the world to outlaw [[sterilization (medicine)|sterilization]] and invasive surgery on [[intersex]] people.<ref name=\"parlament1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parlament.mt/billdetails?bid=494&l=1&legcat=13 |title=Parlament Ta' Malta |accessdate=24 July 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402043931/http://www.parlament.mt/billdetails?bid=494&l=1&legcat=13 |archivedate=2 April 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=\"parlament1\" /><ref name=\"gaynewsnetwork1\">{{cite web|url=http://gaynewsnetwork.com.au/news/world/malta-scraps-surgery-and-sterilisation-measures-and-passes-protections-for-intersex-people-17181.html|title=Malta scraps surgery and setrislation measures and passes protections for intersex people - Gay News Network|first=Cec|last=Busby|work=Gay News Network|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126132217/http://gaynewsnetwork.com.au/news/world/malta-scraps-surgery-and-sterilisation-measures-and-passes-protections-for-intersex-people-17181.html|archivedate=26 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"gaynewsnetwork1\" />\n* '''Sports:'''\n** On May 22, 2015, '''[[Michael Sam]]''' signed a two-year contract with [[Montreal Alouettes]] of the CFL,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cfl.ca/article/d-lineman-michael-sam-signs-with-alouettes|title=D-lineman Michael Sam signs with Alouettes|author=<!-- Staff writers -->|date=May 22, 2015|accessdate=May 22, 2015|work=CFL.ca|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150525005537/http://www.cfl.ca/article/d-lineman-michael-sam-signs-with-alouettes|archivedate=May 25, 2015}}</ref><ref name=alouettes>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/football/2015/05/22/michael-sam-joins-alouettes-first-openly-gay-cfl-player.html|title=Michael Sam joins Alouettes, first openly gay CFL player|last=Campbell|first=Morgan|work=[[Toronto Star]]|date=May 22, 2015|accessdate=May 22, 2015}}</ref> which made him the first openly gay player in the league's history.<ref name=alouettes/>\n** '''[[Michael Sam]]''' made his CFL debut on August 7, 2015, against the [[Ottawa Redblacks]], and thus became the first publicly gay player to play in a CFL regular season game. He did not record a tackle in the game.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/michael-sam-is-1st-openly-gay-man-to-play-in-cfl-regular-season-game-1.3183929 | title=Michael Sam is 1st openly gay man to play in CFL regular season game | publisher=cbc.ca | date=August 7, 2015 | accessdate=August 9, 2015}}</ref><ref name=ap_08142015>{{cite news|title=Michael Sam Says He's Leaving Montreal's Alouettes |date=August 14, 2015 |newspaper=The New York Times |agency=AP |url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2015/08/14/world/ap-fbo-cfl-sam-departs.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6amy7cXuo?url=http://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2015/08/14/world/ap-fbo-cfl-sam-departs.html?_r=0 |archivedate=August 15, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n** '''[[Chris Mosier]]''' became the first known out trans athlete to join a U.S. national team that matched his gender identity, rather than the gender assigned him at birth, when he won a spot on Team USA in the men's sprint duathalon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/sports/2015/06/08/triathlete-chris-mosier-joins-men-team-usa-making-transgender-sports-history|title=Triathlete Chris Mosier Joins Men of Team USA, Making Transgender Sports History|publisher=}}</ref>\n** '''Sean Conroy''' became the first openly gay baseball player to appear in a professional game; Conroy pitched nine scoreless innings to lead the Sonoma Stompers to a 7-0 win over the Vallejo Admirals in the Pacific Association of Baseball Clubs, an independent league featuring teams from Northern California.<ref>{{cite web|last=Corcoran |first=Cliff |url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2015/06/26/openly-gay-professional-baseball-player-sean-conroy-sonoma-stompers |title=Sean Conroy becomes first openly gay professional baseball player - MLB |publisher=SI.com |accessdate=2015-06-26}}</ref>\n** '''[[Benjamin Thomas Watt]]''' from New Zealand became the first openly gay professional boxing judge.<ref>{{cite web|author=Boxrec |url=http://boxrec.com/media/index.php/Benjamin_Watt |title=Benjamin Watt |publisher=Boxrec |accessdate=2015-08-14}}</ref>\n** '''[[David Denson]]''' came out as gay, making him the first active minor league player affiliated with a Major League Baseball organization to do so.<ref name=\"jsonline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jsonline.com/sports/brewers/brewers-minor-leaguer-makes-baseball-history-by-coming-out-publicly-as-gay-b99557156z1-321977731.html|title=Brewers minor-leaguer makes baseball history by coming out publicly as gay|first=Tom|last=Haudricourt|work=jsonline.com|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref>\n** '''Keegan Hirst''' became the first British rugby league professional to come out as gay.<ref>{{cite news|first=Josh |last=Halliday |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/aug/16/keegan-hirst-first-rugby-league-player-come-out-gay |title=Keegan Hirst steps on to field as Britain's first rugby league star to come out as gay &#124; Sport |newspaper=The Guardian |date=16 August 2015|accessdate=2015-08-17}}</ref>\n** '''Sam Stanley''', nephew of [[Joe Stanley]], became the first English rugby union player to come out as gay.<ref>{{cite news|author=Observer Sport |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/aug/30/sam-stanley-england-sevens-first-rugby-union-professional-gay |title=Sam Stanley becomes first English rugby union player to come out as gay &#124; Sport |newspaper=The Guardian |date=2015|accessdate=2015-08-30}}</ref>\n** Chris Burns, an assistant coach at Bryant University, came out as gay, thus becoming the '''first openly gay coach in Division I men's basketball.'''<ref>{{cite web|first=Alec |last=Nathan |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2577063-chris-burns-becomes-1st-openly-gay-mens-basketball-coach-in-division-I |title=Chris Burns Becomes 1st Openly Gay Men's Basketball Coach in Division I |website=Bleacher Report |accessdate=2015-10-08}}</ref>\n** [[Breanna Sinclair\u00e9]] became '''the first openly transgender person to sing the national anthem at a professional sporting event''', which she did at a [[Major League Baseball]] game.<ref>{{cite web|first= Brian |last= Schaefer |url=http://www.out.com/music/2015/6/17/opera-singer-breanna-sinclaire-1st-trans-woman-sing-national-anthem-professional |title=Opera singer Breanna Sinclaire: 1st trans woman to sing national anthem at professional sporting event |publisher=Out.com |date=2015-06-17 |accessdate=2017-02-13}}</ref>\n** '''[[Phuti Lekoloane]]''' came out and thus became South Africa\u2019s first openly gay male footballer.<ref name=\"Phuti\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mambaonline.com/2016/07/22/phuti-lekoloane-south-africas-first-openly-gay-male-footballer/|title=This is Phuti Lekoloane \u2013 South Africa's first openly gay male footballer|last=DeBarros|first=Luiz|date=July 22, 2016|website=Mamba Online|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-07-20}}</ref>\n* '''Military:'''\n* '''Adrianna Vorderbruggen''' died in combat; she is believed to be the first American active duty, openly gay, female service member to die in combat, and is the first openly gay American Air Force officer to die in combat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2015/12/22/u-s-military-s-first-openly-gay-woman-killed-in-combat.html|title=U.S. Military's First Openly Gay Woman Killed in Combat|work=The Daily Beast}}</ref>\n\n==2016==\n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Passed and came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Colombia|Colombia]], [[same-sex marriage in the Isle of Man|Isle of Man]], The Mexican states of [[Same-sex marriage in Jalisco|Jalisco]], [[Same-sex marriage in Campeche|Campeche]], [[Same-sex marriage in Colima|Colima]], [[Same-sex marriage in Michoac\u00e1n|Michoac\u00e1n]] and [[Same-sex marriage in Morelos|Morelos]], [[LGBT rights in Greenland|Greenland,]] [[Same-sex marriage in Gibraltar|Gibraltar]], [[Same-sex marriage in the United Kingdom|British Antarctic Territory]]\n** '''Passed''': [[Same-sex marriage in the Faroe Islands|Faroe Islands]], [[Same-sex marriage in Guernsey|Guernsey]], [[Same-sex marriage in Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha|Ascension Island]]\n* '''Civil Union/Registered Partnership laws''':\n** '''Passed and came into effect''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Italy|Italy]], [[Same-sex marriage in Aruba, Cura\u00e7ao and Sint Maarten|Aruba]]\n** '''Came into effect''': [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Estonia|Estonia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riigiteataja.ee/akt/KooS|title=Kooseluseadus|publisher=}}</ref>\n* '''Same-sex couple adoption legislation''': [[LGBT rights in Portugal|Portugal]]<ref name=\"ft.dk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.dk/sam