Trudeau becomes first Canadian PM to march at Pride|magazine=Metro Weekly|accessdate=2016-07-05}}</ref>\n** [[Geraldine Roman]] became '''the first openly transgender woman elected to Congress in the Philippines.'''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/05/10/asia/philippines-transgender-geraldine-roman/|title=Philippines elects first transgender woman|date=10 May 2016|work=CNN|first=Robert|last=Sawatzky}}</ref>\n** The '''UN Security Council''' condemned the [[2016 Orlando nightclub shooting]]; this statement marked the first time the U.N. Security Council used language recognizing violence targeting the LGBT community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.voanews.com/a/un-acknowledges-human-rights-violation-against-lgbt-community/3374946.html|title=UN Acknowledges Human Rights Violation Against LGBT Community|date=2016-06-14|publisher=M.voanews.com|accessdate=2016-07-05}}</ref>\n* '''Arts and Culture:'''\n** in August, using a high-altitude balloon, activists '''launched the first pride flag into the Stratosphere''' as it floated 21.1 miles (34.1&nbsp;km).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-37504749 |title=Gay pride flag launched into space 'to spread peace' - BBC News |publisher=Bbc.com |date= |accessdate=2019-07-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Noel |last=Gutierrez-Morfin |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/first-pride-flag-launched-sky-outer-space-now-lgbt-friendly-n655691 |title=First Pride Flag Launched Into Stratosphere |publisher=Nbcnews.com |date= |accessdate=2019-07-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/celebrity/pride-flag-launched-into-space-by-planting-peace/|title=First Pride Flag Launched Into Outer Space|date=28 September 2016|website=PEOPLE.com}}</ref>\n** On 24 June 2016, President [[Barack Obama]] officially designated the '''[[Stonewall National Monument]]''', making it the United States' first National Monument designated for an LGBT historic site. The National Monument status encompasses the Stonewall Inn, Christopher Street Park, and the block of Christopher Street bordering the park.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/25/nyregion/stonewall-inn-named-national-monument-a-first-for-gay-rights-movement.html|title=Stonewall Inn Named National Monument, a First for the Gay Rights Movement|date=24 June 2016|first=Eli|last=Rosenberg|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=25 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/obama-designates-stonewall-national-monument-lgbt-rights/story?id=40107660|title=Obama Designates Stonewall as First National Monument for LGBT Rights|date=2016-06-24|website=ABC News|last1=Mallin|first1=Alexander|accessdate=25 June 2016}}</ref>\n** The house at 219 11th St. SE which was home to the [[Furies Collective]] was named as '''the first lesbian-related historic landmark in Washington, D.C.''' when it was unanimously voted into the D.C. Inventory of Historic Sites.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hillnow.com/2016/01/29/capitol-hill-rowhome-becomes-d-c-s-first-lesbian-related-historic-landmark/|title=Capitol Hill Rowhome Becomes D.C.'s First Lesbian-Related Historic Landmark|publisher=}}</ref>\n** Edificio Comunidad de Orgullo Gay became the '''first Latino LGBT site on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].'''<ref name=\"metroweekly.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metroweekly.com/2016/05/furies-collective-becomes-first-lesbian-site-national-register/|title=Furies Collective becomes first lesbian site on National Register|work=Metro Weekly}}</ref>\n** '''[[Mya Taylor]]''' became the first openly transgender actor to win an [[Independent Spirit Awards|Independent Spirit Award]]; she won for Best Supporting Female.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/video/mya-taylor-wins-best-supporting-870473|title=Mya Taylor Wins Best Supporting Female for 'Tangerine' at the 2016 Spirit Awards|date=27 February 2016|author=THR Staff|work=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n** '''Erin O\u2019Flaherty''' became the first openly gay Miss Missouri, which also made her the first openly lesbian Miss America candidate.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/beauty/lesbian-queen-erin-oflaherty-becomes-miss-missouri-and-makes-miss-america-history-by-being-the-first-openly-gay-contestant/news-story/097e5537bfd3e2acc5e8b9168c10e879|title=Lesbian queen Erin O\u00e2\u20ac\u2122Flaherty becomes Miss Missouri and makes Miss America history by being the first openly gay contestant|work=News.com.au|author=24 June, 20161:42am|accessdate=2016-06-23}}</ref>\n** Through her Foundation, [[Jennifer Pritzker]] gave a $2 million donation to create the '''world's first endowed academic chair of [[transgender studies]]''', at the [[University of Victoria in British Columbia]]; [[Aaron Devor]] was chosen as the inaugural chair.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tabletmag.com/scroll/196981/jennifer-pritzkers-foundation-gives-2-million-for-transgender-studies-at-canadian-university|title=Jennifer Pritzker's Foundation Gives $2 Million for Transgender Studies at Canadian University|work=Tablet Magazine}}</ref> The '''[[United Nations]]''' voted to create their first LGBT human rights watchdog.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.gaytimes.co.uk/news/41276/united-nations-votes-create-first-lgbt-rights-watchdog/|title=United Nations votes to create first LGBT rights watchdog|date=2016-07-01|magazine=Gay Times|accessdate=2016-07-05}}</ref>\n** Nur Warsame came out and thus became '''Australia's first openly gay Imam.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/news/thefeed/article/2016/05/02/meet-australias-first-openly-gay-imam|title=Meet Australia's first openly gay Imam|work=News}}</ref>\n** The United Methodist church elected its first openly gay bishop, '''Karen Oliveto.'''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jul/16/united-methodist-church-first-openly-gay-bishop|title=United Methodist church elects first openly gay bishop despite marriage ban &#124; World news|date=2016|newspaper=The Guardian|author=Martin Pengelly and agencies|accessdate=2016-07-17}}</ref>\n** [[Nicholas Chamberlain]] was '''the first bishop in the Church of England to [[coming out|come out]] as gay''', which occurred following threats of an [[outing]] from an unnamed [[Sunday newspaper]]. He said he lived with his partner in a [[celibate]] same-sex relationship, as required by the Bishops' guidelines, under which [[LGBT clergy in Christianity|gay clergy]] must practice [[abstinence]] and may not marry.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/sep/02/nicholas-chamberlain-bishop-of-grantham-c-of-e-gay-relationship|title=Bishop of Grantham first C of E bishop to declare he is in gay relationship|last=Sherwood|first=Harriet|date=2 September 2016|work=The Guardian|accessdate=2 September 2016}}</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/09/02/bishop-of-grantham-becomes-first-church-of-england-bishop-to-com/ The Telegraph \u2014 Bishop of Grantham becomes first Church of England bishop to come out publicly as gay] (Accessed 3 September 2016)</ref><ref>[http://changingattitude.org.uk/archives/8747 Press release \u2014 Changing Attitude England welcomes Bishop Nick Chamberlain's openness] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160903235748/http://changingattitude.org.uk/archives/8747 |date=3 September 2016 }} (Accessed 3 September 2016)</ref><ref>[http://www.lgcm.org.uk/news/the-bishop-of-grantham/ Lesbian and Gay Christian Movement \u2014 The Bishop of Grantham] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916084623/http://www.lgcm.org.uk/news/the-bishop-of-grantham/ |date=16 September 2016 }} (Accessed 3 September 2016)</ref>\n** A Nickelodeon cartoon, called '''The Loud House''', introduced the first animated married same-sex couple to its channel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2016/07/18/nickelodeon-makes-history-with-its-first-cartoon-gay-married-couple/|title=Nickelodeon \u2018makes history\u201