cite web|url=https://www.outrightinternational.org/content/chilean-government-stops-normalization-intersex-children|title=Chilean Government Stops the 'Normalization' of Intersex Children|work=OutRight}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2016/01/11/chilean-officials-oppose-normalization-surgery-for-intersex-children/|title=Chilean officials oppose intersex children 'normalization' surgery|work=Washington Blade: Gay News, Politics, LGBT Rights}}</ref>\n** '''[[Nisha Ayub]]''' received the [[International Women of Courage Award]] in 2016, becoming the first openly transgender woman to receive that award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nst.com.my/news/2016/03/136166/malaysian-first-transgender-woman-earn-international-women-courage-award|title=Malaysian is first transgender woman to earn International Women of Courage Award|work=NST Online|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412150600/http://www.nst.com.my/news/2016/03/136166/malaysian-first-transgender-woman-earn-international-women-courage-award|archivedate=12 April 2016|df=dmy}}</ref>\n** Aiden Katri, 19, became the '''first Israeli transgender woman to be jailed for refusing to serve in the military.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/2610848/israels-transgender-teen-activist-asks-to-go-to-womens-prison/|title=Israel's transgender teen activist asks to go to women's prison|date=31 March 2016|author=Staff|work=Global News}}</ref>\n** On 10 June 2016, an [[Oregon]] circuit court ruled that a resident, '''[[Jamie Shupe]]''', could obtain a non-binary gender designation.<!--don't use a gender-neutral pronoun here: Shupe now identifies as male. See https://jamieshupe.wordpress.com/2019/01/26/public-announcement-i-have-returned-to-my-male-birth-sex/--> The [[Transgender Law Center]] believes this to be \"the first ruling of its kind in the U.S.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailydot.com/lifestyle/oregon-court-rules-non-binary-gender-legal/|title='Nonbinary' is now a legal gender, Oregon court rules|date=10 June 2016|website=[[The Daily Dot]]|last1=O'Hara|first1=Mary Emily|accessdate=10 June 2016}}</ref>\n** An important legal victory for transgender people occurred in April 2016, when the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled in favor of transgender male student '''[[Gavin Grimm]]''', which marked the first ruling by a U.S. appeals court to find that transgender students are protected under federal laws that ban sex-based discrimination.<ref name=\"autogenerated8\">{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-court-transgender-idUSKCN0ZT1XD|title=Transgender bathroom legal fight reaches Supreme Court|date=13 July 2016|publisher=|accessdate=24 July 2016|via=Reuters}}</ref> The ruling came on a challenge to the Gloucester County School Board's policy of making transgender students use alternative restroom facilities.<ref name=\"autogenerated8\" />\n** It was announced on 30 June 2016 that, beginning on that date, '''otherwise qualified United States service members could not any longer be discharged, denied reenlistment, involuntarily separated, or denied continuation of service because of being transgender.'''<ref name=\"transgenderend\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/nation-world/national/article86902072.html|title=TMilitary lifts transgender ban s|date=30 June 2016|agency=McClatchy|accessdate=30 June 2016}}</ref>\n** '''Israel''' held its first transgender beauty pageant, which was called \"Miss Trans Israel\", and was held at a club in Tel Aviv.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.algemeiner.com/2016/03/04/israel-holds-its-first-transgender-beauty-pageant/|title=Israel Holds Its First Transgender Beauty Pageant|work=Algemeiner.com}}</ref>\n* '''Family/Relationships:'''\n** The '''ceremonial first kiss shared between a sailor and their partner after returning from active duty in the Canadian Navy''' was done by two men for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/this-beautiful-gay-navy-kiss-just-made-history_us_56cde91ee4b0ec6725e4b7e1|title=This Beautiful Gay Navy Kiss Just Made History|date=24 February 2016|work=The Huffington Post}}</ref>\n** An anonymous couple held '''the first same-sex wedding in Cyprus,'''<ref name=\"abcnews\">{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/cyprus-public-gay-wedding-takes-aim-prejudices-37404033|title=Cyprus' First Public Gay Wedding Takes Aim at Prejudices|work=ABC News}}</ref> while Marios Frixou and Fanos Eleftheriades held '''the first public same-sex wedding in Cyprus.'''<ref name=\"abcnews\" />\n** Tom Swann and Guillermo Hernandez became the '''first same-sex couple to marry in a United States federal immigration detention center.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/marriage-equality/2016/3/16/gay-couple-make-history-first-marry-immigration-detention-center|title=Gay Couple Make History as First to Marry in an Immigration Detention Center|publisher=}}</ref>\n** The '''first Jewish same-sex wedding ceremony in Latin America''' was celebrated in Buenos Aires; the wedding was for Victoria Escobar and Romina Charur and was officiated by Rabbi Karina Finkielstein.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forward.com/news/breaking-news/338304/argentina-lesbians-tie-knot-in-first-for-latin-america-jews/#ixzz45iihbFOD|title=Argentina Lesbians Tie Knot in First for Latin America Jews|author=JTA|date=11 April 2016|work=The Forward}}</ref>\n** In the '''first such ruling in Italy, a lesbian couple won the right to legally adopt each other's biological children.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/italian-lesbian-couple-wins-right-adopt-each-others-children-1557564|title=Italian lesbian couple wins right to adopt each other's children|first=Ananya|last=Roy|work=International Business Times UK}}</ref>\n** Luke Carine and Zak Tomlinson became '''the first same-sex couple to get married on the Isle of Man.'''<ref name=\"theguardian2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/jul/31/isle-of-man-gay-marriage|title=Three cheers for the gay marriage that ended the Isle of Man's dark history of bigotry &#124; Helen Pidd &#124; Opinion|date=2015-01-27|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=2016-08-06}}</ref>\n** Mexico had rallies for and against marriage equality.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ebar.com/news/article.php?sec=news&article=71889|title=The Bay Area Reporter Online &#124; Mexico rallies for and against marriage equality|last=Cassell|first=Heather|date=2016-09-15|publisher=Ebar.com|accessdate=2016-09-21}}</ref>\n** 250,000 pro-gay marriage protesters gathered at [[Ketagalan Boulevard]], [[Taipei]], [[Taiwan]] the main artery around the presidential office<ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/860215/photos-250000-demonstrators-call-on-taiwan-to-be-the-first-in-asia-to-legalize-gay-marriage/|title=Photos: 250,000 demonstrators call on Taiwan to be the first in Asia to legalize gay marriage \u2014 Quartz|date=2016-12-11|publisher=Qz.com|accessdate=2017-02-01}}</ref> Less than a week earlier, 80,000 people protested against same-sex marriage in Taipei, with an additional 90,000 across the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.towleroad.com/2016/12/taiwan-gay/|title=Taiwan Religious Groups Stage Massive Anti-Gay Marriage Protests: VIDEO|date=2016-12-06|publisher=Towleroad|author=Michael Fitzgerald<!--6 December 2016 | 7:15am-->|accessdate=2017-02-01}}</ref>\n* Rare LGBT protest held in [[Lebanon]] on 16 May 2016.\n\n==2017==\n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha|Ascension Island]], [[Same-sex marriage in the Faroe Islands|Faroe Islands]], [[Same-sex marriage in Finland|Finland]]\n** '''Passed and came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Australia|Australia]], [[Same-sex marriage in Bermuda|Bermuda]] (temporarily repealed from 2 June 2018 \u2013 23 November 2018),  [[Same-sex marriage in Germany|Germany]], [[Same-sex marriage in Guernsey|Guernsey]], [[Same-sex marriage in the Falkland Islands|Falkland Islands]], [[Same-sex marriage in Malta|Malta,]] [[Same-sex marriage in Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha|Saint Helena]], [[Same-sex marriage in Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha|Tristan da Cunha]], the Mexican states [[Same-sex marriage in Chiapas|Chiapas]], [[Same-sex marriage in Baja California|Baja California]] and [[Same-sex marriage in Puebla|Puebla]]\n** '''Supreme Court Ruling''': [[Same-sex marriage in Austria|Austria]] (to take effect by 1 January 2019), [[Same-sex marriage in Taiwan|Taiwan]] (to take effect by 24 May 2019)\n** '''Passed''': [[Same-sex marriage in Guernsey#Alderney|Alderney]]\n* '''Criminalization of homosexuality:''' [[LGBT rights in Chad|Chad]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/chad-passes-law-make-gay-sex-illegal/#gs.TGGA_mM|title=Chad passes law to make gay sex illegal|date=2016-12-15|newspaper=Gay Star News|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-12-26}}</ref> \n* '''Anti-discrimination and hate crime law:'''\n** '''Canada''' passed bill C-16, which bans discrimination against trans people and recognizes bias against trans people as an aggravating factor in crime (hate crime); the province of New Brunswick, and the territories of Nunavut and Yukon also passed laws banning discrimination against trans people and allowing people to change their legal gender without surgery, meaning trans people are now protected from discrimination in all provinces and territories.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailyxtra.com/canada-has-finally-passed-a-trans-rights-bill-73688|title=Canada has finally passed a trans-rights bill|date=2017-06-15|work=Xtra|access-date=2017-07-21|language=en-US}}</ref> \n** '''India''': [[Supreme Court of India]] rules that the right to privacy is intrinsically protected under Article 21 and Part 3 of the [[Constitution of India]], and lambasts the reasoning behind the earlier 2013 Supreme Court ruling ''Koushal v. Naz Foundation'' for its dismissal of LGBT rights as \"so-called\" and of LGBT persons as \"a miniscule fraction of the country\u2019s population\" in its reinstatement of Section 377 of the IPC. The new ruling protects sexual orientation as a constitutional \"sanctity\" of privacy alongside \"preservation of personal intimacies\", \"family life, marriage, procreation, the home\" and \"a right to be left alone\". The ruling leaves room for a stronger legal challenge against Section 377.\n* '''Arts and Culture:'''\n** In the [[Beauty and the Beast (2017 film)|2017 live-action adaptation]] of ''Beauty and the Beast'', Le Fou is gay, making him '''the first gay character in a Disney film.'''<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://time.com/4686896/disney-beauty-beast-emma-watson-dan-stevens-gay-character/ |title=Beauty and the Beast: Disney's First Gay Character Is Here |magazine=Time.com |accessdate=2017-03-03}}</ref>\n** Marshall Bang became '''the first singer in Korea to debut as an openly gay musician.'''<ref name=\"losangelesblade.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.losangelesblade.com/2018/01/22/first-openly-gay-k-pop-star-holland-debuts-first-single/|title=First openly gay K-pop star Holland debuts first single|date=22 January 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n** '''Queer British Art show''' leads Tate 2017 programme.<ref>{{cite news|author=Mark Brown Arts correspondent |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2016/apr/19/queer-british-art-show-leads-tate-2017-programme |title=Queer British Art show leads Tate 2017 programme &#124; Art and design |newspaper=The Guardian |date=2015-08-25 |accessdate=2016-12-15}}</ref>\n** The January 2017 issue of ''[[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]]'' has a 9-year-old transgender girl on the cover (Avery Jackson); she is '''thought to be the first openly transgender person on ''National Geographic''\u2019s cover.'''<ref>{{cite web|last=Avery |first=Dan |url=http://www.newnownext.com/national-geographic-transgender-cover-avery-jackson/12/2016/ |title=National Geographic Magazine Puts Young Transgender Girl On Cover |publisher=NewNowNext |date=2016-09-30 |accessdate=2016-12-15}}</ref>\n** '''[[Ellen Hart]]''', who is openly lesbian,<ref name=\"glbtq.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.glbtq.com/sfeatures/interviewehart.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-08-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513101838/http://www.glbtq.com/sfeatures/interviewehart.html |archivedate=13 May 2008 |df=dmy }}</ref> became the first openly LGBT writer to be named a Grand Master by the [[Mystery Writers of America]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Walters |first=Gillian |url=http://www.afterellen.com/music/529645-lez-dish-lesbianing-afterellen-friday-round |title=Lez Dish it OUT! - Lesbianing With AfterEllen Friday Round-Up |publisher=AfterEllen |date=2017-01-10 |accessdate=2017-01-21}}</ref>\n** Joe Maldonado became '''the first openly transgender member of the Boy Scouts of America'''.<ref name=\"mercurynews1\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2017/02/08/boy-scouts-welcome-first-transgender-member/ |title=Boy Scouts get first transgender member |publisher=Mercurynews.com |date= 8 February 2017|accessdate=2017-02-08}}</ref> In 2016, he was rejected from the Cub Scouts for being transgender, but this policy was changed in 2017 after his story became nationally known.<ref name=\"mercurynews1\" />\n** '''[[Gabrielle Tremblay]]''' became '''the first openly transgender actress ever nominated for a [[Canadian Screen Award]]''', as Best Supporting Actress for her role in ''[[Those Who Make Revolution Halfway Only Dig Their Own Graves]] (Ceux qui font les r\u00e9volutions \u00e0 moiti\u00e9 n'ont fait que se creuser un tombeau)''.<ref name=\"Guy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/cinema/cinema-quebecois/entrevues/201701/20/01-5061473-gabrielle-tremblay-la-revanche-sur-le-passe.php |title=Gabrielle Tremblay: la revanche sur le pass\u00e9 |last=Guy |first=Chantal |date=20 January 2017 |accessdate=29 January 2017 |work=[[La Presse (Canadian newspaper)|La Presse]]}}</ref>\n** Brazilian model Valentina Sampaio became the '''first openly transgender model on the cover of French ''Vogue''.<ref>{{cite web|first=Tori |last=Latham |url=https://nymag.com/thecut/2017/02/transgender-model-covers-french-vogue-for-the-first-time.html |title=Transgender Model Covers French Vogue For the First Time |publisher=Nymag.com |date= |accessdate=2017-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Landon |last=Peoples |url=http://www.refinery29.com/2017/02/140711/french-vogue-transgender-model-cover-valentina-sampaio |title=French Vogue Cover Transgender Model Valentina Sampaio |publisher=Refinery29.com |date=2017-01-26 |accessdate=2017-02-14}}</ref>'''\n** Martina Robledo became the '''first openly transgender woman to act as a trophy presenter at the Grammys.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrc.org/blog/am-equality-tipsheet-february-13-2017 |title=#AM_Equality Tipsheet: February 13, 2017 &#124; Human Rights Campaign |publisher=Hrc.org |date= |accessdate=2017-02-14}}</ref>\n** ''[[Moonlight (2016 film)|Moonlight]]'' became '''the first [[List of LGBT-related films|LGBT-related film]] to win the Best Picture award at the Oscars.'''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2017/feb/27/dont-let-that-oscars-blunder-overshadow-moonlights-monumental-achievement?CMP=fb_us|title=Don't let that Oscars blunder overshadow Moonlight's monumental achievement|last=Rose|first=Steve|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref>\n** M Barclay became the '''first openly non-binary trans person to be commissioned as a Deacon in the [[United Methodist Church]]'''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/acts-of-faith/wp/2017/06/07/the-united-methodist-church-just-appointed-a-transgender-deacon/|title=The United Methodist Church has appointed a transgender deacon|last=Zauzmer|first=Julie|newspaper=The Washington Post|accessdate=2017-06-23}}</ref>\n** [[Alex Hai]] came out as a transgender man, thus becoming '''the first openly transgender gondolier in Venice.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.west-info.eu/dont-call-me-alexandra-word-of-the-first-transgender-gondolier/|title=Don\u2019t call me Alexandra, word of the first transgender gondolier - WEST|date=2007-10-19|publisher=West-info.eu|accessdate=2017-06-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/alexandra-hai-venice-s-first-female-gondolier-to-have-a-sex-change-qhz7k9tqb|title=Venice\u2019s first female gondolier, to have a sex change &#124; World &#124; The Times & The Sunday Times|date=|publisher=Thetimes.co.uk|first=Tom|last=Kington|accessdate=2017-06-23}}</ref>\n** Ryan Atkin became '''the first openly gay official in English soccer.'''<ref>{{cite web|last=O'Callaghan |first=Rory |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/10998938/ryan-atkin-on-the-response-to-becoming-the-first-openly-gay-official-in-english-football |title=Ryan Atkin reveals positive response to becoming the first openly gay official in English football &#124; Football News |publisher=Sky Sports |date= |accessdate=2017-08-23}}</ref>\n** San Francisco 49ers assistant coach Katie Sowers came out as gay, thus becoming '''the NFL's first openly LGBT coach, and the first openly LGBT coach in all of U.S. men's professional sports.'''<ref>{{cite web|last=Buzinski |first=Jim |url=https://www.outsports.com/2017/8/22/16175286/katie-sowers-san-francisco-49ers-coach-gay-coming-out |title=San Francisco 49ers assistant Katie Sowers is first out LGBT coach in NFL |publisher=Outsports |date= |accessdate=2017-08-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/49ers/2017/08/22/san-francisco-49-ers-assistant-katie-sowers-comes-out-becomes-nfls-first-openly-lgbt-coach/589701001/ |title=Katie Sowers, San Francisco 49ers assistant coach, comes out |publisher=Usatoday.com |date= |accessdate=2017-08-23}}</ref>\n** [[Scott Frantz (American football)|Scott Frantz]] became '''the first openly gay college football player to play in a game for a [[NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision]] school.'''<ref>{{cite web|last=Zeigler |first=Cyd |url=https://www.outsports.com/2017/9/4/16254012/gay-football-kansas-state-scott-frantz |title=Big XII football team with openly gay player wins by 36 points. So much for distractions. |publisher=Outsports |date=2017-09-04 |accessdate=2017-09-08}}</ref>\n** In August 2017, '''the first West Africa LGBT-Inclusive religious gathering''' occurred. Over 30 participants indigenous to ten West African countries, including Benin, Nigeria, Ghana, Sierra Leone, Liberia, The Gambia, Burkina Faso, C\u00f4te d'Ivoire, Mali, and Togo participated in an interfaith diversity event hosted by Interfaith Diversity Network of West Africa with the theme of \"Building Bridges, Sharing Stories, Creating Hope\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2017/09/06/first-west-africa-lgbt-friendly-religious-gathering-takes-place/|title=First West Africa LGBT-inclusive religious gathering takes place|date=6 September 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n**MOGA, a Muslim Women's fashion designer becomes '''the first fashion designer in the world to release a rainbow hijab.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2017/11/04/muslim-fashion-designer-creates-rainbow-hijab-to-support-same-sex-marriage/ |title=Muslim fashion designer creates rainbow hijab to support same-sex marriage \u00b7 PinkNews |publisher=Pinknews.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2018-01-03}}</ref>\n* '''Politics:'''\n**[[Jess Herbst]], mayor of New Hope, came out as transgender and thus became '''the first known openly transgender elected official in Texas history.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.texasobserver.org/collin-county-mayor-becomes-texas-first-transgender-elected-official/|title=Collin County Mayor Becomes Texas\u2019 First Transgender Elected Official|last=Wright|first=John|date=2017|publisher=Texasobserver.org|accessdate=2017-02-01}}</ref>\n** Japan became the first country in the world to elect an openly transgender man to a public office when '''Tomoya Hosoda''' was elected as a councilor for the city of [[Iruma, Saitama|Iruma]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Chloe |last=Farand |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/japan-first-world-transgender-man-public-office-councillor-iruma-saitama-kanto-a7636641.html |title=Japan becomes first country in the world to elect a transgender man to a public office |newspaper=The Independent |accessdate=2017-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2017/03/17/japan-just-elected-its-first-trans-man-into-public-office/ |title=Japan just elected its first trans man into public office \u00b7 PinkNews |publisher=Pinknews.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2017-03-18}}</ref>\n** [[Candice Jackson]] is appointed the first openly gay Deputy Assistant Secretary for Strategic Operations and Outreach in the [[Office for Civil Rights]] of the [[United States Department of Education]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lawcomm.pepperdine.edu/candice-jackson-jd-02-appointed-to-us-department-of-education/|title=Candice Jackson (JD '02) appointed to US Department of Education|website=lawcomm.pepperdine.edu}}</ref>\n** Two openly gay candidates were elected to the [[Municipality of Anchorage|Anchorage Assembly]] (Christopher Constant and Felix Rivera), becoming '''the first openly LGBT elected officials in Alaska.'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lgbtweekly.com/2017/04/05/lgbtq-candidates-win-historic-election-in-alaska/ |title=LGBTQ candidates win historic Election in Alaska |publisher=LGBT Weekly |date=2017 |accessdate=2017-04-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170406154216/http://lgbtweekly.com/2017/04/05/lgbtq-candidates-win-historic-election-in-alaska/ |archive-date=6 April 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=John |last=Aronno |url=http://www.alaskacommons.com/2017/04/05/anchorage-makes-history-2017-local-elections-despite-ridiculously-low-voter-turnout/ |title=Anchorage Makes History in 2017 Local Elections Despite Ridiculously Low Voter Turnout |publisher=Alaska Commons |date= |accessdate=2017-04-05}}</ref>\n** [[Andy Street]] became '''the United Kingdom's first openly gay directly elected metro mayor.'''<ref name=\"pinknewsbutterworth\">{{cite news|last1=Butterworth|first1=Benjamin|title=Conservative Andy Street becomes UK\u2019s first directly-elected gay metro mayor|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2017/05/05/gay-conservative-andy-street-elected-metro-mayor-of-west-midlands/|accessdate=7 May 2017|work=Pink News|date=5 May 2017}}</ref>\n** '''[[Leo Varadkar]]''' became the new [[Taoiseach]] (Prime Minister) of [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] and leader of the [[Fine Gael]] party, after winning 51 of the 73 votes in the parliamentary party. He was '''the first openly gay Taoiseach''', as well as the youngest and the first of half-Indian descent.<ref>{{cite web|first=Hugh |last=Linehan |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/is-having-a-gay-taoiseach-a-big-deal-for-ireland-1.3105955 |title=Is having a gay taoiseach a big deal for Ireland? |publisher=Irishtimes.com |date=2017-06-03 |accessdate=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n** [[Paul Feinman]] became the '''first openly gay judge on the [[New York Court of Appeals]].'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/news/politics/albany/2017/06/21/new-yorks-top-court-gets-first-openly-gay-judge/103079984/ |title=Paul Feinman becomes first gay judge on New York's top court |publisher=Democratandchronicle.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-22}}</ref>\n** '''[[Ana Brnabi\u0107]]''' was elected as the first openly gay (and first female) [[Prime Minister of Serbia]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/world/la-fg-serbia-prime-minister-20170629-story.html |title=Serbia lawmakers elect first female, openly gay prime minister |newspaper=LA Times |accessdate=2017-06-30}}</ref> and was the first head of government of any Balkan country to attend a gay pride march; she attended one in Belgrade.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-41297781 |title=Serbia's gay PM is first in region to attend pride parade - BBC News |publisher=Bbc.com |date= |accessdate=2017-09-17}}</ref>\n** '''[[Alice Weidel]]''' was elected as the first openly gay (and first female) co-chair of [[Alternative for Germany]] and was elected to [[Bundestag|Federal Diet]] of [[Germany]].\n** '''[[Danica Roem]]''' was elected as [[Virginia]]'s first transgender lawmaker.\n** [[Andrea Jenkins]] became '''the first openly transgender black woman elected to public office in the United States''' when she was elected to the Minneapolis City Council.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/11/08/meet-andrea-jenkins-the-openly-transgender-black-woman-elected-to-public-office-in-the-u-s/|title=Meet Andrea Jenkins, the first openly transgender black woman elected to public office in the U.S.|last=Eltagouri|first=Marwa|date=8 November 2017|publisher=|via=www.washingtonpost.com}}</ref>\n** Tyler Titus, a transgender man, became '''the first openly transgender person elected to public office in Pennsylvania''' when he was elected to the Erie School Board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dispatch.com/news/20171108/transgender-man-wins-school-board-seat-in-pennsylvania|title=Transgender man wins school board seat in Pennsylvania - News - The Columbus Dispatch - Columbus, OH|author=Ed Palattella, Erie (Pa.) Times-News|date=|publisher=Dispatch.com|accessdate=2017-12-05}}</ref> He and [[Phillipe Cunningham]], elected to the Minneapolis City Council on the same night, became '''the first two openly trans men to be elected to public office in the United States.'''<ref name=WashingtonBlade>{{cite news |url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2017/11/08/phillipe-cunningham-first-trans-man-elected-u-s-public-office/ |title=Phillipe Cunningham makes history as Minnesota trans male candidate |first=Chris |last=Johnson |date=8 November 2017 |newspaper=[[Washington Blade]] |accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref>\n** '''[[Allison Ikley-Freeman]]''' was elected as Oklahoma's first lesbian lawmaker.\n** '''America's first all-LGBT city council''' was elected in Palm Springs, consisting of three gay men, a transgender woman and a bisexual woman.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jan/01/palm-springs-first-lgbt-gay-city-council-government-interview |title=In gay-friendly Palm Springs, America's first all-LGBT government is no surprise &#124; World news |newspaper=The Guardian |date=2017 |accessdate=2018-01-03}}</ref>\n**Taiwan's  [[Judicial Yuan|Constitutional Court]] declared the [[Statute|statutory]] ban on same-sex marriage in Taiwan's Civil Code was \"in violation of both the people\u2019s freedom of marriage as protected by Article 22 and the people's right to equality as guaranteed by Article 7 of the [[Constitution of the Republic of China|Constitution]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/lanesainty/taiwanese-court-delivers-landmark-marriage-ruling|title=Taiwanese Court Delivers Landmark Ruling In Favour Of Marriage Equality|last=|first=|date=|website=BuzzFeed|access-date=}}</ref> The accompanying official press release from the court stated that if the Legislature fails to amend the law within the two-year time frame, then \"two persons of the same-sex...may apply for marriage registration [and] shall be accorded the status of a legally recognized couple, and then enjoy the rights and bear the obligations arising on couples\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://focustaiwan.tw/news/aipl/201705240014.aspx|title=Constitutional Court rules in favor of same-sex marriage|last=|first=|date=|website=Focus Taiwan News Channel|access-date=}}</ref>\n* '''Trans:'''\n** '''Denmark''' became the second country in the world to officially remove transgender identities from its list of mental health disorders.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonblade.com/2017/01/04/denmark-no-longer-considers-transgender-people-mentally-ill/|title=Denmark no longer considers transgender people mentally ill|last=Lavers|first=Michael K.|date=|publisher=Washingtonblade.com|accessdate=2017-01-05}}</ref> \n** The '''[[Unitarian Universalist Association]]'s General Assembly''' voted to create inclusive wordings for non-binary, genderqueer, gender fluid, agender, intersex, two-spirit and polygender people, replacing the words \"men and women\" with the word \"people.\" Of the six sources of the living tradition, the second source of faith, as documented in the bylaws of the denomination, now includes \"Words and deeds of prophetic people which challenge us to confront powers and structures of evil with justice, compassion, and the transforming power of love.\"<ref>{{cite web|first=Zr. Alex|last=Kapitan |url=https://www.believeoutloud.com/latest/unitarian-universalist-general-assembly-votes-change-uu-bylaws-include-non-binary-people#comment-7295 |title=Unitarian Universalist General Assembly Votes To Change UU Bylaws To Include Non-Binary People |publisher=Believe Out Loud |date=2017-06-30 |accessdate=2017-07-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170714221953/https://www.believeoutloud.com/latest/unitarian-universalist-general-assembly-votes-change-uu-bylaws-include-non-binary-people |archive-date=2017-07-14}}</ref> \n** [[Philippa York]], formerly Robert Millar, came out as transgender, thus becoming '''the first former professional cyclist to have publicly transitioned.'''<ref name=\"Guardian Transition\">{{cite news|last1=Fotheringham|first1=William|title=Philippa York: \u2018I\u2019ve known I was different since I was a five-year-old\u2019|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/jul/06/philippa-york-gender-transition-cyclist-robert-millar|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=7 July 2017}}</ref>\n** [[Ines Rau]] became '''the first openly transgender [[Playboy Playmate]]'''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/10/20/entertainment/ines-rau-playboy/index.html|title=Ines Rau is the first transgender Playmate|first=Lisa Respers|last=France|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n** The [[United States]] [[Defense Health Agency]] for the '''first time approved payment''' for [[sex reassignment surgery]] for an active-duty U.S. military service member. The patient, an infantry soldier who identifies as a woman, had already begun a course of treatment for gender reassignment. The procedure, which the treating doctor deemed medically necessary, was performed on 14 November at a private hospital, since U.S. military hospitals lack the requisite surgical expertise.<ref name=\"FirstMilitarySRS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/pentagon-oks-surgery-transgender-soldier-military-hospital-n820721|title=Pentagon to pay for surgery for transgender soldier|last=Kube|first=Courtney|work=NBC News|date=14 November 2017}}</ref>\n*'''Charitable Services United Kingdom:'''\n\n[[Melton Mowbray]] in [[Leicestershire]], [[United Kingdom]] got its first [[youth]] provision specifically aimed at [[LGBT]]Q+ young people. [https://www.lgbtmelton.co.uk] LGBT Melton was established on 21 January and opened its doors for the first time a few weeks later on 6 March. [[LGBT Melton]] was founded by Anthony Marvin who has been recognised for his efforts and his support for the LGBTQ+ by receiving the [[Leicester Pride]] Unsung Hero Award. LGBT Melton has expanded its services to the wider county of Leicestershire and [[Rutland]].\n\n==2018==\n<!--Please also add applicable entries to the List of lesbian, gay, bisexual, or transgender firsts by year article-->\n* '''Same-sex marriage laws''':\n** '''Passed and came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Jersey|Jersey]]\n** '''Came into effect''': [[Same-sex marriage in Guernsey#Alderney|Alderney]], [[Same-sex marriage in Bermuda|Bermuda]] (after Supreme Court decision)\n** '''Supreme Court Ruling''': [[Same-sex marriage in Costa Rica|Costa Rica]] (to take effect by 26 May 2020)\n* '''Decriminalisation of homosexuality''': [[LGBT rights in Trinidad and Tobago|Trinidad and Tobago]], [[LGBT rights in India|India]]\n* '''The Prime Minister of the UK, [[Theresa May]], issues an apology&nbsp;expressing \"deep regret\" for Britain's role in imposing [[LGBT rights in the Commonwealth of Nations|colonial&nbsp;laws that criminalize LGBT people across the Commonwealth]]'''&nbsp;and the&nbsp;legacy of violence and discrimination that persists today. At the time of the apology, 36 of&nbsp;53&nbsp;Commonwealth countries still had colonial-era criminalization laws.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.mambaonline.com/2018/04/17/historic-theresa-may-regrets-commonwealth-anti-gay-laws/ |title=Historic! Theresa May regrets Commonwealth anti-gay laws - MambaOnline - Gay South Africa online |publisher=MambaOnline |date=2018-04-17 |accessdate=2018-11-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Pippa|last=Crerar |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/apr/17/theresa-may-deeply-regrets-britain-legacy-anti-gay-laws-commonwealth-nations-urged-overhaul-legislation |title=Theresa May says she deeply regrets Britain's legacy of anti-gay laws &#124; World news |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=2018-11-07}}</ref>\n* '''Arts and Culture'''\n** On 9 June, around 30 to 40 researchers, 12 of whom identified as LGBT, held the first Pride celebration at a bar in [[McMurdo Station]] in the [[Ross Dependency]], making it '''the first pride celebration in [[Antarctica]].'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.nationalgeographic.com/2018/06/celebrating-pride-worlds-remote-places-culture/ |title=LGBTQ Pride Celebrations and Parades in Remote Places |publisher=News.nationalgeographic.com |date=2018-06-08 |accessdate=2019-07-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/547358/employees-antarcticas-mcmurdo-station-are-throwing-party-pride-month |title=Employees at Antarctica's McMurdo Station Are Throwing a Party for Pride Month |magazine=Mental Floss |accessdate=2019-07-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.travelandleisure.com/travel-news/antarctica-first-pride-parade|title=Antarctica Celebrates Its First Pride Thanks to Team of Researchers|website=www.travelandleisure.com}}</ref>\n**'''[[Stav Strashko]]''' became the first openly transgender actress ever to receive an [[Ophir Award]] nomination for Best Actress.<ref>[https://www.timesofisrael.com/in-first-trans-actress-nominated-for-israels-top-film-prize/ \"In first, trans actress is candidate for Israel\u2019s top film prize\"]. ''[[The Times of Israel]]'', September 3, 2018.</ref>\n**[[Sandra Lawson]] was ordained and thus became '''the first openly gay, female, black rabbi in the world'''.<ref name=\"SandraLawson\">{{cite web|url=http://www.elon.edu/e-net/Article/163441|title=Rabbi Sandra Lawson named associate chaplain for Jewish life, Jewish educator at Hillel|website=E-Net! Elon University News & Information|language=en|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://projects.elonnewsnetwork.com/elonrabbi/|title=Elon Rabbi redefines religion|website=projects.elonnewsnetwork.com|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref> \n**[[Adam Rippon]] became '''the United States\u2019 first openly gay athlete ever to qualify for any Winter Olympics'''.<ref name=\"thinkprogress1\">{{cite web|url=https://thinkprogress.org/adam-rippon-becomes-first-openly-gay-u-s-athlete-to-qualify-for-winter-olympics-0e1b04d34620/ |title=Adam Rippon becomes first openly gay U.S. athlete to qualify for Winter Olympics \u2013 ThinkProgress |publisher=Thinkprogress.org |date= |accessdate=2018-01-08}}</ref> That year he won an Olympic bronze medal as part of the figure skating team event, thus becoming '''the first openly gay U.S. athlete to win a medal at the Winter Olympics.'''<ref>{{cite web |last=Lutz |first=Rachel |url=http://www.nbcolympics.com/news/team-usa-captures-bronze-figure-skating-team-event-help-adam-rippon-mirai-nagasu-and-shibutanis |title=Canada wins gold, USA bronze in figure skating team event |p