 Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Miniseries or Television Movie]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2014\n| rowspan=4 | ''True Detective''\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | 2015\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Miniseries or Television Film]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Drama]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Drama Series]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=4 | 2018\n| rowspan=4 | ''Three Billboards Outside Ebbing, Missouri''\n| [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Supporting Role]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture]]\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commons}}\n* {{IMDb name|437}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{Iobdb name|13375}}\n* [http://www.voiceyourself.com Profile], VoiceYourself.com\n* [http://www.emmys.com/celebrities/woody-harrelson Woody Harrelson profile], Emmys.com\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Woody Harrelson\n|list  =\n{{EmmyAward ComedySupportingActor}}\n{{Independent Spirit Award for Best Supporting Male}}\n{{MTV Movie Award for Best Kiss}}\n{{National Board of Review Award for Best Supporting Actor}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harrelson, Woody}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American anarchists]]\n[[Category:American anti\u2013Iraq War activists]]\n[[Category:American anti-war activists]]\n[[Category:American cannabis activists]]\n[[Category:American environmentalists]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American Presbyterians]]\n[[Category:American theatre directors]]\n[[Category:Hanover College alumni]]\n[[Category:Independent Spirit Award winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Texas]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture Screen Actors Guild Award winners]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Supporting Actor in a Comedy Series Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:People from Lebanon, Ohio]]\n[[Category:People from Midland, Texas]]\n[[Category:Raw foodists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Woody Harrelson\n| image              = Woody Harrelson October 2016.jpg\n| caption            = Harrelson at an event for ''[[LBJ (film)|LBJ]]'' in 2016\n| birth_name         = Woodrow Tracy Harrelson\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1961|07|23|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Midland, Texas|Midland]], [[Texas]], U.S.\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| residence          = [[Maui]], [[Hawaii]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Actor|playwright}}\n| years_active       = 1978\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Nancy Simon<br>|1985|1986|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Laura Louie<br>|2008}}\n| children           = 3\n| education          = [[Lebanon High School (Ohio)|Lebanon High School]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Hanover College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])\n| relatives          = [[Charles Harrelson]] (father)<br />[[Brett Harrelson]] (brother)\n}}\n\n'''Woodrow Tracy Harrelson''' (born July 23, 1961) is an American actor and playwright. He first became known for his role as bartender [[Woody Boyd]] on the [[NBC]] sitcom ''[[Cheers]]'' (1985\u20131993), for which he won a [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Comedy Series]] from a total of five nominations. He has also received three [[Academy Award]] nominations: [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] for ''[[The People vs. Larry Flynt]]'' (1996) and [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for ''[[The Messenger (2009 film)|The Messenger]]'' (2009) and ''[[Three Billboards Outside Ebbing, Missouri]]'' (2017).<ref name=\"imdb\">{{IMDb name|437}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nWoodrow Tracy Harrelson<ref>{{cite web|first=Tim|last=Cooper|url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/theatre/review-574706-welcome-to-woody-world.do|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130505102545/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/theatre/review-574706-welcome-to-woody-world.do|url-status=dead|archive-date=May 5, 2013|title=Welcome to Woody World|publisher=Thisislondon.co.uk|date=July 19, 2002|accessdate=September 30, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Sipchen|first=Bob|title=The Life of Woody|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1998/dec/20/magazine/tm-55786/2|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=December 20, 1998}}</ref> was born in [[Midland, Texas]], on July 23, 1961,<ref name=filmref>{{cite web| url= http://www.filmreference.com/film/56/Woody-Harrelson.html | title=Woody Harrelson Biography (1961-)| publisher= FilmReference.com| accessdate= January 11, 2017| archivedate= October 23, 2015|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20151023175539/http://www.filmreference.com/film/56/Woody-Harrelson.html |url-status=live}}</ref> the son of secretary Diane ({{nee|Oswald}}; * 1940)<ref>[https://www.geni.com/people/Diane-Harrelson/6000000020268987592 Diane Lou Harrelson, Woody Harrelson's mother]</ref> and convicted hitman [[Charles Harrelson|Charles Voyde Harrelson]] (1938\u20132007).<ref name=filmref/> He and his two brothers, Jordan and [[Brett Harrelson|Brett]], were raised in a [[Presbyterian]] household.<ref name=filmref /><ref name=\"ft.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/e3487fc4-5ea6-11e8-9334-2218e7146b04|title=Woody Harrelson: 'I had to go outside and fire up a hooter'|first=Matthew|last=Garrahan|date=May 25, 2018|website=Financial Times}}</ref> Their father received a life sentence for the 1979 killing of Federal Judge [[John H. Wood Jr.]]<ref name=\"cbs\">{{Cite news|title=Woody Harrelson's Father Dies in Prison|agency=Associated Press|publisher=CBS News|date=March 21, 2007|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2007/03/21/entertainment/main2592684.shtml}}</ref> Harrelson has stated that his father was rarely around during his childhood.<ref name=\"ft.com\"/> Charles died in the [[ADX Florence|United States Penitentiary, Administrative Maximum Facility]] on March 15, 2007.<ref name=\"cbs\"/> Harrelson's family was poor and relied on his mother's wage.<ref name=\"ft.com\"/> In 1973, he moved to his mother's native city of [[Lebanon, Ohio]],<ref>{{cite news| url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DDNB&p_theme=ddnb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F504F41A7D42079&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|work=Dayton Daily News|title=Dayton Daily News Archive of Past Articles|date=July 24, 1991}}</ref> where he attended [[Lebanon High School (Ohio)|Lebanon High School]], from which he graduated in 1979.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McClleland|first1=Justin|title=Woody Harrelson's early co-stars share memories|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/news/local/woody-harrelson-early-stars-share-memories/ozs160PxnYgkIV2GOb21JO/|website=[[Dayton Daily News]]|accessdate=March 6, 2018|date=March 4, 2010}}</ref> He spent the summer of 1979 working at [[Kings Island]] amusement park.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celebrities who worked at Kings Island|url=https://www.cincinnati.com/picture-gallery/entertainment/2014/04/14/celebrities-who-worked-at-kings-island/7610777/|website=[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]]|accessdate=March 6, 2018|date=April 14, 2014}}</ref> He attended [[Hanover College]] in [[Hanover, Indiana]], where he joined the [[Sigma Chi]] fraternity. He received a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in theater and English in 1983.\n\nWhile attending Hanover, he crossed paths with future [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Mike Pence]], later commenting in 2018: \"I knew him, yeah. We were both very religious. It was a Presbyterian college at the time, and I was there on a Presbyterian scholarship, and he was involved with the church activities. I was actually considering being a minister and then I just kind of went a different way...I actually quite liked him. I thought he was a pretty good guy. He's, you know, very religious. Very committed. Seeing as how I'm not quite in that ballpark now, I don't know how we'd get along, 'cause I think he's still quite religious and just a whole different brand of religious. That kind of fervor that you really don't want.\"<ref name=kimmel>{{Citation|last=Jimmy Kimmel Live|title=Woody Harrelson Went to College with Mike Pence|date=2018-05-09|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5LwdV3fOZSc|access-date=2019-03-09}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Television===\nHarrelson is widely known for his work on the NBC sitcom ''[[Cheers]]''. He played bartender [[Woody Boyd]], who replaced [[Coach Ernie Pantusso|Coach]] (played by [[Nicholas Colasanto]], who died in February 1985). He joined the cast in 1985 in season four, spending the final eight seasons (1985\u20131993) on the show. For this role, Harrelson was nominated for five [[Emmy Award]]s,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/celebrities/woody-harrelson|title=Woody Harrelson Emmy Nominated|publisher=Emmys.com|accessdate=September 30, 2013}}</ref> winning once in 1989. His character, Woody Boyd, was from [[Hanover, Indiana]], where Harrelson attended college. In 1999, Harrelson guest-starred in the ''Cheers'' spin-off success ''[[Frasier]]'', in which he reprised the role of \"Woody Boyd.\" He was nominated for an Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actor in a Comedy Series for this performance. He appeared in several 2001 episodes of ''[[Will & Grace]]'' as Grace's new boyfriend Nathan.<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\n[[File:Woody Harrelson (1988).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Harrelson on the red carpet at the 40th Annual Primetime Emmy Awards, August 28, 1988]]\nOn the November 12, 2009 episode of the Comedy Central show ''[[The Colbert Report]]'', Harrelson was interviewed by [[Stephen Colbert]], to promote his movie ''[[The Messenger (2009 film)|The Messenger]]''. In response to Colbert's questioning of his support for the troops, Harrelson agreed to let Colbert shave his head on camera. Harrelson returned to television in 2014, starring along with [[Matthew McConaughey]] in the first season of the [[HBO]] crime series [[True Detective (TV series)|''True Detective'']], where he played Marty Hart, a Louisiana cop investigating murders that took place over a timespan of 17 years.<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\nOn June 6, 2010, Harrelson took part playing in [[Soccer Aid#2010: Series 3|Soccer Aid 2010]] for [[UNICEF UK]] at [[Old Trafford]] in [[Manchester]]. The match was broadcast live on UK's [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] television. After being brought on as a substitute for [[Gordon Ramsay]], Harrelson took the final penalty in the [[penalty shootout (association football)|penalty shootout]], following a 2\u20132 draw after 91.2 minutes.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} Despite being initially unaware of exactly from where his kick had to be taken, Harrelson scored to win the game for \"The Rest of the World\" team, beating England for the first time since the tournament began. When later interviewed, he claimed that he \"didn't even remember the moment of scoring.\"<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\nHarrelson also took part in [[Soccer Aid#2012: Series 4|Soccer Aid 2012]] on May 27, 2012. The match ended 3\u20131 in favor of England.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.looktothestars.org/news/8436-soccer-aid-2012-injures-stars-saves-children|title=Soccer Aid 2012 Injures Stars, Saves Children|date=May 29, 2012|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Film===\nWhile still working on ''Cheers'', Harrelson restarted his film career. His first movie had been ''[[Wildcats (film)|Wildcats]]'', a 1986 football comedy with [[Goldie Hawn]]. He reunited with [[Wesley Snipes]] (who also had debuted in ''Wildcats'') in the box-office hit ''[[White Men Can't Jump]]'' (1992) and the [[box office bomb]] ''[[Money Train]]'' (1995).<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\n[[File:Woody Harrelson cropped by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|right|Harrelson in April 2007]]\nIn 1993, Harrelson starred opposite [[Robert Redford]] and [[Demi Moore]] in the drama ''[[Indecent Proposal]]'', which was a box office success, earning a worldwide total of over $265,000,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=indecentproposal.htm|title=Indecent Proposal (1993)|website=Box Office Mojo|date=July 6, 1993|accessdate=September 30, 2013}}</ref> He then played Mickey Knox in [[Oliver Stone]]'s ''[[Natural Born Killers]]'' and Dr. Michael Raynolds in the [[Michael Cimino]] film ''[[The Sunchaser]]''. In 1996, he starred in the comedy ''[[Kingpin (1996 film)|Kingpin]]'' for the Farrelly brothers.<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\nHarrelson's career gained momentum when he starred in the [[Milo\u0161 Forman]] film ''[[The People vs. Larry Flynt]]'', in which he played [[Larry Flynt]], publisher of ''[[Hustler]]'' magazine. The film was a success and Harrelson's performance was nominated for a Golden Globe Award and an Academy Award for Best Actor. After that, Harrelson was cast in more serious film roles. He starred in the 1997 war film ''[[Welcome to Sarajevo]]'' and in 1997 had a featured role as Sergeant Schumann in ''[[Wag the Dog]]''. In 1998, Harrelson starred in the thriller ''[[Palmetto (film)|Palmetto]]'' and played Sergeant Keck in ''[[The Thin Red Line (1998 film)|The Thin Red Line]]'', a war film nominated for seven [[Academy Award]]s in 1999.<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\nHarrelson made other films such as ''[[The Hi-Lo Country]]'' and portrayed Ray Pekurny in the comedy ''[[EDtv]]''. Also in 1999, he appeared as boxer Vince Boudreau in the [[Ron Shelton]] film ''[[Play It to the Bone]]''. Harrelson did not appear in films again until 2003, when he co-starred as Galaxia in the comedy film ''[[Anger Management (film)|Anger Management]]''.<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\nHe appeared in the action film ''[[After the Sunset]]'' and the Spike Lee film ''[[She Hate Me]]''. In 2005, Harrelson was in ''[[The Big White]]'' and ''[[North Country (film)|North Country]]''. Also in 2005 he appeared as Kelly Ryan, husband of a contest-obsessed woman in the film ''[[The Prize Winner of Defiance, Ohio]]''. Harrelson made two films in 2006, the animated film version of ''[[Free Jimmy]]'' and also ''[[A Scanner Darkly (film)|A Scanner Darkly]]''.\n\nIn 2007 he played Carter Page III, gay escort of privileged Washington D.C. women, in the film ''[[The Walker]]''.<ref name=\"imdb\" /> In the Oscar-winning 2007 crime thriller ''[[No Country for Old Men (film)|No Country for Old Men]]'', Harrelson had a key role as Carson Wells, a bounty hunter. The film won [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] and [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for [[Joel Coen]] and [[Ethan Coen]]. Harrelson also won a [[Screen Actors Guild Award]] for Best Cast, along with [[Tommy Lee Jones]], [[Javier Bardem]], [[Josh Brolin]], and [[Kelly Macdonald]].<ref name=\"imdb\"/> In 2007's ''[[Battle in Seattle]]'', Harrelson played another key role of a Seattle police officer whose pregnant wife loses her baby during the 1999 [[World Trade Organization]] protests.\n\nIn 2008, Harrelson appeared in several films, among them the [[Will Ferrell]] basketball comedy ''[[Semi-Pro]]'' and the stark [[Will Smith]] drama ''[[Seven Pounds]]'' as a blind vegan meat salesman named Ezra Turner.<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\n[[File:Woody Harrelson 2016.jpg|left|thumb|Harrelson at the [[LBJ Presidential Library]] in 2016]]\nIn 2009, Harrelson received significant praise for his performance as Captain Tony Stone in ''[[The Messenger (2009 film)|The Messenger]]''. In what many critics considered to be his best role, Harrelson was nominated for a [[Satellite Award]], an [[Independent Spirit Award]], a [[Golden Globe Award]], a [[Screen Actors Guild Award]], and an [[Academy Award]] for Best Supporting Actor. Harrelson has also [[National Board of Review Awards 2009#Winners|won the Best Supporting Actor award in the 2009 National Board of Review award ceremonies]] and received accolades from various critics' societies.<ref name=\"imdb\"/> Also that same year, Harrelson co-starred in the horror comedy ''[[Zombieland]]'', followed by [[Roland Emmerich]]'s ''[[2012 (film)|2012]],'' where he played Charlie Frost, a man who warns of the end of the world.\n\nIn 2010, he starred as a bartender and mentor in the futuristic western martial arts film ''[[Bunraku (film)|Bunraku]]''. In 2011, he starred as Tommy in the movie ''[[Friends with Benefits (film)|Friends with Benefits]]''. Harrelson directed the 2011 film ''ETHOS'', which explores the idea of a self-destructing modern society, governed by unequal power and failed democratic ideals. He played Haymitch Abernathy in 2012's ''[[The Hunger Games (film)|The Hunger Games]]'', and reprised the role in all three subsequent films in the series.<ref name=\"imdb\" />\nIn 2012, he had a leading role in ''Game Change'' as republican strategist Steve Schmidt.\n\nIn 2015, Woody Harrelson and daughter Zoe starred in a 7-minute short film for [[U2]]'s 'Song for Someone.'<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/6627282/-u2-song-for-someone-short-film-starring-woody-harrelson|title=Watch U2's 'Song for Someone' Short Film, Starring Woody Harrelson|work=Billboard|access-date=2017-03-30}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, he played the antagonist The Colonel in the science fiction film ''[[War for the Planet of the Apes]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/woody-harrelson-play-villain-new-823030|title=Woody Harrelson to Play Villain in New 'Planet of the Apes' Movie (Exclusive)|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=October 2, 2015}}</ref> Also that year, he starred in ''[[The Glass Castle (film)|The Glass Castle]],'' an adaptation of [[Jeannette Walls]]'s memoir about how she was raised by dysfunctional and nonconformist parents and then had her world turned upside down when they moved to New York to be near her. [[Brie Larson]] played Walls and Harrelson played her father. The comedic drama was directed by [[Destin Daniel Cretton]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/naomi-watts-talks-join-brie-878672|title=Naomi Watts in Talks to Join Brie Larson in Drama 'Glass Castle' (Exclusive)|website=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=March 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Harrelson announced that he would direct, write, produce, and star in a film, ''[[Lost in London]]'', which was shot as a single [[take]] and premiered live on January 19, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/article/2016/12/15/woody-harrelson-lost-in-london-interview/|title=Woody Harrelson Will Make History With World's First-Ever 'Live Cinema' Movie \u2013 Exclusive|date=December 15, 2016|publisher=|accessdate=January 20, 2017}}</ref> Harrelson played police chief Bill Willoughby in the black comedy crime film ''[[Three Billboards Outside Ebbing, Missouri]]'', released in 2017, for which he received [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]] and [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Supporting Role]] nominations.\n\nIn 2018, Harrelson starred opposite [[Alden Ehrenreich]], [[Donald Glover]], and [[Emilia Clarke]] in [[Lucasfilm]]'s ''[[Solo: A Star Wars Story]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=WOODY HARRELSON SIGNS ON FOR YOUNG HAN SOLO FILM|url=http://www.starwars.com/news/woody-harrelson-signs-on-for-young-han-solo-film|website=StarWars.com|accessdate=January 11, 2017}}</ref> playing [[Han Solo]]'s mentor<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|title=Woody Harrelson Eyed to Play Han Solo's Mentor in ''Star Wars'' Spinoff (EXCLUSIVE)|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/woody-harrelson-star-wars-han-solo-spinoff-1201943429/|website=Variety|accessdate=January 11, 2017}}</ref> and a criminal.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Prudom|first1=Laura|title=Woody Harrelson drops new hints about his role in the ''Star Wars'' Han Solo spinoff|url=http://mashable.com/2017/01/11/woody-harrelson-han-solo-movie-star-wars/#YbjB5QbYeqqF|website=Mashable.com|accessdate=January 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Harrelson appears in a cameo at the end of the film ''[[Venom (2018 film)|Venom]]'', portraying [[Cletus Kasady]].\n\nIn November 2019, he starred in [[Roland Emmerich]]\u2019s blockbuster movie  ''[[Midway (2019 film)|Midway]]'', playing Admiral Chester Nimitz. The film also starred [[Ed Skrein]], [[Patrick Wilson (American actor)|Patrick Wilson]], [[Luke Evans]], [[Aaron Eckhart]], [[Nick Jonas]], [[Dennis Quaid]] and [[Mandy Moore]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://variety.com/2019/film/features/roland-emmerich-midway-1203387268/ |title= Roland Emmerich Just Made a $100 Million Indie Film. Will It Work? |last=Donnelly|first=Matt|date=October 31, 2019|website= [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=October 31, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"May2017D\">{{cite news|last1=Fleming Jr|first1=Mike |title=Bona Film Group Stakes $80M On Roland Emmerich/Mark Gordon WWII Battle Pic 'Midway:' Cannes|url=http://deadline.com/2017/05/midway-roland-emmerich-bona-film-group-mark-gordon-1202101145/|accessdate=May 24, 2017|work=Deadline|date=May 23, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"May2018D\">{{cite news|last1=Wiseman|first1=Andreas|title=Roland Emmerich's WWII Epic 'Midway' Sets Sail With Woody Harrelson, Mandy Moore & AGC Studios \u2014 Cannes Hot Pic|url=http://deadline.com/2018/05/roland-emmerichs-wwii-epic-midway-sets-sail-with-woody-harrelson-mandy-moore-agc-studios-1202374631/|accessdate=May 4, 2018|work=Deadline|date=May 2, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"EvansCast\">{{cite news |last1=Kit |first1=Borys |title=Luke Evans Joins Roland Emmerich's Naval Action Movie 'Midway' (Exclusive) |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/luke-evans-joins-roland-emmerichs-naval-movie-midway-1124746 |accessdate=July 6, 2018 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=July 3, 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Cinematographer\">{{cite news |last1=Marc |first1=Christopher |title=Roland Emmerich's WWII Epic 'Midway' Adds 'The Guest' Cinematographer - GWW |url=https://thegww.com/roland-emmerichs-wwii-epic-midway-adds-the-guest-cinematographer/ |accessdate=July 24, 2018 |work=thegww.com |date=July 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=D'Alessandro |first1=Anthony |title=Roland Emmerich's WWII Epic 'Midway' To Open Veterans Day Weekend 2019 |url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/roland-emmerichs-wwii-epic-midway-to-open-veterans-day-weekend-2019-1202457811/ |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |work=Deadline |date=September 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Theatre===\nIn 1999, Harrelson directed his own play, ''Furthest from the Sun'', at the [[Theatre de la Jeune Lune]] in [[Minneapolis]]. He followed next in Roundabout's Broadway revival of the [[N. Richard Nash]] play ''The Rainmaker'' in 2000, [[Sam Shepard]]'s ''The Late Henry Moss'' in 2001, John Kolvenbach's ''On an Average Day'' opposite [[Kyle MacLachlan]] in London's West End in the fall of 2002, and in the summer of 2003, Harrelson directed the Toronto premiere of Kenneth Lonergan's ''This is Our Youth'' at the Berkley Street Theater.\n\nIn the winter of 2005-06 Harrelson returned to London's West End, starring in Tennessee Williams' ''Night of the Iguana'' at the [[Lyric Theatre (London)|Lyric Theater]]. Harrelson directed ''Bullet for Adolf'' (a play he wrote with Frankie Hyman) at the esteemed [[Hart House Theatre]] in [[Toronto]], Ontario, which ran from April 21 to May 7, 2011. ''Bullet for Adolf'' opened Off-Broadway (New World Stages) with previews beginning July 19, 2012 and closed on September 30, 2012, canceling its announced extension through October 21.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/05/theater/bullet-for-adolf-by-woody-harrelson-and-frankie-hyman.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|title=Two Friends Write a Play After Work |newspaper=The New York Times|date=August 2, 2012|first=Larry|last=Rohter|accessdate=January 4, 2015}}</ref> The play was panned by New York critics.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rao|first1=Mallika|title='Bullet For Adolf,' Woody Harrelson's Play, Panned By Critics Who Wonder If Real Marijuana Would Make It Funnier|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/bullet-for-adolf_n_1760254|accessdate=November 6, 2019|work=HuffPost|date=August 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1985, Harrelson married Nancy Simon (daughter of playwright [[Neil Simon]]) in [[Tijuana]]. The union was not intended to be serious, and the two had planned to divorce the following day, but the storefront marriage/divorce parlor was closed when they returned to it and they remained married for another ten months.<ref name=\"hollywood\">{{cite web|year=2007|url=http://www.hollywood.com/celebrity/Woody_Harrelson/196697|title=Woody Harrelson|publisher=hollywood.com|accessdate=September 9, 2007|quote=whimsically married in Tijuana in 1985 intending to divorce the following day, but when the couple returned to the storefront marriage/divorce parlor, they found it closed because it was Sunday; marriage lasted 10 months; Harrelson would later tell ''USA Today'', \"We had to get a summary dissolution through Jacoby and Meyers. I think at the time Neil was a little bit worried I might try to go after her money.\"}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Harrelson married Laura Louie, a co-founder of the organic food delivery service Yoganics.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/woody-harrelson-on-his-pursuit-of-happiness-off-the-hamster-wheel/article34404136/|title=Woody Harrelson on his pursuit of happiness 'off the hamster wheel'|access-date=2019-03-09}}</ref> They met in 1987 when she worked as his personal assistant.<ref name=\"yahoo\">{{cite web|year=2008|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/news/woody-harrelson-gets-married|title=Woody Harrelson Gets Married in Hawaii|work=[[Us Weekly]]|accessdate=December 30, 2008|quote=wife Laura Louie: born c. 1965; co-founded Yoganics, an organic food home delivery service in 1996|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081231035327/http://www.usmagazine.com/news/woody-harrelson-gets-married|archivedate=December 31, 2008}}</ref> They reside in [[Maui|Maui, Hawaii]], and have three daughters: Deni, Zoe, and Makani.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/global/2018/jan/07/woody-harrelson-i-used-to-have-my-head-up-my-ass- |title=Woody Harrelson: 'I used to have my head up my ass' |first=Martyn |last=Palmer|work=The Observer |date=January 7, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nHarrelson was awarded an honorary [[Doctor of Humane Letters]] (DHL) from [[Hanover College]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indystar.com/story/news/education/2014/04/02/woody-harrelson-receives-honorary-degree-hanover-college/7236229/|title=Woody Harrelson receives honorary degree at Hanover College|website=Indianapolis Star}}</ref>\n\nHarrelson is a fan of [[chess]]. He is considered an amateur player with a basic knowledge of the game. In November 2018, he attended the first game of the [[World Chess Championship 2018|World Chess Championship]] in London, played between Norwegian champion [[Magnus Carlsen]] and American contender [[Fabiano Caruana]]. Harrelson made the ceremonial first move for the game.<ref>Tyers, Alan. \"Woody Harrelson the unlikely star turn as chess stakes its claim as a spectator sport\". ''The Telegraph.'' 11 Nov 2018</ref> He had also played the ceremonial first move for the previous [[World Chess Championship 2016|World Chess Championship]] that was held in New York in 2016.<ref>Young, Zach. \"[https://www.huffpost.com/entry/even-the-world-chess-champion-cant-escape-the-spectre_b_582779ffe4b02b1f5257a350 Even The World Chess Champion Can't Escape The Spectre Of Donald Trump]\". ''HuffPost'' July 21, 2017.</ref>\n\n'''Criticism over 5G'''\n\nIn April 2020, Harrelson received criticism in the press regarding his public sharing a report \u201cabout the negative effects of 5G\u201d and its supposed role in the coronavirus pandemic to his more than 2 million Instagram followers. \u201cI haven\u2019t fully vetted it I find it very interesting,\u201d he wrote of the report claiming \u201c5G radiation\u201d is \u201cexacerbating\u201d the contagion\u2019s spread and making it more lethal.\n <ref>https://www.foxnews.com/us/woody-harrelson-among-stars-sharing-covid-19-conspiracy-theories-tied-to-5g</ref>\n\n==Legal issues==\nIn 1982, Harrelson was arrested for disorderly conduct in [[Columbus, Ohio]], after he was found dancing in the middle of the street.<ref name=\"celebritymugshots\">{{cite web|url=http://crime.about.com/od/famousdiduno/ig/celebrity_mugshots/harrelsonwoody.htm|title=Crime|publisher=About.com}}</ref> He was also charged with resisting arrest after he ran from the police.<ref name=\"celebritymugshots\"/> Harrelson avoided jail time by paying a fine.<ref>{{cite web|author=Time Waster|url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/mugshots/celebrity/hollywood/woody-harrelson|title=Woody Harrelson MUG SHOT |publisher=The Smoking Gun|accessdate=September 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn June 1, 1996, Harrelson was arrested in [[Lee County, Kentucky]], after he symbolically planted four hemp seeds to challenge the state law which did not distinguish between industrial hemp and marijuana. Harrelson had arrived in the county with his attorney, former Kentucky Governor [[Louie B. Nunn]], an agent and a camera crew from [[CNN]]. While at a local hotel, Harrelson phoned the county sheriff, Junior Kilburn, to advise him of his intentions. Kilburn and deputy sheriff Danny Towsend arrived at the location where Harrelson informed them he would be. With the cameras rolling, Harrelson planted the hemp seeds into the ground. Once planted, Kilburn placed Harrelson under arrest for cultivating marijuana and booked him into the county jail. He was released on $200 bail the same day. He later signed autographs and posed for photos with deputies. He was acquitted of those charges with the help of Nunn after just 25 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apps.courts.ky.gov/Supreme/SC_Opinions.shtm|title=Kentucky Supreme Court Opinions|publisher=Apps.courts.ky.gov|accessdate=September 30, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130919234531/http://apps.courts.ky.gov/supreme/sc_opinions.shtm|archivedate=September 19, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Harrelson was arrested in London after an incident in a taxi that ended in a police chase. Harrelson was taken to a London police station and later released on bail.<ref>{{cite news|title=Woody Harrelson arrested in London|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2030786.stm|work=BBC News|date=June 7, 2002}}</ref> The case was later dismissed after Harrelson paid the taxi driver involved in the incident \u00a3550 ($844).<ref>{{cite news|title=Harrelson taxi case dropped |date=July 1, 2002 |url=http://articles.cnn.com/2002-07-01/entertainment/police.harrelson_1_cab-driver-taxi-woody-harrelson?_s=PM:SHOWBIZ |work=CNN |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130307152743/http://articles.cnn.com/2002-07-01/entertainment/police.harrelson_1_cab-driver-taxi-woody-harrelson?_s=PM%3ASHOWBIZ |archivedate=March 7, 2013}}</ref> This became the inspiration for his 2017 live film, ''[[Lost in London]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://christiantimes.com/article/lost-in-london-movie-release-date-latest-news-woody-harrelson-stars-in-first-ever-live-streamed-movie/69818.htm|title='Lost in London' movie release date, latest news: Woody Harrelson stars in first-ever live streamed movie|publisher=|accessdate=January 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, [[TMZ (website)|TMZ]] photographer Josh Levine filed a lawsuit against Harrelson for an alleged attack outside a Hollywood nightclub in 2006. A video of the incident appeared to show Harrelson grabbing a camera and clashing with the photographer. Los Angeles prosecutors declined to press charges against the actor, but Levine filed a suit that summer asking for $2.5&nbsp;million in damages.<ref>{{cite news|title=Woody Harrelson claims he mistook photographer for zombie|date=April 10, 2009|author=Alan Duke, CNN|url=http://articles.cnn.com/2009-04-10/entertainment/woody.harrelson.zombie_1_woody-harrelson-camera-zombie?_s=PM:SHOWBIZ|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120118081952/http://articles.cnn.com/2009-04-10/entertainment/woody.harrelson.zombie_1_woody-harrelson-camera-zombie?_s=PM:SHOWBIZ|archivedate=January 18, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The case was dismissed in April 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Paparazzo's Lawsuit Against Actor Woody Harrelson Dismissed|date=April 17, 2010|url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/entertainment/celebrity/Paparazzo_s_Lawsuit_Against_Actor_Woody_Harrelson_Dismissed-91066694.html}}</ref>\n\n==Advocacy==\n[[Image:Woodyandme.jpg|thumb|Harrelson in 2004]]\n\n===Drug reform===\nHarrelson is an enthusiast and supporter for the legalization of [[cannabis (drug)|marijuana]] and [[hemp]].<ref name=\"name\">{{cite web|year=2007|url=http://www.e-stoned.com/rec/79-Woody-Harrelson|title=Woody Harrelson \u2013 Cannabis activist and personal freedom supporter|publisher=e-stoned.com|accessdate=September 9, 2007|quote=among other prominent activists opposed to marijuana prohibition. He has lent his celebrity status to the cause of reforming marijuana laws. Harrelson Backs Medical Pot Growers in California|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928083323/http://www.e-stoned.com/rec/79-Woody-Harrelson/|archivedate=September 28, 2007|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playboy.com/articles/playboy-interview-woody-harrelson/index.html?page=2|title=Playboy Interview: Woody Harrelson|accessdate=April 28, 2010|date=October 2009|work=Playboy|publisher=Playboy Enterprises, Inc.|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110427093616/http://www.playboy.com/articles/playboy-interview-woody-harrelson/index.html?page=2|archivedate=April 27, 2011}}</ref> He was a guest on [[Ziggy Marley]]'s track \"Wild and Free\", a song advocating the growing of cannabis. Since 2003, Harrelson has served as a member on [[NORML]]'s advisory board.<ref>{{cite web|title=NORML Advisory Board|url=http://www.norml.org/index.cfm?Group_ID=5471|date=August 25, 2009|publisher=[[NORML]]|accessdate=September 13, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Environmental===\nHarrelson has attended environmental events such as the PICNIC'07 festival that was held in [[Amsterdam]] in September 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/25/movies/25carr.html?ref=arts|work=The New York Times|first=David|last=Carr|title=Loves the Beach, the Planet and Movies|date=November 25, 2007}}</ref> PICNIC describes its annual festival as \"three intensive days [when] we mix creativity, science, technology, media, and business to explore new solutions in the spirit of co-creation\".<ref>[http://www.picnicnetwork.org/festival] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141103094806/http://www.picnicnetwork.org/festival|date=November 3, 2014}}</ref> He once scaled the [[Golden Gate Bridge]] with members of North Coast [[Earth First!]] group to unfurl a banner that read, \"Hurwitz, aren't ancient redwoods more precious than gold?\" in protest of Maxxam Inc. CEO [[Charles Hurwitz]], who once stated, \"He who has the gold, makes the rules.\"<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|year=2007 |url = http://www.northcoastearthfirst.org/|title = No Compromise in Defense of Mother Earth! Earth First|publisher = northcoastearthfirst| accessdate =September 9, 2007 |quote=With the help of actor Woody Harrelson, a group of NCEF! activists hung a huge banner from the Golden Gate Bridge in San Francisco, which said, \"Charles Hurwitz, Aren't Ancient Redwoods More Precious Than Gold?\"}}</ref>\n\nHarrelson once traveled to the west coast in the U.S. on a bike and a domino caravan with a hemp oil-fueled [[biodiesel]] bus with the Spitfire Agency (the subject of the independent documentary ''[[Go Further]]'') and narrated the 1999 documentary [[Grass (1999 film)|''Grass'']]. He briefly owned an [[oxygen bar]] in [[West Hollywood, California|West Hollywood]] called \"O2\".{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1997-05-17/news/mn-59768_1_oxygen-bar|title=Room to Breathe : Oxygen Bars Would Serve Customers a Shot of Clean Air|last=ZAMICHOW|first=NORA|date=1997-05-17|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2018-05-20|last2=SAYLOR|first2=MARK|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref>\n\nHarrelson has spoken publicly against the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]] as well as previously protesting against the [[First Gulf War]], both at [[UCLA]] as well as during a college concert tour in Iowa and Nebraska in 1991 under the auspices of \"Woody Harrelson Educational Tours\". In October 2009, he was given an honorary degree by [[York University]] for his contributions in the fields of environmental education, sustainability, and activism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yorku.ca/secretariat/senate/committees/hondeg/recipients.html#H|title=Honorary Degree Recipients - Honorary Degrees & Ceremonials SubCommittee|publisher=Yorku.ca|accessdate=September 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Veganism===\nHarrelson follows a [[Raw veganism|raw vegan]] diet.<ref name=\"esquire\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.esquire.com/features/woody-harrelson-profile-0212 |title=Who Doesn't Love Woody Harrelson? |accessdate=July 7, 2012 |magazine=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.eatveg.com/woody.htm |title=Woody Harrelson on the seeds of spirituality and a change in his diet |accessdate=July 7, 2012 |magazine=[[Premiere (magazine)|Premiere]] }}</ref> Along with not eating meat or dairy, Harrelson also does not eat sugar or flour.<ref name=\"esquire\"/> In ''[[Zombieland]]'', in which he plays a character with an affinity for [[Twinkies]], the Twinkies were replaced with vegan faux-Twinkies made from [[cornmeal]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://readingeagle.com/article.aspx?id=159981 |title=Woody Harrelson: A vegetarian among carnivores |accessdate=July 7, 2012 |publisher=Reading Eagle Press }}</ref> He appeared on a postage stamp (as a PhotoStamp) in 2011 as one of [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA]]'s 20 famous vegetarians,<ref>Bill Hutchinson,\"[http://articles.nydailynews.com/2011-11-28/news/30448367_1_postage-stamps-stamp-honorees-animal-abuse First-Class Stars' Meat-Free Pitch],\" NYDailyNews.com November 28, 2011.</ref> and he was named PETA's Sexiest Vegetarian in 2012 (along with [[Jessica Chastain]]).<ref name=\"eonline\">[http://www.eonline.com/news/marc_malkin/jessica_chastain_woody_harrelson_named/326529 Jessica Chastain and Woody Harrelson Named PETA's 2012 Sexiest Vegetarians], EOnline.com; accessed February 27, 2016.</ref>\n\n===UNICEF===\nIn June 2010, Harrelson took part in [[Soccer Aid]] at [[Old Trafford]] in Manchester to raise money for [[UNICEF]]. He played for the Rest of the World team alongside former professionals [[Zinedine Zidane]] and [[Lu\u00eds Figo]] as well as chef [[Gordon Ramsay]] and fellow Hollywood actors [[Mike Myers]] and [[Michael Sheen]].<ref name=\"MTV\"/> Harrelson played the last 15 minutes and scored the winning goal in the penalty shootout following a 2\u20132 draw during normal time.<ref name=\"MTV\">[http://www.mtv.co.uk/soccer-aid-2010/news/england-beaten-at-soccer-aid \"England Beaten at Soccer Aid\"]. MTV. Retrieved August 25, 2016</ref> He played in the UNICEF game 2012, playing the last 10 minutes of the game for the Rest of the World team, losing 3\u20131 to England.\n\n===Political views===\nHarrelson identifies as an [[anarchist]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Woody Harrelson: I'm an anarchist|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/click/2013/05/woody-harrelson-im-an-anarchist-165139.html|first=Caitlin |last=McDevitt|work=[[Politico]]|date=May 31, 2013|accessdate=June 1, 2013}}</ref> In a conversation with [[Howard Zinn]], Harrelson admitted that he considers Zinn to be a personal hero of his.<ref>{{cite news|title=A Conversation: Howard Zinn and Woody Harrelson|url=http://howardzinn.org/conversation-howard-zinn-woody-harrelson/|work=[[Deep Dish TV]]|date= January 19, 2017|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref> In 2002, Harrelson wrote an article in the British newspaper ''[[The Guardian]]'' condemning President [[George W. Bush]]'s preparation for a [[Iraq War|US invasion of Iraq]] as a \"racist and imperialist war\". He also stated that he was against the U.S.'s previous [[Gulf War|war in Iraq]] and President [[Bill Clinton]]'s [[sanctions against Iraq]].<ref>{{cite news|title=I'm an American tired of American lies|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2002/oct/17/theatre.artsfeatures|first=Woody |last=Harrelson|work=Guardian|date=October 17, 2002|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Religious views===\nHarrelson told ''[[Playboy]]'' in October 2009, \"I was getting into theology and studying the roots of the Bible, but then I started to discover the man-made nature of it. I started seeing things that made me ask, 'Is God really speaking through this instrument?' My eyes opened to the reality of the Bible being just a document to control people. At the time I was a real mama's boy and deeply mesmerized by the church.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Interview|date=October 2009|journal=[[Playboy]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.worldreligionnews.com/entertainment/celebrity/actor-woody-harrelsons-unique-view-religion|title=Actor Woody Harrelson's Unique View of Religion - World Religion News|date=2018-05-19|work=World Religion News|access-date=2018-08-29|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn a May 2018 interview with [[Jimmy Kimmel]],<ref name=kimmel /> Harrelson mentioned his study of theology and that he had considered becoming a minister. He explained that he became disillusioned with the church during his studies at college: \"I started to see how man-made the Bible was and then I started saying, 'I could put this whole thing on hold for a while...let's just put this whole idea on hold so I can have my twenties and thirties of extreme hedonism.'\" He stated that he currently has a belief in God, which he attributed to reading ''[[Autobiography of a Yogi]]'' by [[Paramahansa Yogananda]], whom he described as a \"man of integrity\".\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n<!-- Please note: do NOT use \"rowspans\" per WP:FILMOGRAPHY -->\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[Harper Valley PTA (film)|Harper Valley PTA]]''\n| Extra\n| Uncredited<ref>{{cite web|last1=White|first1=James|title=In Praise of Woody Harrelson|url=http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/woody-harrelson/|website=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|accessdate=September 23, 2017|date=June 13, 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Wildcats (film)|Wildcats]]''\n| Krushinski\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[She's Having a Baby]]''\n| Himself\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Cool Blue]]''\n| Dustin\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 1991\n| ''[[L.A. Story]]''\n| Harris' Boss\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| ''[[Doc Hollywood]]''\n| Hank Gordon\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Ted & Venus]]''\n| Homeless Vietnam Veteran\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[White Men Can't Jump]]''\n| Billy Hoyle\n|\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Indecent Proposal]]''\n| David Murphy\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 1994\n| ''[[Natural Born Killers]]''\n| Mickey Knox\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Cowboy Way (film)|The Cowboy Way]]''\n| Pepper Lewis\n|\n|-\n| ''[[I'll Do Anything]]''\n| Ground Zero Hero\n|\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Money Train]]''\n| Charlie Robinson\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 1996\